('100064036', NULL, 'users/117552848/jonathan-311', 'It seems to me the question of whether the correlation is +ve or -ve is pointless.', '05 Jun ''13, 12:36', '100062086'),
('100064043', NULL, 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'Great point Naomi. Anytime there is opportunity for the researcher to choose something (like who goes into what group) there is a chance that the researcher will introduce bias.', '05 Jun ''13, 12:40', '100063639'),
('100064051', NULL, 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'I know what you''re saying. It seems like the important things are 1) IF two variables are correlated, and 2)how strong that correlation is. The + vs - part seems like it might be an obvious distinction. \n\nBut I find that in casual conversation, having the terms "positively correlated" and "negatively correlated" is actually really useful. I can say something like "Did you know that sometimes, there is actually a POSITIVE correlation between stress and performance?! I would have thought stress always hurts performance, but sometimes it actually helps!"', '05 Jun ''13, 12:49', '100062086'),
('100064082', NULL, 'users/117552848/jonathan-311', 'The number of significant figures you are using should be based on the accuracy of the timer used in the the experiment. So if the timer is accurate to 3 significant figures it is wrong to quote the mean to 4 significant figures.', '05 Jun ''13, 13:32', '100064030'),
('100064083', NULL, 'users/100115570/jeff-diamond', 'Understood.  I recognize my error. I was trying to solve the case instead of classifying the example. Thank you.', '05 Jun ''13, 13:33', '100063602'),
('100064091', NULL, 'users/117552848/jonathan-311', 'Okay, I agree that it is  a useful phrase to use when trying not to overlook something.\nIn the case you show there is definite correlation.\nFor the example shown in the video in question surely it is better to state that there is no correlation. If there is no rigour and you say there is weak correlation in all your graphs, this leads on to bad science and you will end up being misquoted.', '05 Jun ''13, 13:45', '100064056'),
('100064113', NULL, 'users/117552848/jonathan-311', 'I agree with you, it is just that the question stated "As people drink more and more alcohol, their coordination gets worse and worse." From this surely there are two correct statements. As was stated there was a negative correlation, but also from the statement you know that it is strong.\nIs there a precedence between which one of these is usually stated first?', '05 Jun ''13, 14:13', '100062086'),
('100064119', NULL, 'users/117552848/jonathan-311', 'So if you were unlucky and your random assignment got skewed, is then your best choice to repeat this random assignment?', '05 Jun ''13, 14:19', '100063639'),
('100064125', NULL, 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'I don''t think so. If we keep re-randomizing until we get an assignment we like, we aren''t being random anymore.', '05 Jun ''13, 14:21', '100063639'),
('100064130', NULL, 'users/117552848/jonathan-311', 'But like you said you might bias the two groups by intervening.', '05 Jun ''13, 14:25', '100063639'),
('100064232', '100062184', 'users/100053416/francis-geist', 'I was wondering why they use the term "shy" because I am not shy and I have introverted tendencies.. it''s not shyness at all.  I talk to people when I need to but I rather keep away from people because people have different views and it''s hard to talk to them', '05 Jun ''13, 16:05', NULL),
('100064236', NULL, 'users/100053416/francis-geist', 'I just think people use words very loosely  these days.. I   am an introvert and I am definitely NOT shy. I think being shy and being an introvert are two different personality traits. one thing can''t justify the other, but again this  is probably how people have correlated introversion and hence why people have come to understand it that way..  The instructors probably know that and use the term "shy"  in association to introverts because  of that.  (because people have learned it that way, so I can assume it''s how it''s learned, but I must insist, I don''t agree with an introverted individual being shy) if you are shy, you are probably shy for other reasons because I am an introvert and I am not shy.', '05 Jun ''13, 16:08', '100063573'),
('100064338', '100064098', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'In this question, the term "practice" is referring to a psychologist who is treating patients, helping them to overcome or deal with their issues.', '05 Jun ''13, 18:08', NULL),
