('100064405', NULL, 'users/100053416/francis-geist', 'But Where are these correlations coming from? - who started the trend, and are people really that messed up? - could  this be social conditioning? , please someone answer me. ( because I am highly introverted and I am not shy, I can talk to people normally, but I prefer to keep my distance)', '05 Jun ''13, 19:29', '100064297'),
('100064408', '100063484', 'users/100053416/francis-geist', 'oh okay because I can do it , I just don''t know how  I am doing it.. it''s like picking  left and right and I go to the negative side but don''t really understand the whole dots', '05 Jun ''13, 19:36', NULL),
('100064415', '100063484', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'The dots are just the data points.  The line is what we call a "best fit line" and it is the line that best fits the data.  The "best fit line" in the example indicates that as the data values on the x-axis increase, the data values on the y-axis decrease.  Which is why it is a negative correlation.', '05 Jun ''13, 19:48', NULL),
('100064421', NULL, 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'That''s an interesting thought.  Most people I know that I would consider extroverted are not what would one would think of as "bookish".  However, I have certainly found that more than a few of the introverted people I have met in my life have been...more into reading, I guess.  Among just the people on my facebook friends list, I find that I can only think of one "extrovert" that stands out as being....bookish.  Although, I suppose it would depend on how you define bookish.  The person I am thinking of enjoys reading mainly books that fall under his field of study (ancient roman history).  I don''t think I''ve ever heard him talk about any other of sub-genre of literature.  So is he bookish?', '05 Jun ''13, 19:56', '100064221'),
('100064428', NULL, 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'Francis, I''m thinking that based on the correlation Feist talks about, you might be considered an anomaly.  But then, as I said, I generally choose not to socialize because I find that it takes a lot of effort.  I don''t think of myself as a people person, but I also have a job that often requires a lot of time spent around customers.  Sometimes, I just find myself striking up conversations with them because I''m bored.  I''ve noticed that a lot of instances where I find myself exhibiting what I think of as shy behavior (a reluctance to socialize with someone for a reason), it''s often out of intimidation.  But isn''t that relatively common, I wonder?  I''m just rambling and speculating here.  Any thoughts would be appreciated.  I often have trouble getting my ideas across coherently.', '05 Jun ''13, 20:07', '100064297'),
('100064439', NULL, 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'It''s funny that you mention the improvement, Andy.  I tried out the test for myself, and I did notice an improvement in my reaction time as I took the test.  So, I also wondered, how many times were the participants asked to take the test...  We were given an average score for each group, but I found myself wondering if the test scores displayed for each person were their individual averages.  We weren''t told, and I didn''t know.', '05 Jun ''13, 20:20', '100064041'),
('100064441', NULL, 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'You''re very welcome.', '05 Jun ''13, 20:22', '100063602'),
