('100064831', '100061827', 'users/117771440/darlene-4', 'Hi, I am Darlene.  I have always had an interest in psychology and thought that I should have been a psychologist of sorts.  People tend to confide in me and I seem to find myself in situations where I am dishing out advice.   I find it a very fascinating and diverse field of study.  I am interested in knowing what makes people tick.  It may also help me to understand myself better.', '06 Jun ''13, 07:47', NULL),
('100064965', NULL, 'users/116393908/lucas-87', 'First of all its very important to have a clear definition of what we are talking about. I will try to define how i see shyness and introversion are, if it is wrong please someone let me know.\n\nShyness: Shy people usually avoid social interactions because they feel uncomfortable in this kind of situations. It doesnt mean this kind of person dont want to interact with others, actually they usually want to but their fear of judgment and the fear of others reactions make it difficult to them.\n\nIntroversion: This person usually choose/prefer not to interact with others just because to them individual activities or even social activities that depends more of individual thinking are more beneficial. For example, if they need to interact they will, while shy people may run away/void to interact even it is necessary and they want to.\n\nSometimes i see people talking about introvert as a person who burn/lost energy while involved in social interactions while extrovert recovery/gain energy from it. I am not really sure how accurately this definition is although i think it really makes sense.', '06 Jun ''13, 12:24', '100064297'),
('100064973', NULL, 'users/117592144/lour', 'Hi Dear, I''ve studied Psycholinguistics as well when I was at college. It is a very interesting field. Which subfield interests you more? I was fond of "language adquisition" and "Languages pathologies"', '06 Jun ''13, 12:31', '100064941'),
('100064982', NULL, 'users/116393908/lucas-87', 'As people who are introvert usually spend less time in social activities some of them can fail to develop the social skills needed to fully enjoy and get benefit from social interactions. This can make them start feeling insecure and develop some shyness behaviour. So I guess we can find a higher number of shy people among the introverts. Is this enough to say there is correlation ? \nIn most of time I identify myself "introvert" but I known parts of what I call an introvert behavior maybe are more related to indifference, unawareness or insecurity. The same way there are some behaviours I used to think were provoked by shyness but are not.\nI hope I am not being too simplistic neither misunderstanding basic concepts.', '06 Jun ''13, 12:47', '100064297'),
('100064983', NULL, 'users/117592144/lour', 'I know how you feel. I guess you were expecting some definitions of what psychology is as well as the subfields. Maybe we''ll see them through the course and if not, as far as I''m concern we still need to know some other aspects before we see the subfields.', '06 Jun ''13, 12:48', '100064483'),
('100065052', NULL, 'users/100053416/francis-geist', 'Basically what I believe is that people who are introverted do lack social skills which I find to be true in my case but again I think that''s were the correlation comes from despite not being shy at all. I don''t recognize them as "shyness behavior" as it would be insensitive to say someone shy is introverted or someone introverted is shy .. take the short definition for Shy:  "Being reserved or having or showing nervousness or timidity in the company of other people". and  the word Introvert: " person predominantly concerned with their own thoughts and feelings rather than with external things".  There is a certain "similarity" that breeds that misconception between people (hence the correlation), but being shy and being introverted are two complete different subjects .. . \n\nIn my case, introversion doesn''t cause shyness in the very same way shyness doesn''t cause introvertio, introversion it''s more of a choice, or lifestyle  of the individual (if you can call it that way) above anything else. A shy person actually feels anxiety and nervousness around other people  . An introverted person''s  lack of social skills can  often be viewed as  "shyness".  . But it''s bound to happen in society, beliefs are proliferated, especially in a society that feeds on competition, acquisition, money and all that.', '06 Jun ''13, 14:20', '100064297'),
('100065089', NULL, 'users/118069137/brian-388', '"0ur schools ... are designed mostly for extroverts"  NOT! In my experience, schools reward well behaved students who follow the rules, do what they''re told, and don''t question authority. Cain obviously has a horse in the race, but that sounds more like introversion to me.', '06 Jun ''13, 15:03', '100064154'),
