('100065300', '100065293', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question! Researchers may have RA''s (Research assistants) that can help with everything from forming the groups to running the experiments.', '06 Jun ''13, 19:36', NULL),
('100065301', NULL, 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Correlational studies are sometimes used for many reasons.  Often they are used to see if something is worth running an experiment.  Other times they are used when it is not ethical to run an experiment.  For example, if you wanted to find out if releasing convicted murders was related to an increase in crime.  It would be unethical (and probably not possible) to release convicted murders just for an experiment, but we could look at previous instances and come up with a correlation.', '06 Jun ''13, 19:41', '100065204'),
('100065303', '100065293', 'users/100053416/francis-geist', 'I see,   but then the question would be....  How does a researcher determines how accurate or reliable the information gathered from the RA''s?', '06 Jun ''13, 19:47', NULL),
('100065312', '100065293', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'RA''s may apply to work to do research for someone, or they may be chosen, much like a job.  Much like the manager of a bank would trust the employees to not steal or act unethical, a researcher trusts the RA''s in the same way.  A big part of reliability in the psychological study world, is replication.  Experiments are replicated many times by different researchers and their teams to ensure that the findings of studies are accurate.  This is why in published psychological articles, much information is included that pertains to the methodology, analysis, and results of the experiment.', '06 Jun ''13, 19:56', NULL),
('100065319', '100065170', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Awesome questions! I think that people often mistakenly think that they are either introverts or extroverts.  In reality, its is more accurate to think of the personality trait as a a spectrum, with introvert being on one side and extrovert being on the other.  People actually fall somewhere in between the two  rather than completely being one or the other.  Just because a person may be slightly more introverted does not mean they don''t do things that are characteristics of introverts, and vise versa. There are many different measures of personality characteristics, one being the Big Five Personality test, which measures people on 5 personality traits; Openness, Conscientiousness, Extroversion, Agreeableness, and Neuroticism.', '06 Jun ''13, 20:10', NULL),
('100065323', NULL, 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Whichever answer you have entered before the due dates are the ones that will be graded.  You can do the problem set questions as many times as you like, just be sure to have your final answers entered before the due date.', '06 Jun ''13, 20:16', '100063151'),
('100065329', '100065041', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'The next lessons will be available next week.', '06 Jun ''13, 20:23', NULL),
('100065346', NULL, 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'The questions are designed to help you learn that there are many different perspectives that psychologists come from.  Say a person is depressed, a cognitive psychologists will want to know whats going on with their mental processes, a behavioral psychologist will want to know what experiences may have occurred in the persons life that may have reinforced depressed behavior, and a biological psychologist may want to know what is going on with the persons chemical balances.  There may be many different approaches that help understand and solve the issue, which is why there are many different areas of psychology!  Hope that helps!', '06 Jun ''13, 20:38', '100065072'),
('100065352', NULL, 'users/117276885/sandhyaa', 'Thanks Steven.', '06 Jun ''13, 20:47', '100065072'),
('100065364', '100065293', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'I failed to mention that there are a variety of ways that a researcher can randomly assign participants to groups other than through the use of RA''s.  There are methods that allow researchers themselves to randomly assign participants, say for instance, assigning the participants numbers and randomly assigning them to groups, or even having a third party randomize.', '06 Jun ''13, 21:17', NULL),
('100065365', NULL, 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'No problem! I love all of the discussion posts and am very happy to see you engaged in the material!', '06 Jun ''13, 21:18', '100065072'),
('100065376', '100065339', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question! It is possible that each one of these professionals will be able to help equally well! Or maybe even all of them working together!  There may be many different ways to solve the same problem, so there really is not an "ultimate" perspective here.  Hope that helps!', '06 Jun ''13, 21:40', NULL),
('100065428', '100064960', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question! Thats kind of the reason psychologists use random assignment.  The thought is that through random assignment and a large sample size, all of the different attributes of people (e.g. being more accustomed to computers) will even out.  Hope that helps!', '06 Jun ''13, 23:16', NULL),
