('100066534', '100064960', 'users/100062192/nathan-jervis', 'It''s the same with any test they could enforce, which is why random sample sizes and a large sample are sought out. I worked at a research centre that had some studies use hundreds of thousands of participants to try to remove any bias in the groups.', '08 Jun ''13, 15:51', NULL),
('100066538', NULL, 'users/100062192/nathan-jervis', '@Tobias Actually in a scenario like organ transplants there are multiple tests done, and the improvement/reduction is what is measured. For instance they could evaluate the patients health, then either do the transplant or not do it, then measure the health again (and probably again several times over the course of the next few years). Administering the treatment (caffeine or transplant) only needs to be done once, but measurements can be done several times, and in the best studies are done very frequently. Ideally the researchers would measure baseline reaction, administer the coffee, then measure reaction times something like once every 5 minutes for the next hour (so that they could make sure that they measure everyone''s peak time after they have the coffee, as caffeine may be absorbed into the system at different rates).', '08 Jun ''13, 15:58', '100065037'),
('100066605', NULL, 'users/100042256/tobias-kuster', '@Nathan You are right; however, you misunderstood my organ-transplant example to some extent. I did not mean that tests are done, then organs are transplanted, then the test is repeated, but that the transplantation itself is the test. Say you are testing a medicine to improve... well, whatever is to be improved with organ transplants. You can not transplant some organ without the medicine, and then transplant the organ again, on the same person, with the medicine. Still, you are absolutely right that -- whenever possible -- more tests are better. :-)', '08 Jun ''13, 17:46', '100065037'),
