('100068061', NULL, 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'It''s a good question. A lot of science goes in to determining whether an allele is dominant or recessive. In the case of eye color here is a real report from 1996 discussing the dominance of brown eye pigmentation: \n\nhttp://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8875191\n\nAll alleles have to be looked at individually to see how and why they might be dominant or recessive. It turns out that technically eye color isn''t quite as simple as this:\n\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eye_color#Genetic_determination\n\nSee the next exercise for another brief explanation. We just used eye color as an example in this case because the appearance is easy to interpret. Remember though, there are more kinds of dominance, but this lesson only covers dominant and recessive.', '11 Jun ''13, 01:15', '100068047');
INSERT INTO `comentarios` (`idComment`, `idPost`, `idUser`, `textComment`, `dateComment`, `idAnswer`) VALUES
('100068064', NULL, 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'It turns out that eye color is more complicated than just a single gene.\n\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eye_color#Genetic_determination\n\nBut in general brown is dominant because of the way pigmentation works. It is possible for alleles involved in other traits (like blood type) to be co-dominant. There are other forms of dominance but this lesson only covers one kind.\n\nIn a couple of months there will be a new Udacity course on genetics and genomics that will answer this question in more detail.', '11 Jun ''13, 01:17', '100068058'),
