('100071296', NULL, 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'You both are making really good points! Julien, remember, artificial selection has the same ''evolving'' effect that natural selection does. The word "evolution" itself doesn''t describe a direction other than one that fits the selection pressures, whether artificial or natural. As you both point out, there are aspects of human evolution that are artificial but still plenty of natural ones too. For example, infectious disease is one majore way that we''re still affected. Although we have vaccines against smallpox and other detrimental diseases, others still plague us. For example the flu and HIV are two different viruses that kill people who can''t survive them. Our gene pool has responded accordingly, and in northern europe there are alleles of genes (the CCR5 gene) that make people resistant to HIV (and also the bubonic plague). Though it''s a trade-off (as all alleles usually are) and that same allele makes one more susceptible to west nile virus.\n\nThe main point is that both natural and artificial selection are evolution; humans are subject to both.', '15 Jun ''13, 19:35', '100071227'),
