('100071415', NULL, 'users/100012341/jeff-scott', 'Might be interesting also to ask what areas of human activity or behavior that psychology can answer accurately and usefully, with validity outside of the set of 18-22 age undergraduate american college students who are the subjects of the vast majority of studies, nearly all which are done with very small sample sets. Does any of the various universal claims of psychology apply to Masai tribesmen of africa? Has it been so tested.\n\nWhen I took psychology courses much was made of the phenomenon of "wilding", where humans (black teens actually) would get together in packs like wolves and attack innocent white women, all based on the Central Park Jogger case. This, and input from psychologists about the dynamics of this, created a moral panic and much racism towards and perceived need to control and limit the freedom of minority teens.\n\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Park_Jogger_case\n\nWhen it was found that the kids were all tortured by forensic psychologists into false confessions and the rape was committed by one adult acting alone, psychology textbooks merely dropped that chapter rather than admitting to the long history of failures and intense damage to society and people that the field has caused, with no failures ever admitted, but instead buried and whitewashed.\n\nSeveral classes I took discussed the danger of black teen "wilding", where humans loose their humanity in "packs", emphasizing through the word "packs" and the psychological theory pushed how minority youth are animal like and barely human. Never is the parallel phenomenon discussed where adult white soldiers, working under orders, and with the approval of their culture, commit violent war atrocities such as in Iraq and Afghanistan discussed. Instead it is always young black teens that must be discussed, in a single case that never happened.\n\nHere in this class we are already talking about the case where a bunch of people didn''t do anything when a women was raped and killed. It''s this same one case that is always discussed over and over. If this was really a truth or principle of human behavior don''t you think that after 40 years there would be a second example?', '15 Jun ''13, 23:56', '100066346'),
