('100077226', NULL, 'users/120191717/andre-luiz-1', 'I couldn''t agree more. But the point is, under the control of a strong emotion, will a person remember those words? When we are caught by strong emotion, we can hardly think. Have you seen or experienced something like that before?\nWe don''t need big things to make us lose control of our emotion. We are constantly being pressured in our everyday life. So, one small thing can work just as a trigger for an emotional outburst, that could be avoid under other circumstance.', '24 Jun ''13, 10:58', '100076615'),
('100077233', NULL, 'users/120191717/andre-luiz-1', 'Youre absolutely right. We can''t avoid going through all the stages, but the strength and the duration of each stage vary from person to person depending on a variety of circumstances. \nWe can''t forget we talking about emotions. Although emotions are what give colors to life and make it rich and fascinating, they are also what makes life challenging and difficult at times.\nThe pain may be inevitable, but the suffering is optional? Is it taking longer that it should be? Is it somehow causing problem in your life, or to the people around you?', '24 Jun ''13, 11:14', '100076764'),
('100077236', NULL, 'users/120191717/andre-luiz-1', 'We are talking about one of the most difficult challenge one can face in life, and that is, the death of a loved one. As you said, some situation (i.e. what happened to your wife) may seem strange, but it is not uncommon, it happens all the time. The fact is that we can''t predict how someone will react under the control of a strong emotion (strong for the person and maybe not for us).\nYou can have an idea of how you would react under a certain situation. You know yourself better than anyone else. But don''t forget we are talking about strong emotion (hard to deal with), and the death of a loved one may bring your emotion to the top, in its strongest level. At this point, you will hardly be thinking reasonably and how you would expect to see yourself acting reasonably?', '24 Jun ''13, 11:19', '100077083'),
('100077240', NULL, 'users/120191717/andre-luiz-1', 'Youre absolutely right. We can''t avoid going through all the stages, but the strength and the duration of each stage vary from person to person depending on a variety of circumstances. \nWe can''t forget we talking about emotions. Although emotions are what give colors to life and make it rich and fascinating, they are also what makes life challenging and difficult at times.\nTo handle emotions is not that simple. It is easy to think that you know how to handle your emotions when you are in a controlled situation, that is, you are not involved emotionally. Most of the time what we can see (and this happens when we are observing others) is the emotions controlling the person). \nThe fact is that the death of a loved one brings emotions to the top, and when this happens people are not supposed to think reasonably. We are not taught how to handle them. The only advise we got is: \n1- Express you emotions (crying like a child), or \n2- Suppress your emotions (Don''t feel it, or be strong and hold your emotions in)\nwhatever you choose to express your strong emotions when you are in public, not all options are available.', '24 Jun ''13, 11:22', '100077112'),
