('100080478', NULL, 'users/100042668/jason-smith-6', '"Macro evolution" isn''t distinct from evolution, it''s part of it, and has been observed in nature since Darwin published The Origin of Species. In addition, there is a vast amount of evidence for macro-evolution from before then, such as the fossil record and differences in DNA. Note the evolution is accepted fact by the vast majority of scientists - "Project Steve" showed that there are more scientists named "Steve" who accept evolution as fact than all scientists (regardless of name) who support Intelligent Design.\n\nScience is based on inferences and leaps of logic - nobody has ever directly seen an atom, or directly observed gravity. They are the simplest falsifiable inferences we have made from the evidence. Similarly, the theory of evolution is the simplest falsifiable inference we have made for the copious evidence for evolution.', '29 Jun ''13, 16:17', '100079162'),
('100080514', NULL, 'users/120686583/chadwick-4', 'Evolution theory is large and multi-disciplinary. There is distinction between micro-evolution and macro-evolution (one is the difference within species and the other is the difference between species). Evolution is "change" and change is a description of many facts. So, Evolution is not a fact, it is a body of knowledge. If I fall, it hurts. If I throw something it tends to land. These are facts and measured. Then those facts are put together to describe the shared behavior, which we call gravity. Gravitational Theory is large and contains a number of facts, but also a number of things that are conditional on whether new evidence will change the understanding. Evolution Theory has many facts and a number of assertions are conditional on whether new evidence will change the understanding.\n\nUnfortunately, any discussion of evolution leads to the cultural dichotomy of Evolution vs Intelligent Design. This is a false dichotomy. If quantum physics and technology give us better understanding of how the smallest elements of energy work within a framework to create new substances or change existing substances, the mechanism will include observable facts and then the facts will create a set of beliefs about what those facts means. People will have interests for control and certainty and will rely on different constructs. Some find comfort in a godless world based on impersonal rules of chemistry and some find comfort in a personal hand behind the mechanisms. Neither of these can be proven with science, only interpreted by people. Stronger personalities will try to persuade others and solitify their certainty.\n\nI try not to get bogged down in the rhetoric as much as remind myself that science is always under pressure to find solutions to problems and eventually a paradigm shift occurs and the whole understanding changes. Being humble means understanding history and knowing that where we are now is not the end of where things are going. Neither is science the answer to meaning in our lives. We still have to choose for ourselves how we will live in the time we have. We will always teeter between certainty and uncertainty in everything we do. Psychology will probably look at this, but it is within Systems Theory, so probably more sociology, though I am looking for it in this class. :) (Sorry this is so long and cheers!)', '29 Jun ''13, 17:40', '100079162'),
