('100101985', NULL, 'users/100119986/anthony-21', '@jamie-77 : You touched upon a point regarding therapy (talk therapy I assume) not being covered by insurance.\nHere are two interesting articles that expand upon the topic and the ease at which psychiatrists dole out prescriptions - including one from the APA.\n\nhttp://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/06/health/policy/06doctors.html?pagewanted=all&amp;_r=0\n\nhttp://www.apa.org/monitor/2012/06/prescribing.aspx\n\nIn spite of the lack of coverage for talk therapy, I simply can''t help but think there is a conflict of interest at play when it comes to prescribing drugs.  This part is most troubling to me because the therapy being administered becomes less genuine unbeknownst to the patients.\n\nThe monetary incentive to see someone for a short period of time (15-20min), hold steady/increase/decrease/refill a prescription seems like it would be more profitable than to conduct talk therapy for one person.  \n\nIn the time it takes to conduct one talk therapy session, the same psychiatrist can see three to four different people.  From the NYT article: " A psychiatrist can earn $150 for three 15-minute medication visits compared with $90 for a 45-minute talk therapy session."\n\nAlso from the NYT article is the disturbing statistic from a government survey that states that only 11% (and declining) of psychiatrists provide talk therapy to all patients.\n\nAs you stated, "A trained psychologist should know to take many factors and context into account when making a diagnosis such as home life, social life, or classroom."  I completely agree.  However, the I feel as though the rater (the trained psychiatrist) reliability becomes poor when he or she cannot ( for lack of coverage on behalf of the patients insurance provider, or even conflict of interest ) form a sound judgement about a personality or dysfunction to personality without extended time spent with a patient.\n\nAs for the 20 internet tabs, texting, ipod stuff, I have to disagree.  Again, as I stated earlier, we typically over-prescribe medications compared to other industrialized nations - the same type of nations that probably have ipods, web browsers, and text messaging.  \n\nSo what''s so fundamentally different between our industrialized nation and the others?\nFor starters, this may or may not come to you as a shock but we (I assume you''re in the US) are the only industrialized nation to allow pharmaceutical companies to directly advertise to consumers.  \n\nThis also may or may not come to you as a shock but John Watson, you may remember him from our studies regarding classical conditioning and the Little Albert study, took refuge in the advertising industry post-academia.  Others have followed suit as well.   There''s a lot of psychology (and money) involved in marketing - priming, appealing to emotions, manipulating thoughts - all aimed at parting consumers from their money.\n\nHeck, as you walk into a super market, the first thing you''ll probably see is produce.  There''s a marketing reason for that - it primes the consumer into associating fresh food with the rest of the goods in the store.  \n\nAt any rate, marketing, pharmaceutical advertisements and an alarming trend of decreasing talk therapy, and increasing prescriptions is troubling to me.  I apologize if this wasn''t coherent.  \n\nTin foil hat aside, I''m interested in hearing what our instructors think about this topic.', '09 Aug ''13, 00:51', '100101529'),
