('100115029', '100099604', 'users/100047785/pitossomo', 'you see... A man who raises cattle will get the biggest or the strongest ones to have babies. That''s human selection. Now, natural selection is similar to it, but is the environment that defines which cow will live and have descendants. If there''s to cows, one strong and big, and another one who was born weak and small, when a predator comes the fittest to survive will be the big one, which will live more, reproduce more and pass its characteristics to the babies.', '21 Sep ''13, 06:19', NULL),
('100115030', '100111872', 'users/100047785/pitossomo', 'The "bigger brain" characteristics must be seen as a characteristics for our species, the Homo Sapiens, not for an single individual. So when the humans learned how to hunter he started to eat more, which could sustain his brain to grow. When humans learned how to cook, it was the same process happening again. And in fact, is not just about the quantity, but the quality - eating more meat could lend more energy than just fruits and vegetables.', '21 Sep ''13, 06:30', NULL),
