('100115213', '100114994', 'users/147085674/lauren-55', 'My parents didn''t get married until they were 30, and waited a couple years before starting to have kids. This most likely influences my own thoughts on marriage that I can wait and don''t have any type of set age goal for getting married. I want to have a successful career and be able to take care of myself completely before even thinking about getting married. It'' a huge commitment to somebody else for the rest of your life (50% of the time). At this point I don''t even know myself well enough to know what I want in 5 years, let alone WHO I''d want in 5 years. Looking back 5 years ago, I was a totally different person and I accept that I''ll change between now and 5 years from now.\nThe marriage age has probably been shifting because of how socially acceptable it is and how difficult it is. It was expected for people to get married young in the 50''s and start families, to become the perfect American family. It''s much different now where we hold careers, higher education, and independence at a higher priority than having a family. It''s more acceptable in the present day to be alone with a successful job or fulfilling career, opposed to in the 50''s they''d wonder if the person had a problem if they didn''t get married.\nBeing ready to get married is highly subjective. I''d want to fully believe I could commit to that person for the rest of my life, be able to have a comfortable life together, and feel that they want the same things. There has to be no question that you''d want to spend the rest of your life with them, that they''re the best person for you. Then maybe if mutually agreed on, marriage would be the right option.', '21 Sep ''13, 22:42', NULL),
('100115355', '100072804', 'users/125984079/dieter-9', 'I agree with you that an absolute scale of dB always uses a reference level. In acoustics, this level is well accepted, so it is quite common not to reference it. I just looked it up, and the reference pressure you mention is the default used in air, but there is another one in water.\nThe teachers got it right in that they equate the amplitude with pressure. What they call volume in technical terms would be termed sound intensity, and it relates to pressure as intensity=pressure^2/rho/c where rho the density of air and c the speed of sound actually. This statement is actually not correct either because the same dB value at sea level and on top of a mountain (with rho only half that at seal level) correspond to a factor of two change in Intensity.\nWhat seems to confuse students more is the nature of the logarithmic scale. It also seems to have thrown the instructors as they confuse the log base 10 with log base 2 (which is a bit odd as the only field I have seen log base 2 much is in computer algorithms). I think the point they try to make is that the sound intensity changes by a constant factor with every 10dB of sound intensity.', '22 Sep ''13, 17:29', NULL),
