('100119637', NULL, 'users/100044700/jim-roames', 'Actually, there are people who deny that there were many people who did not do anything about it. I mentioned the Manning et al article for a reason. They draw a distinction between the actual events (which they feel do not display evidence of the bystander effect in the way that it is defined in psychological research) with the "Parable of the 38 Witnesses."\n\nIt is not a matter of some minor details being wrong. The main point of the story is wrong. But it is these "details" which gave the story its power. Saying that there were 38 eye witnesses is a lot more powerful than saying that there were really just 6. The eye witnesses seeing 3 attacks is a lot more powerful than saying that a handful of people saw part of the first attack, but could not have seen the second. Saying that no one did anything is a lot more powerful than saying that they drove off Moseley, someone called the police and they saw that Kitty was able to walk away. Saying that they knew she was being stabbed is more powerful than saying that no one knew that Moseley had a knife and they all thought it was a domestic dispute.\n\nYes, there was a tragic murder. In the Parable of the 38 Witnesses it happened because of the bystander effect/bystander apathy. In what actually happened (according to the research of Manning et al, using court documents, statements from the DA at the time, and other sources) the main problem was that people did not understand the severity of the situation. The six people who saw any part of either attack thought that they were witnessing a domestic disturbance and behaved accordingly. They made sure the man was chased away (he drove off in his car) and that the woman was able to get up and walk away (albeit very slowly). At least one of them called the police. The police also thought it was no big deal, so they were very slow to respond. Tragic? Absolutely. But not understanding the severity of the situation is different from understanding the severity of the situation yet failing to act because you assume someone else will. The latter is the bystander effect. The former, while tragic, is not.', '09 Oct ''13, 16:13', '100116026'),
