('100131775', NULL, 'users/100029839/viliam-bur', 'Traits passing on from one generation to another, that is also evolution, just on a shorter time scale. Just like the gravitational force is the same force whether we speak about why apples fall down to Earth, or why the Earth rotates around the Sun. Different scale does not make it fundamentally a different thing.\n\nSometimes a different scale seems like being governed by different laws of nature, because on small scales some changes are too small to be visible. For example, when an apple falls down to the Earth, at the same time the Earth moves up towards the apple -- but that movement is so small that we cannot observe it. So it seems like the apple is moving, but the Earth is somehow eternally fixed in the same place. Analogically, by observing one generation replaced by another, we usually don''t see a lot of change, so it seems like the species as a whole is somehow eternally fixed, too. Or an example outside of science: if you only observed a tree yesterday and today, it also doesn''t seem like the tree was growing, but on a larger time scale the changes will be more obvious.', '29 Nov ''13, 07:35', '100110296'),
