('100174083', NULL, 'users/100018081/markus-spath', 'The difference between you providing hours and hours of free online support and Udacity might be scale. Once a course is created, hundreds of thousands of learners - e.g. CS 101: "Join 337,087 Students" - can enjoy it at marginal costs of maintenance for Udacity. Hence the alternative to their new model is not necessarily shutting down, but to find a better model.\n\n(I''m currently taking a course on Coursera and out of about 6,000 students who completed the course 25% (1,500) opted in for the ''signature track'' for a verified certificate netting Coursera 75,000 for the first run alone)\n\nI''m not in their shoes and they definitely have good reasons for taking this approach, but I have to agree with Anurag, outside of the US $150/m does not look like a good deal given all available alternatives.', '27 Apr ''14, 04:40', '100173744'),
('100174131', NULL, 'users/100002514/anurag-acharya', 'I realize it might not be feasible always for Udacity to keep giving everything for free, but the "verified" track is ridiculously expensive. Even a one-time minimal fee to get a certificate would be a decent option, but "per month per course" is just insanely expensive.\n\nSay I want to do a three-course programming track. Even if I complete a course in 3 months (and that''s really fast!), it would cost me $1350. For this cost, I could get about a dozen courses in other MOOC sites or even do a course in a physical institue and get proper certified in a tenth of that cost. So why would anyone do these Udacity courses?', '27 Apr ''14, 06:33', '100173744'),
('100174135', NULL, 'users/100002514/anurag-acharya', 'I agree. A middle way can be found, I am sure. A minimal amount to get a certificate verified would be a decent compromise, but this current plan is way too much. But like you said, there must be some sort of recognition for the effort we put into the courses. Else I could just view course materials and lecture notes and videos of reputed Universities and learn from books.', '27 Apr ''14, 06:37', '100174061'),
('100174451', NULL, 'users/100048531/paula-franzini', 'If you can do a course in a physical institute for a tenth of the cost, why don''t you do that? Coding bootcamps in North America are on the order of 6000$ to 15000$ for a two month (full-time course) so Udacity certification is still quite inexpensive compared to that. Why would you expect them to be able to charge prices competitive with prices outside of the US when they ARE in the US (and therefore their cost basis is American)?', '27 Apr ''14, 17:47', '100173744'),
