('100182020', NULL, 'users/115118682/sealfin', 'Thrun said that MOOCs were a bad product because less than ten percent of the MOOC students managed to complete each class.\n\nIs it bad that MOOCs have a 90% drop-out rate? \n\nThe tertiary education drop-out rate in the UK (reported recently by the Times Higher Education) is 16% but that statistic is biased: most  if not all?  tertiary education institutes in the UK have entry requirements; surely MOOCs will have a higher drop-out rate due to not having those entry requirements and thus students who lack the necessary foundation will begin to study a MOOC, realise that the MOOC is currently beyond their abilities, and drop-out more freely than they would from a traditional course as with a MOOC there are no negative repercussions to trying, and failing.\n\nI''ve been rejected by every university I''ve ever applied to study at in the UK, yet I''ve been awarded a certificate of Highest Distinction by Udacity. Being able to try, and failing without negative repercussion, is good. Being able to try, and succeeding, is better ;)', '13 May ''14, 19:25', '100181519'),
