('100186514', NULL, 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Fantastic question, Spoony!! The words "dominant" and "recessive" are relative to one another. You can have many different alleles of a gene (not just two!) and we call that an allelic series. \n\nFor example, if we have alleles A, B, C, D, and E, we might find that D is dominant to B, B is dominant to E, E is dominant to A, and A is dominant to C. We would call this an "allelic series" and write it as follows:\n\nD &gt; B &gt; E &gt; A &gt; C\n\nSo if you were heterozygous for alleles C and E then you would see the phenotype of E. If you were heterozygous for alleles B and E then you would see the phenotype of B. \n\nDoes that make sense?', '29 May ''14, 12:23', '100186291'),
