('100186553', NULL, 'users/100234475/spoony', 'I was going to reply there, but having read over what I had written it was a most terrifyingly hair raising controversial question/rant (in my opinion at least) that would have made you choke as you read it.\n\nSo I deleted it and instead I''ll follow up with a much tamer version of my question.\n\nIntelligence, nature or nurture? I would hope that the the extent to which someone intellectually develops is more about environment than your genes because it at least, in a truly fair situation levels the playing field between people. (not that life is fair or anything.) But I suspect that this is not in fact the widely held opinion.\n\nIf you have any thoughts on that I''d be fascinated to read them.', '29 May ''14, 13:55', '100186525'),
('100186624', NULL, 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'I do have thoughts, though I''m not an expert in cognition or neuroscience. However, I am a biologist/geneticist and think I can clarify the current consensus.\n\nRemember that your ability to think/reason depends on a complex network of neurons (and other cell types) that make up your brain. This complex organ is developed extensively during embryonic development and continues to grow and change during childhood, responding dramatically to hormones at puberty, and reaching stability finally around the age of 25.\n\nThe methods we have for measuring intelligence are imperfect, but IQ is one method of examining higher order cognition (the ability to reason/think). There are people with extremely high IQs, those with incredibly low IQs, and most somewhere in the middle. Although it can be difficult to differentiate what genetic/physiological/environmental differences distinguish a person with an average IQ from a person with a high IQ, there have been many studies demonstrating clear defects that would differentiate someone with a very low IQ from those with an average or high IQ. \n\nFor example, Fragile X mental retardation is "a spectrum of intellectual disabilities ranging from mild to severe" (wiki ref). "Fragile X syndrome is associated with the expansion of the CGG trinucleotide repeat affecting the Fragile X mental retardation 1 (FMR1) gene on the X chromosome, resulting in a failure to express the fragile X mental retardation protein (FMRP), which is required for normal neural development." Mutations in the FMR1 gene cause all sorts of developmental defects that affect intelligence. Exactly how this occurs is not fully known, but lots has been learned by modeling the disease in the fruit fly. You can learn more about Fragile X Syndrome here:\n\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fragile_X_syndrome#Neurological\n\nand more about the fruit fly model here:\n\nhttp://modencode.sciencemag.org/drosophila/autism/\n\nSo this is a clear example of how genetics affects intelligence. Science researchers are learning more about the genetic basis of intelligence all the time. In fact, IQ has a relatively high heritability (indicating that the variation in intelligence seen in the human population can be explained largely by genetics). \n\nHOWEVER, there are plenty of environmental factors that affect intelligence, but many are likely to be most effective if their action occurs during embryonic development, when the foundation of the brain is being laid down. I don''t have any specifics to cite about this.\n\nThis is a very gray area, and like most traits, both genetics and environment play a role in intelligence; but be wary of placing too much emphasis on the environmental factors - there is a lot of hidden privilege and societal factors that are responsible for moderate variation in IQ between individuals in a population. Each case must be examined individually and with extreme attention to detail.', '29 May ''14, 18:52', '100186525'),
