('100187438', NULL, 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Not quite. Technically, all humans are apes. Chimpanzees are also apes. You can find out more about what apes are on the wiki page here:\n\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ape\n\nNow, chimpanzees and humans are cousins - LITERALLY. We are apes that share a common ancestor (like cousins sharing a common grandparent or great grandparent or great-great grandparent etc.). About 8 million years ago that ancestor roamed the East African Savannah. 8 million years ago there were no humans or chimpanzees. But there were ape-like creatures. At least one population of these ape-like ancestors were split into two separate populations that could not interbreed frequently (if at all). One of these populations eventually continued to intrabreed and evolved into modern day chimpanzees. The other population continues to intrabreed and evolved into modern day humans. Chimpanzees and humans are cousins whose common ancestor (grandparent) is no longer alive. But we''re all apes.\n\nDoes that help clarify?', '02 Jun ''14, 01:08', '100187430'),
