('100074375', 'Word "no" for children', 'null', 'Hello everybody, I''m russian arab and I have a question for psychologists. As I know, babies and small children don''t perceive word "no" and negative expressions. E.g. if I say to my little sister "don''t go there" or "don''t do it", she will understand it like "go there" and "do it".\nIs it a true (experimentally it is :) )? And if it is a true, why does it happen?\nAnd the last question. There are some statistics that little children every day hear from their parents about 300-400 negative expressions. Is it harmful for them?  ', 'users/100057011/muammar', '20 Jun ''13, 04:15', 100, 0, 0),
('100074445', '''Foreign Accent Syndrome''. Is this even real?', 'null', 'Just read this online. No, not on Onion. How real / made-up is this?\n http://edition.cnn.com/2013/06/20/world/australia-car-crash-new-french-accent/index.html  http://edition.cnn.com/2013/06/20/world/australia-car-crash-new-french-accent/index.html', 'users/118232219/sourav-3', '20 Jun ''13, 09:14', 121, 0, 0),
('100074447', 'Baby fears', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 05 Problem Set - Problem 19', 'Hi, I know my mom used to put my hands in the blanket when i''d sleep because, she said, babies get scared of their own arms moving around. Is that true? And do babies get irrational fears too (like fear of the dark)? Thanks,\nIulia ', 'users/121166559/iulia-5', '20 Jun ''13, 09:20', 160, 1, 2),
('100074479', 'Total Hours of the Course Content', 'null', 'Hi Everyone, Could you please help me to know the total hours that one needs to invest to go through the videos and answer the assignments ? This will help me to plan my schedule accordingly. Thanks a lot. Regards,\nShahan ', 'users/121543333/shahan', '20 Jun ''13, 10:27', 148, 0, 0),
('100074553', 'Sexual Identity and single gendered schools', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 05 Development - Sexual identity in adolescence', 'I noticed something and was wondering if there are any studies done on this: Does going to a single gendered school increase the chances of being a homosexual in life? I read in many places that being a homosexual is due to genetic makeup, however, among my friends who identifies as homosexuals. I noticed that most of them went to single-gender schools during their adolescence  and wonder if it might play a factor in the nurture aspect. Thus I wonder about the research and speculation on this as well as wonder about the argument of sexual orientation being fixed or fluid over time. I understands the popular argument of homosexuality being genetic makeup thus it is fixed, but wonder if that is the popular argument because it is a more politically correct &amp; easiest way to get the general public to be more accepting homosexuality (since genetics do play a role too as research has shown) Note: I''m not against people sexual orientation here. Everyone is free to love whoever they like. But just want to hear some interesting opinions on it.', 'users/100008253/snowpolar', '20 Jun ''13, 13:02', 373, 4, 2),
('100074630', 'i chose personality in hte first place but all the answers were marked incorrect', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 01 Problem Set - Problem 17', 'Seems like this part of the quiz doen{t work', 'users/121595781/valeria-11', '20 Jun ''13, 15:11', 158, 0, 1),
('100074643', 'Pain treshold likely to be higher for Lauren?', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 04 Problem Set - Problem 08', 'Hello! I have read that the pain threshold is - on average - higher for women, thus, Andy is likely to hurt more (and recently, this subject has been on broadcast in The Netherlands by an "experiment" on TV) - This seems to be plausible for me as women must withstand the pain in a childbirth; but is this true or another urban legend? Best regards,\nJulien Caussin ', 'users/117588655/julirn', '20 Jun ''13, 15:30', 215, 2, 1),
('100074650', 'Congratulations for the Golden Brain; how was the test carried out?', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 04 Problem Set - Problem 10', 'Hello! Please satisfy my curiosity: how exactly has the test been carried out?  The test person lifted two weights and should tell which one was heavier; but was ONE correct answer sufficient to count the challenge as successful? - What would interest me, too: were two equal weights given to the test person, as a "countercheck"? Best regards,\nJulien Caussin ', 'users/117588655/julirn', '20 Jun ''13, 15:43', 207, 1, 3),
('100074656', 'Just a remark: one basic taste was missing', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 04 Problem Set - Problem 12', 'Hello! Thing I did''t know: there are not four basic tastes as I learned as a pupil - there is a fifth (or sixth if you count pungency, as this course does): umami. Read here if this interests you: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umami http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umami Best regards, \nJulien Caussin ', 'users/117588655/julirn', '20 Jun ''13, 15:54', 661, 2, 3),
