('100121518', 'Lesson 12 Stress and Health: Different responses to stress: important addition, Greg', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 12 Stress and Health - Different responses to stress', 'In this video (Greg with a glass of water: Different responses to stress) the context is: positive(=instrumental) emotional(=autoplastic) coping. And the best way is to feel free to be an optimist. The example with the glass of water is an instrumental revision when he chooses to see it as half full.\nBut of course there are environmental(extrinsic) factors which take effect on your coping with the world. It''s not just the alloplastic(what could be changed in the environment) such as lots of work or the relationship to your boss or such things as social norms such as role-norms e.g. the expectation that you have to see bad things happening to you as an optimist. People often get into a downward spiral via the negative coping that follows: denial(i.e. not seeing that there is a problem at all) or repression(i.e.telling yourself you have to see it positively, you have to....). Denial and repression belong to the autoplastic(where you deal with feelings but in a negative(i.e. palliative) way and do yourself harm. ', 'users/100104209/marcus', '17 Oct ''13, 11:39', 99, 0, 0),
('100121677', 'hypothesis for why there are sleep cycles', 'Intro to Psychology - Lesson 06 Consciousness - Sleep stages', 'it seems interesting that we cycle back up and down in our sleep.  I think it is probably a survival trait.  A person get''s to the point where they are almost awake to probably check their surroundings and make sure all is well and no tigers about to jump out and maul them and then go back into deeper levels of sleep.  ', 'users/154020240/sandra-89', '17 Oct ''13, 23:29', 95, 0, 0),
