('100062919', '100062247', 'users/100044283/mykl-w-clason-2', 'Here are my results (best time is probably not good data wise), edited from original formatting to avoid being too long of a post, notable scores in bold. Anticipation seems troublesome. For every .21 or better I get I get 2-5 worst than .25.\nFirst set\n0.264 seconds 0.362 seconds 0.233 seconds 0.206 seconds 0.231 seconds 0.275 seconds 0.212 seconds  0.204 seconds 0.229 seconds 0.253 seconds 0.286 seconds 0.182 seconds 0.338 seconds 0.289 seconds 0.253 seconds\nSecond set\n0.253 seconds 0.312 seconds 0.231 seconds 0.271 seconds 0.171 seconds 0.257 seconds 0.242 seconds 0.341 seconds 0.208 seconds 0.284 seconds 0.204 seconds  0.22 seconds 0.238 seconds 0.3 seconds 0.275 seconds 0.221 seconds\nIn any case, I''m not sure this is the best measure of reaction time, at least beyond a certain error margin of probably around +- .5 seconds or so on average, as it depends on how fast you can click, anticipation and how fast that click can be processed.', '04 Jun ''13, 10:36', 2),
('100062926', '100062834', 'users/117523005/judy-12', 'As a linguist I''d like to offer something here - both are correct actually. Your example "To which .... " is regarded as very formal and appropriate for written communication in such contexts as academic papers, legal documents, official reports and so on. Here I think we have a more informal situation and the question comes across as more friendly, relaxed and approachable. These days use of language is about the context it''s used in and is not about correctness (prescriptive approach) but about how it''s really used by people (descriptive). As language changes all the time, it''s impossible to be prescriptive!', '04 Jun ''13, 10:45', 3),
('100062994', '100061827', 'users/100036208/prasad-bhattad', 'Hi everyone!\nI am Prasad from Mumbai, India!\nI am in my final year of Chemical Engineering.\nI took this course because since my childhood I have been very interested in the human behavior.I used to make my own theories since I was in 4th grade and tell my mom (in a teaching tone) that why my sister is behaving in the way she is behaving!\nIt is then that I came to know that my mom herself had a degree in Child Psychology!\nSo then on wards I started telling my theories to my mom which she would correct if necessary and guide me!It was just a fun thing to do!\nBut now I really want to know this field in and out and what possibly could be better than a free course from the experts in the field!\nReally looking forward to what you guys have in store!', '04 Jun ''13, 12:03', 1),
('100063010', '100062645', 'users/117488257/mai-6', 'Cognitive psychology deals with  the mental processes that affect human behavior, or, in other words, our mental abilities such as: perceiving, remembering, solving problems, learning and decision making.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:18', 5),
('100063015', '100062860', 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'Great point Arpit. Random distributions can certainly wind up skewed. \nIf you thought that gender may play a big role in your experiment, you could do what you said (intervene to make sure the gender ratio is equal for the different groups) or just restrict your experiment (at least to begin with) to one gender. Of course, increasing your sample size is also a good idea. As your sample size gets bigger and bigger, it becomes less and less likely that you will have a significant skewing.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:21', 6),
('100063020', '100062824', 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'It sounds like you are in the right place. As to your questions... that first one is tough, though lesson 6, which is on Consciousness, should be interesting. And for question 2, lesson 9 is on Language and Thought. I think you''ll find it interesting too.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:25', 2),
('100063021', '100061827', 'users/100027642/phil-gallagher', 'Hi everyone\nMy name is Phil, I''m from the UK, but I live in Maryland, USA. I''m a management consultant with a background in training and development. I''ve been studying psychology in a dilettante fashion for many years, ever since I came across psychometrics and aptitude tests. I''m 2/3 of the way through Thinking, Fast and Slow by Daniel Kahneman, and I thought it might be fun to get the academic overview of what psychology is.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:27', 1),
('100063026', '100062432', 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'Let''s say you were looking at 10 different cities and looking at the number of drowning deaths and the number of ice cream cones eaten in each.\nThe cities with more people in them will likely have more of, well, everything. They will have more drowning deaths AND more ice cream cone consumption simply because there are more people in them.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:32', 2),
('100063034', '100062489', 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'As stated, this question only gives us a tendency. In general, as a person drinks more alcohol, their physical coordination gets worse. \nWe don''t know how strong that correlation is though. If alcohol consumption was a perfect predictor of coordination, the correlation would be strong (perfect, in fact). But there are other factors that affect coordination (how tired you are, how clumsy you are "naturally", how focused you are, etc...) so I suspect this reduces the strength of the correlation.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:37', 0),
('100063040', '100062645', 'users/114827221/opportunity', 'The cognitive psychologists concentrate on how people understand things and how people deal with problems.\nI thought this is the answer.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:41', 0),
('100063042', '100062911', 'users/100058328/bulut-bulgu', 'Multiple choices can be correct.', '04 Jun ''13, 12:43', 0),
('100063055', '100061827', 'users/116968514/alexandra-26', 'I''m Alexandra, 26.  I''m from Texas, US.\nAnd I love Psychology!!!!!! \nThis is the third Intro class I''ve taken (one my last year of high school, one semester at college, and here) and I have in my possession at least 8 different college textbooks (including one from 1943) and several various books authored on the subject. I can''t get enough of learning how the human mind works!', '04 Jun ''13, 13:05', 1),
('100063067', '100061827', 'users/117572522/anil-30', 'Hello Everyone,\nI am Anil Varma from India working in the telecommunications industry. \nThis is an excellent platform to get aqainted with something I have been yearning to know for a long time.\nI have an interest to know questions like Why does one person behave different from another? and about introverts and extroverts.\nNow I know that I am supposed to look into Behavioural and peronality psychology, nonetless looking forward to learn a lot.\n  Thanks to Susan,Lauren,Greg and TIckles too. :)', '04 Jun ''13, 13:17', 1),
