('100063151', '100062835', 'users/115787008/broderick', 'So, if you get a question wrong and then you correct it, does that still count against you?', '04 Jun ''13, 14:22', 3),
('100063159', '100062645', 'users/117589276/rani-2', 'The individuals I work with are described as having cognitive impairments. They have been diagnosed with developmental disorders. Those on the autism spectrum, the intellectually challenged, many genetic and brain injury use cognitive psychologists. Often a measure of cognition is IQ but there are many measurement tools and assessments that they do.', '04 Jun ''13, 14:31', 0),
('100063166', '100061827', 'users/117589276/rani-2', 'Hi everyone. I am Rani. Some of the reasons i am interested in this course;\nthe mind \nthe brain \nthe human \nspirit human \nbehavior \ngenetics \ncrystal children \nmental health \nearly childhood intervention \nfunction and dysfunction\nSocial context of normal\nSocial engineering\nSocialization\nI think that the potential of children are dramatically overlooked. I think brains are amazing. \nI''m 57 with 4 biological children and 50+ adopted and raised children. I have no formal education but am a life long learner. \nNice to meet you all.', '04 Jun ''13, 14:50', 2),
('100063182', '100062184', 'users/100036208/prasad-bhattad', 'Well for the reference part he did tell us that he has a PhD in Personality psychology.\nAnd Wikipedia I really think is not the best source of information or I should say the accurate source of information.Here if you want even you can edit the page, and you will be shocked to see the number of WRONG INFORMATION pages on Wikipedia.And Wikipedia itself says so.I think this will be helpful :\nhttp://www.findingdulcinea.com/news/education/2010/march/The-Top-10-Reasons-Students-Cannot-Cite-or-Rely-on-Wikipedia.html\nI am not saying its all wrong but its not an accurate source.', '04 Jun ''13, 15:12', 0),
