('100063202', '100061827', 'users/117350536/julia-72', 'Hi everyone!\nMy name is Julia.  I am 20 and I am from Mxico. I  am studying Organizational Psychology :)   And well, I think it is very important that we continue learning about psychology because it help us to understand many things such as personality, the reactions of people in different situations, why people feel more motivated at work with money or with incentives. Also I  want to practice my english because I''m planning having an intership in 1 o 2 years.  \nit''s really helpful that the course is online!! =) \nNice to meet you!!', '04 Jun ''13, 15:34', 2),
('100063213', '100063027', 'users/112111845/cristina-26', 'It is cognitive because this can happen to both humans and dogs.\nThe dog remembers that behind that door there is food. It has to do with thinking, in this special case, remembering, therefore it''s cognitive. The same thing happens when we find out that mom prepared our favorite dish. Only the thought of it makes us salivate, because we remember the taste of it.', '04 Jun ''13, 15:48', 3),
('100063229', '100063173', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question!  We don''t ignore the fact that different groups of people have different reaction times, in fact, we know that most peoples times will differ.  However, on average, the reaction times for most people will be very similar.  One of the issues with giving the same person different amounts of coffee and measuring their reaction times is that the results would not be very generalizable.  We would only be measuring the results of one person and it would be very hard to argue that those results applied to anyone else.  Hope that helps!', '04 Jun ''13, 16:04', 2),
('100063232', '100063052', 'users/112111845/cristina-26', 'Cognitive psychology deals with perception, thinking, memories, problem solving, even language.\nIn this case, Dr. Katz believes that Jared''s issue is related to the way he perceives himself, having unrealistic negative thoughts.\nHope this helps!', '04 Jun ''13, 16:08', 8),
('100063248', '100061827', 'users/117596824/heinz-1', 'My name is Heinz, I live in Berne, Switzerland. \nLike many others I also work in the software business as a project leader. I like working with people very much, find it interesting and see the teamwork as the most important element to success with your success. I''m very curious about this course, because I have had a lot of experience but no special eduction so far.', '04 Jun ''13, 16:34', 1),
('100063273', '100061842', 'users/117276885/sandhyaa', 'According to me when people interacting online their behavior is more open. They behave the way they actually are. When there is no eye contact people feel more confident, and they know they can get away with anything when ever they want.', '04 Jun ''13, 17:01', 2),
('100063287', '100061827', 'users/117625566/john-692', 'Hi everyone, I''m John from Nottingham, UK. \nRecently, I''ve enrolled on an MA Philosophy of Health and Happiness at the University of Birmingham. I have a passion for understanding other people''s thought processes, which originally led me into a BA in Philosophy and Theology. I enrolled on this MOOC as a way of expanding my knowledge of psychological practice and theory (beyond the little I used as evidence in BA essays!) My main objective in this course is to learn enough to be useful in exploring my desire to study the interrelationship between philosophy and psychology. I hope to pursue this subject to PhD, with special focus on the how exploring the philosophical conception of mental health issues may be able to aid understanding, and eventually diagnosis/treatment.\nThis is meant to be in preparation for my MA, but it doesn''t hurt to have a little fun on the way! So far so good!', '04 Jun ''13, 17:13', 1),
('100063301', '100062266', 'users/117285039/juliana-8', 'I had the same problem. In some cases, I had to make couples of answers and play with them', '04 Jun ''13, 17:21', 0),
('100063308', '100063027', 'users/100027642/phil-gallagher', 'I''m not sure I totally agree with that. Do people (or dogs) really salivate in response to a memory of food? In the dog''s case, isn''t this closer to the Pavlovian, conditioned response? The animal has learnt that the cupboard is opened shortly before it gets fed. There is an association, therefore, between the door being opened and food. This may well be cognitive, but it looks behavioral to me.', '04 Jun ''13, 17:28', 0),
('100063363', '100063340', 'users/117643015/mohammed-salley', 'i think its more important to complet all the video and the quiz', '04 Jun ''13, 18:13', 1),
('100063426', '100061918', 'users/100020046/code_jamer', 'Behavioral Psychology deals with conditioning a subject according to a specific environment and in return generating a response or behavior. \nIt also involves studying voluntary behavior of a subject and the consequences of that action or behavior. \nThe consequence can be taken as a reward in response to a particular action. That reward could either be positive(a treat) or negative(a punishment).\nSo, the case of studying some one being an introvert or an extrovert is not so much behavioral psychology, rather it is a study of individual personality traits that shape the overall personality of an individual', '04 Jun ''13, 19:24', 0),
('100063522', '100061827', 'users/117520869/benedick', 'Hi! I''m Benedick from Philippines. I have studied AB in Psychology and would like to explore a different means of delivery in studying it.  Hope to learn more!', '04 Jun ''13, 21:08', 1),
('100063528', '100061872', 'users/117681680/norma-dalia', 'i think could be..\n to analyze every conduct on the behavior\n to watch and learn the differences on cases (as the case of the snake)\n be honest with ur patients\n to identify the problem in each case\n to research\n to practice\n* dont stop learning :)', '04 Jun ''13, 21:15', 2),
('100063543', '100061827', 'users/117681680/norma-dalia', 'Hi, im norma from mexico.\nIm a lawyer but am taking this course cos i really enjoy to understand the human behavior, and i want to learn about it. :)', '04 Jun ''13, 21:34', 2),
('100063545', '100061827', 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'I''m Naomi, I''m 29 and I''m from North Carolina in the US. I''m taking the course as a refresher. I took intro to psych in college about ten years ago, and it''s been a long time since then.\nBut even so, I''m curious about the psychological reasoning behind the way humans act toward one another on a global scale. I''m also curious about why some people seem to have an innate curiosity about the world around them and an eagerness to explore the unknown when others seem to have no interest in knowing more than what they see everyday. I''m such a curious person and I love to explore. It''s hard for me to understand people who profess to having no interest in knowing what''s beyond the borders of their everyday lives.', '04 Jun ''13, 21:38', 1),
('100063573', '100062184', 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'As someone who is introverted, I know that sometimes I am shy and sometimes, I''m very much not shy.  I consider myself an introvert because I do prefer solitary activities to social activities, and am oftentimes more comfortable with my own company than I am with even one other person around.  This is not because they make me uncomfortable, but because I often feel as though I am obligated to focus all my attention, constantly, on social interaction when someone else is in my company.  It''s even sometimes considered rude not to act on this sense of obligation. Rather than constantly feeling that need to fulfill my social obligation (as well trying to act socially pleasing), I prefer to do things on my own. This does not make me consistently shy towards other people.  I guess it just makes me socially lazy.  lol\nThe sentence is misleading in the video certainly. If people are to learn information from the course that they are most certainly going to assume is accurate (to the finest detail) just because someone with a doctorate in psychology is the instructor, the information should be portrayed with as much clarity and attention to detail where facts are concerned as possible.  It''s impossible to be perfect, but the Udacity interface does allow for corrections to information to be made...\nAnd there''s my 2 cents plus a few bucks.  lol', '04 Jun ''13, 22:26', 6),
('100063575', '100062977', 'users/114015140/michael-650', 'You can also find used hardcover versions online at Amazon inexpensively if you find e-books more difficult to read than printed text.', '04 Jun ''13, 22:30', 0);
INSERT INTO `respuesta` (`idAnswer`, `idPost`, `idUser`, `textAnswer`, `dateAnswer`, `votesAnswer`) VALUES
('100063595', '100062619', 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'I have to say that I think the question is worded clearly.  It essentially asks which type of psychologist would study ethnic/racial discrimination (Mary is usually considered an ordinary "white" name and Juanita is generally a name given to latino or hispanic children).  We are (rather slyly, too) led to believe racial and/or ethnic discrimination was the cause of Juanita''s not being promoted. Discrimination is an inherently social behavior as it deals with social perception; therefore, social psychologist must be the answer.', '04 Jun ''13, 23:04', 4),
('100063602', '100062413', 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'The question was not what kind of psychologist would study the individual who supposedly discriminated against Juanita or what kind of psychologist would study discrimination solely in the workplace.  The question was what kind of psychologist would study discrimination like the kind we read in the example.  We are given names which subtly give us the impression that Juanita is a minority where Mary is not.  The names imply ethnic or racial discrimination.  The study of discrimination itself falls into social psychology.  Discrimination deals with social perception, or really how people perceive others in a negative context based on something that makes them seemingly "different" than what is generally considered normal.', '04 Jun ''13, 23:14', 2),
('100063620', '100063173', 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'Wouldn''t it be best to first get a baseline for reaction times without caffeine for the people in both groups?  I mean, we know their reaction times will probably be different (for a number of reasons, no less), but I''d think the study would be inherently flawed by starting it off based on the assumption that reaction times across a particular group of people at a particular time of day will be similar.  They probably will be, but shouldn''t you check this just to say in the future that you had that covered?  Plus, you''d want to find those people whose reaction times are "naturally" higher, and those who reaction times aren''t...up to par, so to speak.  In other words, you''d want a baseline, but you''d also want to know who your anomalous individuals (within the particular group) are right from the start.', '04 Jun ''13, 23:42', 1),
('100063639', '100062860', 'users/115794268/naomi-13', 'I would think that even with the possibility of the random distribution leaving the two groups skewed, random distribution is still the best method because having the researcher try to assign individuals based on traits might also result in the researcher affecting the results because of some subconscious bias.', '05 Jun ''13, 00:10', 0),
('100063710', '100063484', 'users/100113949/ahmad-5', 'I guess you cannot figure out how the .4 was arrived at just by looking at graph. It must have been generated by the computer program in which the data were processed. I think these graphs in this course are just for demonstation purposes and they do not represent actual data.', '05 Jun ''13, 01:51', 2),
('100063731', '100062836', 'users/100113949/ahmad-5', 'I agree, I''m really enjoying the Research Methods  module.', '05 Jun ''13, 02:29', 1),
('100063776', '100062184', 'users/100304477/ampharos', 'Perhaps some people are not familiar with with the terms introvert and extrovert. (For example, because English isn''t their first language or because they''re new to psychology.) By changing those terms (in this question) to shy and outgoing, which, although not perfectly, do align with introvert and extrovert, you will still get the same answer.', '05 Jun ''13, 03:57', 0),
('100063813', '100062366', 'users/100000724/hisham-showeir', 'May the Prof. should have used a smiley face emoticon, so that one can remember he is still on the psychology course one started with ! And please remember that the goal of psychology is to get learners to learn and not necessarily be happy.', '05 Jun ''13, 05:24', 1),
('100063838', '100061827', 'users/117592144/lour', 'Hi!\nMy name is Lourdes and I''m writing from Madrid, Spain. I heard about those courses on the radio and I quickly looked it up for more info about it. \nI majored in English but I also studied Linguistics, Translation, Literature, etc.\n I'' ve always felt fascinated about the human mind, language and behavior and I am really happy to have joined the course.', '05 Jun ''13, 06:33', 1),
('100063854', '100062238', 'users/117759990/smidha', 'just go with the flow', '05 Jun ''13, 07:16', 2),
('100063879', '100061827', 'users/100000724/hisham-showeir', 'Hi,\nMy name is Hisham, 52, I''m taking this course to get a better understanding of human behavior, and more importantly to see if I can blend  psychological theories to my conscious and come up with improved performance.', '05 Jun ''13, 07:55', 1),
('100063889', '100062238', 'users/100000724/hisham-showeir', 'Pick up the right answer, and it''ll be ok.', '05 Jun ''13, 08:14', 1),
('100063913', '100062184', 'users/100032516/simon-15', 'Your question is pretty good. In @Greg Feist''s answer (I don''t know how to @ person here), I found that, he meant shyness and introvert are highly related, although not exactly the same. And the wikipedia link and the essay wiki refers to point out where the differences are, but not enough to prove there is no relation between them, so I don''t think there is any contradiction between their opinions. I agree that Susan said "Introverts or shy people" here to make it more easier for us to understand, but words like "they are exactly the same" are needed to make it accurate.', '05 Jun ''13, 09:09', 0),
('100063914', '100061872', 'users/117775645/elena-alexandra', 'to love people', '05 Jun ''13, 09:10', 1),
('100064008', '100061872', 'users/117795046/hisham-5', 'I am totally agree with isalbella answer ... really  curiosity and passion are fundamental factors .. I can add also being honest and sincere, also,  to be discreet and reticent for patients'' secrets ... giving your patient the trust and contentment is super important for being a remarkable psychologist..... \nNice to meet everybody here in this course', '05 Jun ''13, 12:06', 1),
('100064030', '100064014', 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'I think you are getting at significant figures here. I''m not sure what the "official" rules are. A bit of google searching has given me sources that say there should be 3 and sources that say there should be 4 significant digits in this mean. Assuming that each of the data points in this data are implied to be 3 digits (so 0.38 actually means 0.380), then I think I prefer adding the extra digit. \nImagine you wanted the average height of me and you. Let''s say you are 6 feet tall and I''m 5 feet tall. I think it makes more sense to say that we have an average height of 5.5 feet than to try to round to one significant digit.\nRegardless, this is a good thing to be aware of! We generally do not want to imply that we know a number with more precision than we do.', '05 Jun ''13, 12:23', 0),
('100064041', '100063173', 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', 'I think this is also a study worth doing Naomi. I''d be worried that you might see an improvement in reaction times as people got better at the test, which may mean you''d see a less dramatic change (even if one exists), which means you''d need an even larger sample size to see if your treatment has an affect. \nYou are right that we need to be aware of how much of the difference that we see is due to natural variation within the population and how much is due to our treatment (in this case caffeine). If you want to learn more about this, you should take a look at Udacity''s statistics course. Lesson 12 is on ANOVA (analysis of variance) which talks a lot about this.', '05 Jun ''13, 12:39', 0),
('100064044', '100062247', 'users/100058328/bulut-bulgu', '0.262 seconds \n0.238 seconds \n0.174 seconds \n0.191 seconds', '05 Jun ''13, 12:42', 1),
('100064056', '100064045', 'users/100007518/andyatudacity', '"Weak to no correlation" is a phrase we use when we are being very careful not to be wrong :) Sometimes data looks like it has no correlation, but when you run the numbers it turns out that there actually is some VERY weak correlation. If you look about a third of the way down this page, you will see some examples of very weak correlations that--had you not seen the best-fit line--you may have been tempted to say were examples of "no correlation."', '05 Jun ''13, 12:52', 0),
