('100065182', '100064953', 'users/100067936/melissa-rice', 'I''m a mathematician, not a psychologist, but here are my musings on objective vs subjective, for what it''s worth.\nAn objective measurement is one which can be expected to have the same value (within appropriate experimental error) regardless of the observer who takes the measurement. My heart rate is not the same all the time, of course, but heart rate is an objective measure because all measurements of it taken at one point in time should be the same regardless of who (or what machine) takes the measurement. So if I get hooked up to three different machines and two nurses also take my pulse at the same time, all 5 measurements of my heart rate should be about the same (maybe 60, 61, 59, 60, 61 - we expect some small error is possible). If one machine reads 80 while the others all read 60 we assume the machine which read 80 is broken. We don''t assume that 80 is a valid opinion of my heart rate because heart rate is not subjective. It is not subject to different opinions. \nA subjective measurement would be expected to vary with the observer and or with the observation. Movie rating is subjective because different people have different opinions on the same movie and each of these is equally valid. Some of this subjectivity could be because the measurement scale is subject to interpretation. If I ask people to rate a movie on a scale 1 to 5 then there might be very different meanings implied by different people when they use the rating 2. This can be clarified by assigning meanings to the scale levels like: 1 = hated this movie, 2 = didn''t like, 3 = ok, 4 = liked, 5 = loved. This, at least, ensures that two people who each rated a movie 4 both liked, but did not love the movie. The movie rating is still subjective because I might like different movies than you. But at least we can remove the subjectivity related to a fuzzy scale.\nAsking someone to recall how many hours of homework they did last week is subjective because they may not recall properly or may be moved to overestimate out of guilt for not doing as much homework as they had wished, etc. However it seems to me if you have them log their homework hours each day you are moving closer to an objective measure, assuming you don''t think they will lie. If someone observes them and records their homework hours this would certainly be objective (assuming you can tell, by looking at them, if they are doing homework). \nSo, it seems to me that it is not the case that every self-reported measurement is subjective (or at least not equally subjective). If I record my pulse every day when I wake up that is an objective measurement. If I am asked to recall what I think my pulse might have been on prior days when I did not measure, that is subjective. Both of these might be considered self-reported. The question is whether a measurement or recording was made vs whether a person is recalling.', '06 Jun ''13, 17:08', 12),
('100065204', '100065189', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question!  Remember that the direction refers to whether or not the variables are positively or negatively correlated and the strength refers to how strong the relationship is.  So the direction in the sex and chores example is positive, this is because when the number of chores completed increases the number of sexual encounters also increases.', '06 Jun ''13, 17:42', 0),
('100065297', '100064953', 'users/100067936/melissa-rice', 'Further thoughts:\nScientific measurements of physical quantities are generally able to be done in an objective fashion. This is because the things being measured are matters of fact, not opinion. I don''t expect two different observers to each have a valid (but differing) opinion on my height. When we measure in this way there are two ways to evaluate the quality of the measurement: precision and accuracy.  \nPrecision means how finely can we measure (usually depends on the resolution of the measuring instrument). For instance: if I am measuring height to the nearest cm then a measuring stick marked off in cm increments will do and I can measure a person''s height as 180cm. If I need more precision in this measurement then I need a measuring stick marked off in mm in which case I can measure 180.3cm. Better precision.\nAccuracy means how close is the measurement to the true height. If a person is really 180.0cm high and I measure 185.354cm, this is very precise but not very accurate. Why? Perhaps my ruler is not correctly marked. Perhaps I am too short to see the ruler properly. Perhaps the ruler wasn''t vertical. Perhaps I need glasses to read the ruler properly, etc. Regardless of how precisely the ruler is marked the accuracy will not be good if I don''t use the ruler properly.\nRepeatability is also important - the degree to which you can get the same value (within the expected accuracy and precision range) from multiple measurements. If you make the measurement 10 times, what range of values do you get? Usually there''s some kind of normal distribution of the measurements and we assume (barring systemic error) that the average reading is an estimator of the true value. Repeatability does not guarantee accuracy (if the instrument is broken or the observer is not properly trained they could make a bad measurement which is bad in some repeatable way, like reading the scale wrong or the instrument maxing out). \nSome quantities are inherently subjective because they are matters of opinion, not fact. How attractive is that person? How did you like that movie, or music, or art work? These are matters of opinion. They do not have an underlying fact that we are measuring so there is no hope of anything but a subjective measurement. Seems like we mostly are not talking about these sorts of things at present.\nOther quantities are inherently objective but difficult to measure objectively. How much time did you spend on homework last week? Say you spent 12 hours. This is a fact. If we can agree on a measurable definition of what constitutes doing homework we could theoretically measure this. But we have to work hard to measure this accurately. Someone needs to watch you and be able to determine when you are doing homework and when not (pretty objective). Or you log it yourself and we hope you are truthful and log carefully (somewhat less objective). If we ask you to recall how much time you spent on homework last week, this is a much more subjective measurement, but the quantity being measured is still inherently objective (there is a certain number of hours you did actually spent on homework last week and we would know it if we had set up the proper measurement apparatus). If we want to improve the measurement we think about what can go wrong: you don''t recall properly, you lie, you have a different idea of what counts as "doing homework" than what the experimenter means, etc. Then we try to make a measurement system that addresses each problem we are concerned about.\nI would say your example (witness testimony about a crime scene) falls into this last category. There was a murderer at the crime scene and there were witnesses. These are indisputable facts. If we had cameras and DNA testing on the scene during the crime we could very objectively determine the murderer, I would think. Unless the murderer has a twin, perhaps.\nMost likely (if we are arguing about it) the witness is making a subjective measurement in fingering the defendant, but there are different degrees of subjectivity.\nIf I am standing right next to the murderer and see him commit the murder and he is very well known to me, then my "measurement" is pretty objective. Unless I''m lying for some reason. After all, do you think you would have any difficulty identifying your family or close friends in good lighting at close range? No. So this is very strongly repeatable, which makes it more like an objective measurement. But only for truthful, trained observers under ideal conditions (which means, in this case, people who also know the defendant very well, at close-range in good viewing conditions). \nIf it is dark and I don''t know the murderer and I am 2 blocks away, well, that seems rather weak. This would be a much more subjective "measurement" because it''s not likely to be very repeatable. It may be helpful to think about what would compromise accuracy and precision of such a measurement.\nThis illustrates how complex experimental design can be. The security folks have a useful idea called a "threat model". If you want to make something secure you have to decide what sort of threat you are defending against (that''s the threat model). Likewise, if you want to design a good experiment you have to envision what can go wrong and how to design the experiment to minimize that particular problem. So I think the examples given for subjective vs. objective are part of this process of understanding what sorts of problems can render experimental data less useful and then looking at how to design the experiment to reduce or avoid these problems. These experimental design principles arose out of earlier experiments that actually encountered these sorts of problems so the experimenters said, "hey, we can do it better next time if we....".\nSo it seems to me we''ve mostly been looking at things which have an objective underlying value and asking what can get in the way of measuring that value (lying, poor recall, suggestibility, bad measurement, etc) and then asking how we can design the experiment to minimize that problem. \nBut also bear in mind I am not trained in experimental design so I''m just speaking from tangential experience in science/math research. \nWhat do you think? Can a witness every be fully objective in identifying a criminal? Can we ever know if the witness is objective? For instance, can we ever know for sure if the witness may be lying? This seems to happen often enough (the witness is lying to protect his/her self or others or because threatened by the police, etc). I think objective/subjective measurement is a continuum and it''s just very complex to place any particular measurement on the continuum.', '06 Jun ''13, 19:27', 3),
