('100065864', '100063993', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Here is a little help with understanding the concept of this question, hope this helps!\n-First, when the question says that the experimental and control groups are the same, it does not mean that the exact same people that were in the control group were the exact same people in the experimental group.  Those are actually two separate groups of people.  When it says that the people are the "same," it means that they come from the same sample, and that the attributes of the two groups are relatively the same.  And when the question says that they are different, it is referring to the differences in the dependent variable.  Remember that we manipulate the independent variable and we measure the dependent variable.\nLet me give you an example of a hypothetical experiment.  Say we wanted to figure out if caffeine caused college students to sleep less over the course of a day. First we would gather a bunch of college students and ask them how much they sleep per day (lets say that the average of sleep the college students reported was 8 hours per day).  Next, we would randomly assign them to one of two groups, the control group and the experimental group.  \n***Here are are the variables:\nIndependent variable- Caffeine\nDependent variable- Sleep\nMore importantly, here is a breakdown of the groups and their characteristics so far:\nControl Group- College students that sleep an average of 8 hours per day.\nExperimental Group- College students that sleep an average of 8 hours per day.\n***As you can see, before we actually run the experiment, the groups are the same.\nNow lets run the experiment.\nNext we would give one group no caffeine (the control group), and we would give the other group caffeine (the experimental group).  After a day passed we would find out how much time people in each group slept.  After we asked both groups how much they slept, we find out that on average the control group (the group that did not receive caffeine) still slept 8 hours that day, and the experimental group (the group that received caffeine) on average reported sleeping only 6 hours that day.\nNow lets take a look at the groups after we ran the experiment and the independent variable (caffeine) was manipulated:\nControl Group- College students that slept an average of 8 hours \nExperimental Group- College students that slept an average of 6 hours \n***As you can see, now the groups are different, and the only thing that happened different between the groups was whether or not they received caffeine.  \nSo now, since the only thing that happened different between the groups was was whether or not they received caffeine, we can say that the difference between the groups was caused by the independent variable (caffeine).\nI really hope this helped because I know that part of the material can be confusing.  See you in class!', '07 Jun ''13, 13:53', 4),
