('100066217', '100064557', 'users/100004223/tung-nguyen', 'For example, suppose that we want to know if intelligence has anything to do with good grades. One way we can do is to collect the IQ and GPA of students from a large population, then spray them onto the scatter plot to see if there''s any pattern in the data. It''s very likely that we would see a straight line pointing upwards (indicating positive correlation) in the plot. Or we could say, the more intelligent a student is the better her grades are.', '08 Jun ''13, 01:09', 0),
('100066259', '100064557', 'users/100000165/andrew-cardno', 'Or we could say the higher the grades are the more intelligence they are more likely to be. But we cannot say that intelligence causes higher grades because this is observational data. It could be some other factor that causes both intelligence and higher grades. For example drinking coffee before intelligence tests and taking exams might cause both to increase (I am not saying this is true just using this as an example). If we used experimentation to establish this then we could say that (maybe just in part) that caffeine consumption is the cause of both higher intelligence and higher grades.', '08 Jun ''13, 02:44', 1),
