('100067121', '100066998', 'users/117823996/marina-42', 'Please correct me if I am wrong: I believe this experiment was contaminated because it used individuals that may be addicted to caffeine. In both groups there are people that take coffee every morning, but in the control group it was a disadvantage because all the people that "needed" caffeine to operate as a normal person (that''s what people addicted to coffee usually say, that without caffeine they are slow and zombie-like) so by not having their usual dose of caffeine they decreased the average score of their group by being slower than their non-addicted co-members of the group.\nMy point is that if we tested caffeine on people that never had or do not usually take caffeine we would get a 100% objective result and most probable we would get the same outcome: caffeine does affect and decreases the time of reaction. That''s because caffeine is a drug. If we tested some other kind of drug, less common than coffee, on people that do not take it we would be on the same situation.', '09 Jun ''13, 15:04', 0),
