('100067201', '100066442', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question!  First, a correlational study does not allow causal statements, because no independent variable has been manipulated, whereas an experimental study that manipulates the independent variable  allows, to some degree, causal statements to be made.  Researchers will use correlational studies for many different reasons!  Sometimes it is not possible to do an experimental study due to the lack of resources or ethical concerns, and other times researchers use them just to see if an experimental study is worth doing.  Hope that helps!', '09 Jun ''13, 16:35', 5),
