('100067248', '100066618', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'In a double-blind study, the researcher does not know which group is getting which treatment and the participants also do not know which treatment or group they are in. For example, if a researcher was studying a drug for decreasing anxiety by conducting a double-blind study, she would not know which participants are getting the placebo and which are getting the active drug; also, the participants do not know if they are getting the placebo or the active drug. However, the researcher will have a coding system so that when the study is over she can look to see which people were in which group. We do this to help eliminate bias or expectancy effects.', '09 Jun ''13, 18:06', 2),
