('100068291', '100064962', 'users/111260994/nick-78', 'This is a simple statistical exercise.\nMeasuring the reactions times, for each INDIVIDUAL would require several testing sessions to determine a range and an average for each participant which was not biased by lack of sleep, stress, etc.\nIf the test are then repeated once the administering of caffeine/placebo has begun, then ONLY those tests results which are OUTSIDE of the previously recorded results are of any relevance. If the results are only slightly outside the recorded range, how can you determine whether caffeine (if administered) was the actual cause?\nBy randomly selecting two separate groups of people  you can achieve a "group average", or ''mean'', which should (if the group is large enough) be almost identical, without the need to actually measure it.\n(Think ''bell curve'')\nYou can then commence the testing and compare the results.\nIf the results for the experimental group are significantly higher (has a faster mean reaction time) then you can postulate that caffeine does have an effect on reaction times.\nObviously, the larger the number of people in each group, the more accurate the results will be.', '11 Jun ''13, 10:52', 1),
('100068296', '100067954', 'users/117523005/judy-12', 'Learning a second language doesn''t involve the same processes as learning a first language, unless a child is brought up in a bi-lingual context. If someone learning a second language finds it difficult, it is absolutely not due to brain damage to Broca''s or Wernicke''s area - but if they did, then there would be some kind of aphasia in the first language too - in fact in any language. Not sure what you mean by ''alteration''. People have different talents, and different learning styles, and these may affect how easily or how quickly a second language is learnt. It''s thought that children pick up pronunciation really well, that teens are better at learning vocabulary and adults latch onto the grammar more easily, but age alone isn''t a factor.  It''s hard to pinpoint one cause for difficulty in language learning. Second language acquisition research tells us little - apart from the one factor of language aptitude - a natural (perhaps genetic?) talent for languages.', '11 Jun ''13, 11:04', 2),
('100068301', '100067931', 'users/117523005/judy-12', 'Not sure what you mean Manuel - is there such a thing as suffering from reuptake? It''s a natural thing! People with abnormal conditions such as depression might need a drug like an SSRI to restore the natural balance of neurotransmitters I guess.', '11 Jun ''13, 11:08', 0),
('100068326', '100068310', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'It''s a good question, and there''s a myth out there that humans only use 10% of their brain activity. That''s just simply not true. Your whole brain can function and works throughout various aspects of your life experiences. The only time someone''s brain is not functioning as highly as another''s is if there is impairment from injury or aberrant development. As for IQ, the wikipedia page on it is pretty good. You''ll note that during childhood there can be an increase over time, but in general IQ does not fluctuate too much over time. Remember that any IQ measurement comes with an error range; so any given person''s IQ is more of a range than a specific number. Hope this helps answer your question.', '11 Jun ''13, 11:52', 2),
('100068333', '100068325', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'It''s actually 3 billion letters (3,000,000,000) not million (in the US billion and million are distinguished differently than in other countries). And the reason we know is that we''ve sequenced virtually every one of those letters to count them. The first attempt to count was called the Human Genome Project. Now there are more human genomes being sequenced, thousands of them.', '11 Jun ''13, 11:59', 2),
