('100069468', '100068655', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question! As you mentioned, the correlations range from -1 to 1, the closer the correlation gets to either of the 1''s, the stronger it is.  And the closer the correlations get to zero, in either direction, the weaker the correlation is. If there is a negative sign in front of the number that is just indicating that there is a negative correlation, meaning that when one variable increases, the other decreases.  For example, when  temperature increases, or gets hotter, the amount of clothes people will wear will probably decrease on average, so we say there is a negative correlation between temperature and the amount of clothes people wear on average.  And when there is no sign in front of the correlation, it is indicating a positive correlation, meaning that when one variable increases, the other one does too!  For example, using temperature again, when the temperature increases, ice cream sales increase as well.  Hope that helps!', '13 Jun ''13, 00:57', 4),
('100069518', '100068325', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Glad to see you''re thinking! But don''t forget that the genome code is made up of 4 possible letters. Any given position could have one of those four letters. So to calculate the number of unique possibilities that would be 4^3,000,000,000 which is a REALLY big number! And our population isn''t even close to reaching that.\nHowever! You don''t need to have a big population to find people who are genetically identical. Just ask any twins - monozygotic twins are genetically identical because they split from the same embryo very early during development.', '13 Jun ''13, 03:29', 1),
('100069521', '100068805', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Ha, that''s a good question. I assume you mean how fast can we fix errors that ended up being recorded? It depends on the significance of the error. Obviously major content errors take priority and get done pretty quickly. Unfortunately spelling and grammar mistakes last longer before being corrected, in part because courses like Psychology are still in production and focus is still be spent of making new content. Hope this answers your question.', '13 Jun ''13, 03:36', 2),
('100069523', '100068804', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'What a great point. My background is cell and molecular biology, so I''m not primatologist, but I''m under the impression that bonobos are classified as a distinct species from Pan troglodytes. Bonobos, or pygmy chimps, are classified as Pan paniscus. Both bonobos and chimps are closely related. An interesting fact: bonobos are a highly sexual species whereas chimpanzees are a highly violent species. Humans are an interesting mix of both. For this question I just wanted to refer to one of the species (they''re both generally considered ''chimps''), but thanks for bringing this point up.', '13 Jun ''13, 03:42', 4),
