('100069850', '100069749', 'users/118410427/david-j', 'Hello Julien,\nWe still evolve. As a matter of fact we could not stop to evolve, because it is a natural process and we are a apart of nature. But you have to notice that evolution needn''t to have positive effects. Even if we evolve into couch-potatoes, the process is still called evolution. Furthermore you have to notice, that evolution is a really slow process.  Since the agricultural revolution, that happened around 12.000 years ago, our genome hasn''t change significantly, whereas our daily life changed radically.\nBecause of the little speed of the evolution, we hardly notice this process.\nBest regards,\nDavid J.', '13 Jun ''13, 16:25', 7),
('100069885', '100069588', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Ooo, that''s an interesting one. Remember, if brown is dominant, someone with brown eyes could have one brown allele and one green allele. If two parents like this make children, then they could each pass a green allele down even though they both have brown eyes. The child would end up with green eyes: different from both parents! Of course the green allele came from somewhere, likely the grandfather who had green eyes. So technically, the gene didn''t jump generations but the TRAIT jumped generations. Make sense?', '13 Jun ''13, 17:13', 5),
