('100071227', '100069749', 'users/117588655/julirn', 'Hello David!\nThanks for the answer, but still, I am not convinced you are (completely) right. \nIt has been pointed out that natural selection is one main point of evolution. As human beings, we have made many things that exclude us from being selected naturally - take me, for an example: my eyes are bad. I have to wear glasses to see properly. Without them, I would likely have died some thousand years ago since I would not have been able to hunt or to fight successfully- but today, all I have to do is to put my glasses on. Hence, my bad genes do not become extinct any more and I will pass them to the next generation (and have likely, my daughter has bad eyes, too). \nI am sure we DO evolve in some way, but how does my point fit in your answer - are there now simply other selection mechanisms?\nBest regards,\nJulien Caussin', '15 Jun ''13, 16:57', 4),
