('100071306', '100070542', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'It''s a fair question and I want to be clear: in the example we gave here in the video, YES, brown eyes would always be dominant to blue. HOWEVER, eye color is slightly more complicated than what we showed in the video; in real life eye color is controlled by multiple genes, not just one, so it''s not as simple as brown always being dominant over blue. If you''re interested in the whole story about eye color, the wiki page is quite good, and I recommend you check it out here:  \nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eye_color\n\nIn humans, brown eyes result from a relatively high concentration of\nmelanin in the stroma of the iris, which causes light of both shorter\nand longer wavelengths to be absorbed. Dark brown eyes are dominant in\nhumans and in many parts of the world, it is nearly the only iris\ncolor present. Dark pigment of brown eyes is most common in East Asia,\nSoutheast Asia, South Asia, West Asia, Oceania, Africa, Americas, etc.\nas well as parts of Eastern Europe and Southern Europe.', '15 Jun ''13, 19:48', 0),
