('100071354', '100069749', 'users/117578412/greg-feist', 'Great discussion on a very fascinating and difficult question. I like how the answers progressed quite intelligently. My take is that we are still evolving but perhaps in slower and different ways than 100''s of thousands of years ago--for the simply reason that evolution by natural and sexual selection work fasted in isolated populations and humans are no longer isolated from one another. But it would be really interesting to get hard data from group genetics and look at this. If any one has a reference or link they''d like to post, I''d love to see it. \n~Greg Feist (Instructor)', '15 Jun ''13, 21:30', 3),
('100071373', '100064960', 'users/115381911/johnny-43', 'in a Auditory Evoke Potential a Tick noise is given to one ear and recorded the time to get  the brain time in m/s  is   with electrodes place in the head.  This method will see Physiological reaction time.  5 picks way are trace in screen of the system.', '15 Jun ''13, 22:14', 0),
('100071400', '100066063', 'users/100012341/jeff-scott', 'The dog salivating is definitely behavioral psychology, hands down.\nThe professors seem to be coming in and answering some of these skeptical inquiries with blas authoritarian responses that they have the answers, which is not helpful.\nIn this case perhaps they will focus on the "why" aspect  of this, parsing "why" to mean something different than normally expected.\nThese sorts of questions where one must start going through every possible answer permutation to find the "correct" one is at best an experiment to see if we have the patience  rather than any genuine test of understanding. But these random guessing questions are in a lot of other udacity classes as well. I doubt there is any evidence that this approach, of demanding we give an arbitrary response rather than a correct one, is sound pedagogically. I could be convinced though that it is an effective test of whether we will submit to authority and accept what we are told is the answer. The willingness to do so is likely a desirable aspect in evaluating a potential employee, which we know is udacity''s current business model - to use the system to watch how well we "master" the material, and sell that information.\nI guess that''s OK, and actually I wouldn''t mind if the classes had better content so that one learned something rather than was "trained" to mimic the expected answers to get the food pellet.', '15 Jun ''13, 23:29', 0),
('100071405', '100061918', 'users/100012341/jeff-scott', 'Behavioral deals with stimulus-response, which is something that is learned non-cognitively. One learns to avoid  touching hot stoves after burning their fingers because of behavioral psychology.\nCognitive fundamentally involves cognition, or higher thinking abilities. It is about thought processes.\nWhen you avoid touching the stove because you were burned before it''s not because you reasoned that hot things burned, it''s because you know they are from having received pain in the past.\nIf you avoid the stove because you somehow learned through teaching that hot things burn, that can be cognitive psychology. Also note perhaps you believe that warm things, or fuzzy things burn as well. That''s not a correct belief, but it is a cognition you have, and so could be covered here as well.\nThe class is weird and different from a normal psych class in that it doesn''t really define these things adequately for a non-specialist to answer the quizzes other than through informed guessing.', '15 Jun ''13, 23:41', 0),
('100071509', '100071221', 'users/117588655/julirn', 'Hello!\nIt does. Thanks!\nBest regards,\nJulien Caussin', '16 Jun ''13, 05:18', 0),
