('100071632', '100064815', 'users/100012341/jeff-scott', 'There are lots of interesting things to discuss with these sorts of examples. The study discussed is of a common sort one sees reported in magazines and newspapers, making a claim that high fives cause happiness, and pointing out that it was a randomized study done with a control group and an independent and dependent variables. Not blind in this case, but such studies, not being correlational observation studies, are often referred to as "gold standard" in research and much made of the results. However, we also know that results reported even under these conditions are often wrong. For example, Ioannidis famously showed that more than half of research results published in peer reviewed journals are false (see "Why Most Published Research Findings Are False"), with results much more likely to be false for things like pharmaceutical studies where the organization sponsoring the study stands to benefit financially from a particular result.\nA question one may wish to consider is whether smiles in a work environment are equivalent to measuring happiness. Another would be to define what one means by happiness. Is it the number of smiles or something else. Consider for example a sexually hostile work environment where an authority figure with power, such as a boss, or even a very respected colleague who would never be fired, starts slapping coworkers not on the hand, but on the ass, and it is known that those who complain about this are seen as troublemakers and fired. This situation at work was very common in the US until the 1990s when fear of sexual harassment lawsuits caused some reform. But it still exists in the work environment in many cultures. Does a smile from a coworker after receiving their ass-slap indicate they are truly happy, for however we have defined happiness in the study? Or perhaps it instead indicates seething resentment. Perhaps the smiling coworker is actually as a result of the slap contemplating either suicide or strangling their coworker/boss one night when no one else is there. To assume that smiles equate or even correlate with happiness, whatever happiness is, would have to be demonstrated in a proper study and quantified. Unfortunately finding flaws such as these, where conclusions are based on untested and unsubstantiated assumptions, is quite common in research studies. Or fortunately, because it is exceptionally valuable to be able to identify such flaws which are endemic, and realize that the vast majority of claimed scientific results that are constantly trotted out to support some political or financial agenda are absolute bunk.\nOf course it will be said this is an intro course and things can not be covered in depth, but intro courses are the most common exposure college students have to many fields. Focusing on the most common ways in which most research studies are flawed and invalid would be extremely useful and of immense practical value, in the same way that studies of how businesses fail are much more useful than studies of how businesses succeed.', '16 Jun ''13, 12:01', 0),
('100071752', '100064953', 'users/100012341/jeff-scott', 'From the examples given, you can see some of the problems with this categorization.\nThe word "objective" is always presentedas something more right and accurate and scientific and mathematical and less biased than things described as "subjective".\nHere we see though - objective is given as when the "researcher", the person with authority, a degree, and some sort of grant or funding, writes down in a log how many hours someone watches TV. But if the person themselves writes it down it''s called "subjective". This is not really a traditional definition of the word. It''s more of an attempt to paint that which is written down by a credentialled academic as "the truth", but that which a layman writes down, as "subjective and unreliable", even when it is exactly the same information. It''s basically an attempt to use language to paint one group''s opinions, measurements and judgments as more reliable.\nIt''s very similar to the way that the histories of non-white peoples are considered unreliable, unverified and false, but a history written down by a white person, like Julius Caesar''s Gallic Wars, is considered to be a true and accepted history, evidence of proof that things claimed in the history were real and happened. Even though the only  difference is whether the person reporting is white (an "objective" report according to western academics) or non-white (a subjective mythology, considered untrue according to western academics.)\nConsider the current practice of psychological diagnosis. People are often evaluated according to a diagnostic checklist to determine if they are "depressed". Then a treatment is prescribed, which doesn''t differ from the treatment of many other "disorders". If the person merely says they are depressed or are not depressed, that is considered unreliable and subjective, but an outside observer with a checklist, which has never really been validated, is considered objective. If a non-licensed practitioner gives the checklist though it is not considered a valid diagnosis. The only criteria for objective in much of the field is not whether it is objective according to traditional definitions, but whether the authority making the pronouncement is part of the existing power structure.\nWe might also ask, if we are to consider a person''s self logging of their own experiences to be subjective, what should be said of a researcher''s logging of his own experimental data, particularly should professional or financial advantage be likely to follow from getting certain results. Would it not be better to use a third party observer, one who does not benefit from the results of the study, to be the one to log all the data. It would probably be more accurate in the same way that self measured and reported weight figures are less accurate than those measured and reported by another party even if both used the same scale.', '16 Jun ''13, 15:24', 2),
