('100072273', '100071680', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'As with all studies, we need to operationally define each construct.  In this case, the construct was happiness, and in order to conduct the study we operationally defined happiness in terms of smiles.  There are always things to consider (e.g. do smiles really indicate happiness), which is why researchers often try to tackle studies using different methodologies.  It is very unlikely that a study will be perfect, and in fact, most are not.  But it is through observations such as your own that studies are often improved!', '17 Jun ''13, 13:14', 4),
('100072282', '100071601', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'SO many good questions and all at once! Eye pigmentation is the result of the pigment, melanin, deposited by special pigmentation cells called melanocytes. Because humans originated in Africa, where the suns rays are the harshest, melanocytes produced lots of melanin (pigment) to make dark skin which protects the body''s cells from DNA-damaging UV radiation. These same cells with lots of melanin make brown eyes. As humans moved out of Africa to climates with less sunlight, there was selection for less melanin so that enough of the suns rays could get in the skin to help make vitamin D (one of the good effects of the sun for you!). Eyes began to lighten as skin lightened, but currently there''s no evidence to suggest that there was any natural selection pressure for differently colored eyes; just differently colored skin that also affected the eyes. However, sexual selection has been shown to favor lightly colored eyes. In other words, as lighter eyes appeared, humans tended to prefer the lighter colors like amber, green, and blue.\nThat said, there are reports that having differently colored eyes can result in different abilities, though the research is still ongoing. Lighter colored eyes (blue) are at more risk of macular degeneration. Darker eyed people tend to be better at reactive-type tasks (football and boxing) and light eyed people tend to be better at self-paced tasks (golfing). Though this data has been disputed. \nhttp://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/health/20real.html?_r=1&amp;;', '17 Jun ''13, 13:26', 2),
