('100072529', '100065000', 'users/120642982/sheaeugene', 'I''ve thought about this question many times over the last few years. I believe have a unique perspective on it having raised 5 kids, 2 which were biologically mine and three which were not (but I know the biological father). Some traits and tendencies, even facial expressions seem to sometimes be a genetic factor but at other times it can be hard to accept there is any relation at all because they are so different.\nMy father was an alcoholic, and my youngest biological son (now 22) is also. When he drinks -especially when he drinks, it is shocking how much he reminds me of my own father when he was drunk even though the two met only briefly. This experience certainly seems to say a lot for nature. On the other hand, my youngest step-son is remarkably like me in many ways, and very unlike his own father except for some physical features. This convinces me that nurture can often trump nature.\nI suspect also -based on my own experience and research- that there is some third category beyond nurture and nature, (but not untouched by either) which can heavily influence our personality and behavior. Science doesn''t seem to have much to say here, or doesn''t care to, but I am curious enough I guess to keep asking these questions.', '17 Jun ''13, 20:22', 2),
('100072541', '100072433', 'users/100082074/katy-3', 'Short answer is yes. Most headphones have an uneven frequency response at very high frequencies. This means that they would not accurately reproduce input sounds of high frequencies with the correct power (volume) output.\nEverything else, including the computer, its sound card, the encoding from YouTube and the encoding used to generate the original video can muddle the sound as well. This tends not to be a problem for the majority of the range of human hearing - all the hardware described is generally designed for humans to hear normal sounds after all - but may be an issue for these high frequencies.', '17 Jun ''13, 21:22', 3),
('100072543', '100064953', 'users/100067936/melissa-rice', 'Certainly I agree fundamentally with your observations. \nIt is abundantly clear to me that colonialism, imperialism, sexism, racism, authoritarianism, provincialism, and many other bad things are still very prevalent in the world and this saddens me a great deal. \nI also think that Western science is often arrogant, dogmatic, authoritarian, and rigid, which is completely contrary to what the scientific method teaches. Alas, scientists are also human and may be subject to the same failings as other humans, despite their scientific training. \nFinally, I think there are some grave problems with the way we fund and conduct research and disseminate this information and it would be very interesting to have a longer conversation about how to fix this. Perhaps in another thread?\nI would also like to argue that good experimental design, data collection, and analysis are absolutely crucial to ending up with useful scientific conclusions and these issues can be subtle and are not always reducible to something like politics, paternalism, or authoritarianism although they may often be intermixed with these. \nI think a good starting point is to look at the etymology of these terms. Objective refers to a property of the object, say, the length of a movie, and hence should be measured the same by all observers. The movie is 2 hours long regardless of who watches it. \nSubjective refers to a property of the subject, say the rating of a movie, which is a property of the observer (the subject) not a property of the movie (the object). Different people can be expected to give different ratings of the same movie. Perception of movie length is also subjective because we are asking how long the subject felt the movie to be (a property of the subject) not how long the movie actually was (a property of the object). \nBoth objective and subjective questions may be useful and interesting to ask. In both cases we hope to answer the questions as accurately as possible, but the experimental design, data collection, and ways to acheive accuracy may be different.\nAn objective question about movie length might be: Has the average length of movies increased since 1975? To achieve an accurate answer we would need to establish a method of getting a representative sampling of movies for each year and then compute the average length of the movies in each year since 1975. An intuitive way to answer the question would be to graph this data as a time series and observe the trend. The more objective way to answer the question is to use statistical methods to estimate the probability that such a trend could result from random data. \nSo the objective/subjective issue appears in several ways here. First, the data itself represents an objective measurement (movie length). Second, the way we analyze the data can be subjective or objective. If the trend in movie length over time is not strong then different people can look at the graph and some may see an increasing trend and some may not. For this reason, using inferential statistics is more objective because once we all agree on the specific method and the level of confidence then everyone should get the same answer from the same data. And the answer would look something like this perhaps: there is a 99% chance that movies have increased in average length since 1975 (or another way to say it is that there is only a 1% chance that movie length is not increasing but we just happened to get a non-representative sample). In this paradigm we increase accuracy by increasing sample size so that we can increase confidence level and by using techniques for acheiving representative samples.\nIn contrast we can ask an inherently subjective question about the same data (movie length) by asking "Do you think that average movie length has increased since 1975?" This is a perfectly valid question but we are asking about peoples'' perception of movie length, not about the actual length of the movies. So it is subjective (and subjective is not meant as a value judgement). We know that perception of the passage of time is not particularly accurate in humans but depends on mental state (when we are bored time appears to pass more slowly than when we are interested or excited). And because it is a subjective question the experiment is trying to answer then it is entirely appropriate to ask people a subjective question about their perception (rather than measuring actual length).\nSo both of these questions about movie length are valid and interesting but the experimental designs are not interchangeable. We can''t get a good estimate of actual movie length by asking people how long the movie seemed to be (the boring movies may have length overestimated and the exciting movies may have length underestimated). So how do we know if movies are getting longer over time or just more boring? This would be a poorly designed study because we can''t have confidence that it answers the question we posed about actual movie length. \nIn the same way, the second question (about perceived movie length) cannot be answered with objective data about actual movie length. It is an inherently subjective question and needs a subjective question to be asked as a part of the experimental design.\nSo it''s not that objective data is always better than subjective data. But they are different and require different experimental designs. In each case we should be clear and precise about what we want to know, and design the experiment to find that out as accurately as we can.\nIn the example of asking about homework time, if we want to know about students'' perception of how much time they are spending on homework then we should ask them (this is inherently a subjective question so we collect subjective data to answer it). \nIf we want to know about actual time spent on homework (an objective question) then it will be more accurate to have students log their time each day than to guess at the end of the week. This is not insulting the students, just using common sense to improve the quality of the data collected. \nThere may be situations where logging is not going to be accurate enough. Suppose you are studying a population of high-school students who are under court order to spend 10 hours a week doing homework in order to avoid being sent to juvenile detention and you want to know if this is effective at improving grades. Having the students log their own hours is not likely to be a good experimental design in this case. A better design might be an after-school program where attendence is taken and study help offered. \nThis could be interpreted as a judgement against the students (these students are bad people and they will lie) or it could be viewed as a recognition that experimental variables need to be controlled to get good data. For instance, possibly these students are from difficult living situations where they may not have the skills or opportunity to study effectively at home (not their fault, perhaps, but an aspect of their reality which effects whether they study and how effectively). Also, it is human nature to lie to avoid punishment, especially punishment which is perceived as undeserved. So whether we want to label such lying as "bad" is really not relevant to the experiment. But if the logging of homework time is not accurate then the data collected will be garbage and the study will be worthless (or worse, misleading). From such a poorly-designed study we might erroneously conclude that these students are not intelligent because even if you force them to study 10 hours a week their grades still do not improve. Perhaps what was really happening is that they didn''t actually study because their home-life did not permit it or because they don''t have good study skills and aren''t able to study effectively even if they put in the seat-time. \nSo good experimental design is critical and you can''t get a good experimental design by ignoring the reality of the population you study. Unfortunately, just about any legitimate experimental design technique or scientific model can be twisted and used to evil purposes, just as perfectly fine fountain pens can be used to sign treaties we don''t intend to keep. It doesn''t mean we should stop using fountain pens or scientific method or good experimental design technique.\nTo some extent, the peer-reviewed research system provides a partial remedy for such evil uses of science by putting out detailed information about the experiment so that right-minded persons can point out the flaws in design, data collection, and analysis. Sadly, societies can hold their prejudices deeply so even this sensible system is not a cure-all. After all, the U.S. Declaration of Independence says "all men are created equal" and it has taken us over 200 years (and still counting) to fully understand what the word "all" means in this context, despite the fact that the same sentence of the same document asserts that this fact is supposed to be self-evident.', '17 Jun ''13, 21:31', 1);
