('100073026', '100069584', 'users/100047875/tiago-santos', 'I would then humbly make a suggestion to the organizers of the course. Drop this lesson. If there isn''t any way to show that knowing about soma and dendrites will help us understand how people think and behave, then there is not much use for us to study this in, as you said, an introductory course.\nPsychology is fascinating. Unlike you, I have no formal education, but I did read a thing or two. I can think of so many other things to teach if I were trying to give someone the only contact to rigorous psychology he would have, or if I were trying to engage people on becoming psychologists themselves. Maybe destroy the most pervasive myths - as this book http://www.amazon.com/Great-Myths-Popular-Psychology-Misconceptions/dp/1405131128 does so well - maybe give a general impression on how genes and environment shape behavior - as Pinker''s "The Blank Slate" does so brilliantly. Perhaps by showing what is wrong with the most visible face of psychology - clinical - as Robyn Dawes does in "House of Cards".\nIn any case, I could not help but think of Richard Feyman''s lesson on how knowing the name of something and knowing something:\nhttp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=05WS0WN7zMQ', '18 Jun ''13, 14:50', 0),
