('100073799', '100073313', 'users/117523005/judy-12', 'Yes, I thought too that to only offer Piaget''s model of cognitive development was limited, and it would have been useful to place him in a historical perspective. I believe also a simple critique of Piaget would be useful. His experimental procedures weren''t that rigorous and so the famous conservation experiment has been largely discredited as belonging to a particular age range. Adults also fail this test!  Also, for example, children in primary (elementary) school are capable of ''simple'' formal operations through guided science experiments in class. They are also able to ''idealise'' and so on. And the use of fMRI technology shows that the adolescent brain development stage can go on to our early 20s, whereas Piaget proposed a human was cognitively mature around the age of 16. The work of Vygotsky is interesting - development is seen as a socially mediated phenomenon, but Piaget did only classical lab work, with no social aspect. Could go on but better stop here - it''s a huuuuge subject!', '19 Jun ''13, 14:43', 3),
