('100074112', '100073918', 'users/100017797/peter-mccarron', 'Peter, this is a great question (and apologies if what is wrtten below is alrady known to you). The lectures are covering a lot of ground while at the same time trying to keep matters as simple as possible.  So, it has not been explained that if randomization worked properly - which it should have done if the procedure was correct and the size of the study group was sufficientlly large, then the intervention (caffeine) and control (decaffinated) groups will be similar in terms of both so-called known confounders, e.g. sex, age, socioeconomic bacground/eduction, and  - very imporantly - unknown confounders. In other words, say there is a factor X, as yet undiscovered, which is associated with reaction time, it does not matter that this has not been - and by definition cannot be - measured, for the number of study participants with factor X will be balanced between the two groups, so the only difference will be exposure to caffeine/no exposue to caffeine. \nHowever, say you wanted to investigate the effect of caffeine on CHANGE in reaction times, but not absolute reaction times per se, then your design is appropriate.\nI hope this is helpful - I assume it will be covered in later sessions.', '19 Jun ''13, 21:22', 4),
