('100075026', '100074553', 'users/117578412/greg-feist', 'That is an interesting question and observation. I can say that I know of no research on that particular topic. Sexual orientation is a complex process and one that is influenced by both biological and environmental factors--nature and nurture once again. But also understand that as we know from epigenetics, things that are genetic are NOT fixed. Environment can turn on and off when and how genes get expressed. Interestingly, there is some research that sexual orientation is somewhat more under genetic influence for males than females (Bailey et al 2000; Demir &amp; Jackson 2005; Rahman, 2005).\nGreat question!! Keep it up. \n~Greg Feist\nBailey, M. J., Dunne, M. P., &amp; Martin, N.\nG. (2000). Genetic and environment effects\non sexual orientation and its correlates in an\nAustralian twin sample. Journal of Personality\nand Social Psychology, 78, 524536.\nDemir, E., &amp; Dickson, B. J. (2005). fruitless\nsplicing specifi es male courtship behavior in\nDrosophila. Cell, 121, 785794\nRahman, Q. (2005). The neurodevelopment\nof human sexual orientation. Neuroscience\nand Biobehavioral Reviews, 29, 10571066.', '21 Jun ''13, 10:30', 3),
('100075029', '100074868', 'users/117578412/greg-feist', 'Great question and one that is fascinating to think about. Here is what we wrote about this in our Intro book. Note the fMRI findings and the fascinating finding that painkillers like Tylenol actually relieve EMOTIONAL pain too!: \n"Being rejected hurts. In fact, social exclusion creates physical pain. In one study on the neural\nbasis for social pain, participants were brought into a lab with an fMRI scanner and were told they\nwould be involved in an electronic ball tossing game called Cyberball (Eisenberger et al., 2003;\nMasten et al., 2009). Once inside the scanner, they could see, on a screen, a Cyberball game that\nwas apparently in progress between two other research participants in scanners in diff erent rooms.\nUnknown to the participant, there were no other people playing the game. After watching the others\nplay for a few throws, the participant joined in. For a while, the three players continued playing\nCyberball together. After seven throws, the other players stopped throwing the ball to the participant\nand resumed their game. In eff ect, the participant was left out, as Thalia had been. Participants\nreported being upset about their exclusion. Whats more, the fMRI scans showed activation of brain\ncircuitry involved in physical pain, especially those areas that are involved with how unpleasant pain\nfeels. Indeed, this kind of social pain can be relieved by painkillers like Tylenol (DeWall et al., 2010)\nand may aff ect endocrine systems that support social connection (Maner et al., 2010). Also, people\nwho are more sensitive to physical pain are more sensitive to the pain of rejection, and these diff erences\nmay have a genetic basis (Eisenberger et al., 2006; Way, Taylor, &amp; Eisenberger, 2009)." \n    Feist &amp; Rosenberg, 2012, p. 548. \nCheck out some of the references if you have access to them. I hope this helps. \n~Greg Feist', '21 Jun ''13, 10:39', 6),
