('100075229', '100073836', 'users/113783970/andy-chin-peng', 'Please note that many people in other parts of the world don''t watch this twilight saga thing. I had to look it up and its about vampires and were wolves. The vampires don''t breathe and its a wonder where they get their energy from if they don''t have oxygen to burn. And werewolves when they change from human forms, their total mass increases. Einstein would have been puzzled where all those mass came from without any huge energy sources being absorbed or discharged when they changed back to human form. I wonder which is the more unstable form though.', '21 Jun ''13, 16:41', 0),
('100075251', '100072456', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'I''ll concur with Jeff''s thorough explanation with minor point to the questioner: identical twins are a natural example of individuals who are genetically identical. Of course they came from the same sperm and egg (thus the same mother and father) whereas in these mice experiments there were different mothers and fathers (but they are all so inbred that they are virtually genetically identical like twins).', '21 Jun ''13, 17:15', 2),
('100075255', '100074938', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'You''re so right, Mostafa. This will be corrected in the instructors'' notes until the video can be modified.', '21 Jun ''13, 17:29', 1),
('100075256', '100073331', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Right - remember, that the environment can influence which genes are turned on and turned off in any of your cells. But only changes in your germ cells (also known as sex cells) will get passed on to the next generation.', '21 Jun ''13, 17:32', 2),
('100075259', '100072686', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Thanks for pointing that out, Marcus, but for this lesson the goal was to stay away from the chemistry. It is true that DNA building blocks are deoxynucleotides and RNA building blocks are nucleotides. It is generally acceptable to use ''nucleotide''  as a general reference to nucleic acids.', '21 Jun ''13, 17:36', 1),
('100075262', '100072705', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Remember that when we''re counting genomic information we normally separate ''unique'' vs. ''total''. Plants are well-known for being polyploid, or having many copies of their chromosomes. So although a plant''s ''total'' genome may be really large, looking at just the ''unique'' (or haploid) genome it would be much less.\nSo in your example, you''d need to find the haploid genomes for each species and compare. I don''t have those numbers handy and can''t seem to easily google them...', '21 Jun ''13, 17:44', 0),
('100075267', '100073933', 'users/111495789/corina', 'EXCELLENT PRESENTATION, INTERACTIVE, EASY TO UNDERSTAND.\nTHANK YOU', '21 Jun ''13, 17:51', 7),
('100075294', '100073933', 'users/115226568/lauren-castellano', 'Thanks, we love the feedback! We had a lot of fun with that lesson and are happy to see you are enjoying it.', '21 Jun ''13, 18:38', 3),
('100075387', '100073352', 'users/117942111/sonal-4', 'With my parents, it was a little different. My dad got married when he was almost 30 and my mom got married when she was 20. There is a really big age difference between them. It is different from what I want in my marriage and when I want to get married. I would like to get married in my mid 20''s and would also like a partner who is around the same age as me or having a year or two gap between us is fine also. There is a shift in the age people get married because of society and how everyone perceives themselves. Some people like to wait to get married or not get married at all because they have way to much fun with their friends and being single. But others get tired of being with friends all the time, and they want someone who will always be there and share their life with. In my opinion, it all depends on the person and how they view their life. One of the main things that I look for in a marriage when I do get married in the future, is love, honesty, happiness, communication and being financially stable. I want to be able to support myself and maybe even my kids, and find a suitable husband as well that can do the same for me and our kids.', '21 Jun ''13, 22:09', 3),
('100075400', '100073373', 'users/117942111/sonal-4', 'Yes I think its a similar process, trying to accept the fact that a loved one will soon not be with you anymore.', '21 Jun ''13, 22:25', 0),
('100075447', '100073950', 'users/117890761/julienne', 'Sooo what''s the answer?', '22 Jun ''13, 00:04', 2),
('100075483', '100073373', 'users/115802110/osei', 'I believe that the steps are the same in that this process is exhibited during the impending death of a loved one. The process that would come after a loved-one has passed might be avoidance and anger/depression and then acceptance. Whether using the emotional or rational mind we cannot bargain with the fact that a loved one is deceased and cannot return. We may regret their passing and not spending more time with them, not saying the things that they''d wished that they''d said or not trying harder to forge that relationship deeper, but these are a different set of processes for grieving.', '22 Jun ''13, 02:15', 0),
('100075485', '100073341', 'users/100047065/jeyram-jadenthradevan', 'since brain is involved in this situation, why CNS is not part of it? correct me if i am wrong', '22 Jun ''13, 02:17', 1),
('100075502', '100073373', 'users/119698652/kaz', 'We feel and grow through the exact same stages. We suffer the most, in fact sometimes the acceptance  sometimes is not present in my opinion.', '22 Jun ''13, 03:27', 1),
('100075503', '100073352', 'users/117354100/deepthi-4', 'In my opinion priorities and and responsibilities are the two main factors that influence the age at which people decide to get married. People yet to be married may have reservations if they perceive life after marriage as restrictive while others may look forward to challenges and the beginning of something new. What is to say the average age of marriage may not go down again in a few decades time? May be people will start establishing themselves earlier and would want to marry early. At what age one marries might matter much less than whom one marries. That said, in my opinion after the age of 21 it is completely subjective and based on circumstances and situations in ones life that dictates the age at which they get married.', '22 Jun ''13, 03:30', 1),
('100075514', '100067009', 'users/121895134/de-wet', 'When will the next semester start and how to do you prepare for these courses? This is a first for me', '22 Jun ''13, 04:25', 1),
('100075686', '100074350', 'users/114334914/angel-es', 'Victoria, a correct answer would be:\n"Formal operational"', '22 Jun ''13, 13:10', 1),
('100075689', '100075363', 'users/114334914/angel-es', 'Monique, "Formal operational" is accepted as valid answer.', '22 Jun ''13, 13:18', 0),
('100075690', '100073272', 'users/114334914/angel-es', 'My guess is that implies no warm hug for mummy, as being ignored.', '22 Jun ''13, 13:22', 0),
('100075717', '100073352', 'users/100113949/ahmad-5', 'My parents were married in the mid 1950s when my father was 30 and my mother was 16. I think every case is unique but in general people used to get married at younger age and on average have more kids perhaps because life was simpler. \nI''m 45 and I got married at the age of 31 and my wife was 26. We now have 4 kids and they are the joy of my life. Given the current economic and social conditions, I seem to believe the mid 20s is a good age for marriage for both sexes.', '22 Jun ''13, 14:05', 2),
('100075799', '100073352', 'users/117588655/julirn', 'Hello!\nMy parents married in the 80s. It seems to be quite seldom, but I married my wife aged 24 (i am male), which is quite early in Germany and earlier than my parents did - my father was 31 and my mother 27. \nI think there is a shift to get married with an higher age in Germany because of economic reasons. Aged 24, I was working full-time with a job that was well paid, and in the early 2000s, this was not a matter of course. There has been (and still is) a great uncertainity in my generation; and what is more: an aversion to make commitments! For me, the decision to marry my wife was because I felt it was right, but the IDEAL age to marry is probably dependent as well of oneself as of the society you live in. \nHow is it in your home countries? \nBest regards,\nJulien Caussin', '22 Jun ''13, 16:39', 1),
('100075807', '100073373', 'users/114553671/jeannette-4', 'I think basically it is the same. But I think it also depends upon the age of the person passing and what happened before. If someone dies young, then I think there is more anger. My Mother died at the age of 81 and we accepted in much better than when my sister died at age 45. My father is age 86 and I think it is harder to watch his decline than it was to see my Mother die. I think it depends upon the circumstances of the person that has died or is dying and how much death you have been through. I have processed each one differently with each death I have experienced. I also do animal rescue so we see animals die - this is always hard too. I guess I have experienced so much death that now it seems fairly natural process but it still sucks and hurts. Even those this might not be part of the formal operational process, I believe in an after life so I believe we will have a great party when I get there.', '22 Jun ''13, 16:51', 1),
('100075811', '100073105', 'users/117588655/julirn', 'Hello!\nI don''t know why, but my personal guess is that shy men have trouble to get to know a potential partner. Shy women, on the other hand, are more likely to make contact with a potential partner than shy men; and might be less carrer - centered and therefore get children earlier than their extroverted female counterparts. \nPlease do not call me a chauvinist; I have described only what I think I see whitout validation of it!\nBest regards, \nJulien Caussin', '22 Jun ''13, 16:53', 3),
('100075821', '100074995', 'users/117588655/julirn', 'Hello!\nThis might of course be, but remember that it was said that only "most" people go through the stages. Also one point might be that many people rediscover ther religiousity faced with their own certain death. And it is not said with who the "bargaining" is, it has not to be with a divinity. An atheist might also say: "If I survive I will quit smoking and exercise more regularly"!\nBest regards,\nJulien Caussin', '22 Jun ''13, 17:06', 3),
('100075895', '100075847', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'Great question!  Experimental studies allow us to draw causal inferences, correlational studies only allow us to determine relationships.  Here is an example of finding different levels of the independent variable:\nSay if we wanted to test the effects of different drug dosages on a sample.\nIf we have one group get 0mg/kg of mdma, another group get 100mg/kg of mdma, and another group get 200mg/kg of mdma. Our independent variable would be drug dosage, and there would be 3 levels.  Hope that helps!', '22 Jun ''13, 19:37', 0),
('100075897', '100075728', 'users/116520495/steven-205', 'This video may help you identify the answer.\nhttps://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-ps001/l-217096854/m-216319942\nHope that helps!', '22 Jun ''13, 19:39', 1),
('100075926', '100073352', 'users/120224010/omar-78', 'My father got married at 26, my mom got married at 24.\nI don''t think I would follow them simply because I wanna travel, I wanna discover different career opportunities and I wanna discover myself more, before choosing a country and a job and a place where to settle.\nThe shift in the age of which people marry is related to the cultural differences, religious ones and to the economics and mentalities of a certain period of time, or a certain country or population.\nI will be ready to marry the day I will feel happy in my job, having enough resources (money) and not seeing marriage as a "stop" of freedom but as the beginning of a new one.', '22 Jun ''13, 20:27', 1),
('100075936', '100073373', 'users/117934169/karthik-44', 'Though the five stages advised by Ross applies to one''s own death or loved one''s demise, I guess it does apply even on situations like job loss or rejection or failure during exams.  In few cases, the acceptance and depression in those situations might lead someone to a suicide.', '22 Jun ''13, 20:40', 1);
INSERT INTO `respuesta` (`idAnswer`, `idPost`, `idUser`, `textAnswer`, `dateAnswer`, `votesAnswer`) VALUES
('100075946', '100073352', 'users/118494555/bingyu', 'M y parents got married when they were 24 and 26.  As for me , I think I will get married late ,maybe after 30 and I am quiet enjoy single life .There is also another reason that I think it''s little difficult for  me to communicate with boys cause I am often shy . Most of time ,I choose to stay alone and I like this ,but I still have the dream that to marry with someone and have a happy family. The shift ,I think   the modern life that office work takes us most of time and also the indifference between people , it little difficult for us to make true friends and have relationships with other. And also I think education is  important ,the more we required ,the more we realized and also the more we confused. The main reason for me ,it''s must be love and responsibility.  Both of us want to contribute a happy family together. When I meet my destiny husband, there must be some special feeling in my heart.', '22 Jun ''13, 21:02', 1),
('100075953', '100075562', 'users/117578412/greg-feist', 'Ignore that. That is not meaningful or important. I am not sure where you are getting this text, but it doesn''t make much sense. \n~Dr. Feist', '22 Jun ''13, 21:10', 0),
('100075991', '100073352', 'users/119901270/benjamin-159', 'My parents were in their early thirties when they got married. I would think that the ideal time to get married would be when I have a stable financial situation, regardless of age. It is foolish for one to get married just out of college and in debt, considering that the average cost of a marriage is $25,000 (http://www.costofwedding.com/). An age shift could be due to such factors as war and the economy. If I recall, the graph showed that the biggest dip in marriage age happened after WWII, right around the age of veterans at the time. Perhaps those who survived felt that life was finite and fleeting because of seeing so many other people their age die and felt an urgency to get married.', '22 Jun ''13, 23:07', 1),
('100075996', '100074995', 'users/119901270/benjamin-159', 'As an atheist who has had to deal with death, I can say that bargaining might happen in other ways. For example, we might look for different doctors, or try different treatments. It is times like this where some atheists might also end up turning to a god to ask for mercy. The more eccentric or optimistic might turn to alternative medicines as well.', '22 Jun ''13, 23:22', 9),
('100076013', '100075343', 'users/114639240/yuying-1', 'I had the same problem. It turns out that 2 is the correct answer.', '23 Jun ''13, 00:10', 2),
('100076026', '100073373', 'users/118359379/emir-4', 'I agree that the stages are the same. You go through denial and depression when someone close passes away, but as you grow, you realize with time that you have to accept it and move on with your life.', '23 Jun ''13, 00:42', 1),
('100076055', '100076029', 'users/118801367/ludmila-2', 'The answer is 2', '23 Jun ''13, 01:47', 1),
('100076164', '100073652', 'users/100000364/michael-button', 'I also think there are two partly correct answers.  It seems that the "correct" answer focuses more on the ambivalence part of the attachment..', '23 Jun ''13, 06:52', 2),
('100076166', '100076165', 'users/100000364/michael-button', 'Try listening to what Lauren has to say about two types of intelligence.  One to use to solve problems we have seen before and one to use on problems that we have never seen.', '23 Jun ''13, 07:02', 3),
('100076168', '100076123', 'users/100000364/michael-button', 'Ahmad, go back and listen to what Greg has to say about REM sleep.', '23 Jun ''13, 07:05', 2),
('100076174', '100076123', 'users/100113949/ahmad-5', 'Thanks, Michael. I will do that.', '23 Jun ''13, 07:19', 0),
('100076193', '100064755', 'users/100020080/brett73', 'I''m hoping he''ll be able to team up with the San Jose State University''s Physics department (http://physics.sjsu.edu/) to offer more physics courses.  It''d be really cool if Udacity could do a chemistry course (through San Jose State: http://www.sjsu.edu/chemistry/)', '23 Jun ''13, 08:06', 1),
('100076201', '100070741', 'users/100020080/brett73', 'If you''re interested in statistics then check out the Udacity course Statistics (https://www.udacity.com/course/st095) done in conjunction with San Jose State Uni (like this course), and done by the Psychology Department, no less!', '23 Jun ''13, 08:22', 1),
('100076215', '100073352', 'users/117336435/melanie-suzanne-wilson', 'My parents were married around age 23 and 25. I was married at 20, and divorced at 21. I thought I was ready because we had lived together at my parents'' house for a year. That''s some time ago now. There is a trend in my home city where property and rent prices are extremely high. Most people my age (24) stayed in college for longer, therefore take longer to save up money. And we need more money than previous generations to buy or rent. So they take a long time to move out into independently affordable accommodation. So we live with our parents for longer, and this affects our relationships. I think this lack of independence makes people want to marry later.', '23 Jun ''13, 09:00', 1),
('100076238', '100073352', 'users/118541022/michael-979', 'My parents married when they were around 20 years old.\nI do not necessarily "plan" to get married, but if my relationship I have now continues and developes well, I think there is nothing wrong with me marrying. \nWhen my parents married it was not really an option, because they lived in a very christian-conservative community and marriage kind of came along with (and was a social prerequisite for) having children and living together. \nNowadays getting married is very often a legal issue because it grants some tax benefits and social/legal security for the partner and children in case one of the partners in the relationship dies. \nBecause it is no longer a necessity to get married for living together, most people first try out living together and then marry (if it works out well). In the past, it was more the other way around. This pretty much explains the shift in the age of people getting married. It simply takes longer to find "the one" and get to the point where it makes sense to get married nowadays.\nI ought to add that I am from Austria and therefore my experience does not necessarily have any weight for other countries.', '23 Jun ''13, 10:05', 1),
('100076287', '100074254', 'users/100020046/code_jamer', 'It is the "medulla" part of the hind brain.', '23 Jun ''13, 11:47', 2),
('100076290', '100071612', 'users/100020046/code_jamer', 'Blank 1: Limbic system\nBlank 2: Emotion', '23 Jun ''13, 11:55', 3),
('100076521', '100073373', 'users/100037806/anastasia-zarafidou', 'I do believe the 5 stages apply to the (impending) death of a loved one. Sure one can argue that they differ from the situation where you''re the one dying and that their intensity varies depending on the strength of the bond with the person. They are also believed to apply during other significant losses such as a breakup or being laid off.', '23 Jun ''13, 16:51', 1),
('100076579', '100073352', 'users/117336430/andrew-621', 'My parents were dad 21, and mom 19. At 23 dad, and 21 mom, the first child came, so far dad is 49 and mom 47 and we just celebrated child 9, 2nd birthday. I am 21 now, but am not ready would like to mature more spiritually first before, the Lord provides a wife. I believe I will be ready when I am humble, lead by example, and when I am a servant loving unconditionally. When I have been successful in the responsibilities God has given me, and am ready for a larger task.', '23 Jun ''13, 17:50', 1),
('100076603', '100073352', 'users/120081393/leah-14', 'My parents got married when my mom was about 23 and my dad was about 25. This does differ when I think about when I want to get married. I''d rather get married in my late 20''s because I''ll be done with school and hopefully on the road to a great career. \nThere is a shift in the age when people get married because now the world is very career based and want to make sure they can provide for their children.\nThe main things that will help me realize when I want to get married is if I''m done with my schooling, if I can support my husband and whether he can support our life together.', '23 Jun ''13, 18:18', 1),
('100076606', '100073373', 'users/120191717/andre-luiz-1', 'We all know that we''re going to die and that''s for certain. But this inevitable knowledge of the reality is not enough to prevent us from the pain and sadness that the death of a loved one brings. We know that we are going to wake up the next morning, and next, and that person won''t be there. They will not be part of our life anymore. They will only live in our memory.  That feeling of loss is what brings pain in our heart. But they tend to become lesser and lesser intense as  time goes by. If you can''t  deal with that, it''s better for you to seek for help, for the sake of the people around you who are still alive and loves you.\nPS. No matter if you lost someone from natural cause, or suddenly in an accident, or you may even think it was better because the loved one was suffering and there was no hope at all, the fact is that the pain and sadness will have the same intensity. Your pain will not be more or less,no matter the cause of the lost.\nAndr', '23 Jun ''13, 18:24', 0),
('100076615', '100073373', 'users/120081393/leah-14', 'I agree that grievers go through the same model to cope with someone''s death. It may sometimes take longer and they stay at the stages for a while but they all come to terms with the inevitable end.', '23 Jun ''13, 18:38', 1),
('100076649', '100070777', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'The quiz was not supposed to have said "correct." Instead, it was just supposed to thank you for replying and inform you to continue the lesson to get the answer. Thanks for pointing this out. As you all saw, he did not die, but he was a changed person.', '23 Jun ''13, 19:17', 2),
('100076694', '100073352', 'users/120191717/andre-luiz-1', 'TO GET MARRIED  x TO START A FAMILY (Can you feel the difference?)\nIt hard  to just try to set a perfect age for marriage (at any time) because it involves many variables and variants. Life is dynamic.\nToday it is expected that when two persons are thinking to start a family, they both should be mature (mind and body), have emotional and financial security, they both should be aware of the responsibilities and duties connected with the new roles they are about to assume in their life (husband and wife / mother and father). Doing that, there will be no great expectation unfulfilled and  there will be no surprise strong enough to undermine their relationship. \nOtherwise, Dont marry! You will be unhappy and make the other persons life miserable. And the other person will be unhappy and make your life miserable.\nAndr', '23 Jun ''13, 20:09', 1),
('100076743', '100073352', 'users/117152742/medina', 'My mom was 21 while my dad was 33 when they got married.\nThis does significantly differ from when I plan to get married because I will be 21 in about a year and a half and I can''t imagine making that commitment this early.\nWhy? I would want to be in a committed relationships for years, as well as gone through moving in with my husband (to be) to make sure we''re compatible for marriage. Considering I have yet to even have a serious relationship, getting married at 21 sounds ridiculous. \nI think there is a shift in the age people get married because people are finishing their education later, starting their careers later, therefore aren''t ready marriage or commitment until a later time than before.\nFinished with my schooling, stable career, and I have to be living a healthy life before I could share one with another person.', '23 Jun ''13, 21:35', 1),
('100076764', '100073373', 'users/117152742/medina', 'Yes I think this is very similar to coping with death of a loved one. One of my childhood friends recently passed away and I went through these stages. First I couldn''t believe this was happening, it felt unreal. Then I saw him in the hospital and was mad at myself, for not being their for him, for not being able to prevent it. I started praying and bargaining  with god, thinking if you just let him live I will stand by him.. do anything to fix things. Finally after his death there was nothing I could do but feel depressed, hopeless, and considering this happened only about a month ago the acceptance stage is coming with time.', '23 Jun ''13, 22:00', 1),
('100076980', '100073352', 'users/118474007/jason-410', 'My parents were around 30 when they married, when my mom was 28 and my dad was 31. I think it varies from person to person because of environmental factors such as occupation, location, and money. I feel that the older you get, the less children you have become of the time factor and the realization of how expensive children can be. Because it is harder to financially support a child, the age I feel is becoming later. I plan to get married around the same time as my parents, when I feel that I can adequately support a child or children.', '24 Jun ''13, 01:45', 1),
('100076992', '100073373', 'users/118474007/jason-410', 'I think it is a pretty similar process when it comes to coping with a death of a loved one. They will deny it at first, then when it settles, they become angry at why God would let something like this happen. Once the person fully realizes, depression hits until he or she fully accepts what has happened.', '24 Jun ''13, 01:54', 1),
('100076996', '100076995', 'users/119477191/nadia', 'may be something goes wrong with the internet connection or something else.i don,t exactly know.', '24 Jun ''13, 01:59', 0),
('100077042', '100073352', 'users/114866635/olga-61', 'Throughout history, numerous men tend to marry later than women.', '24 Jun ''13, 02:57', 1),
('100077051', '100073373', 'users/114866635/olga-61', 'There is no doubt that such things are related with similar stages.', '24 Jun ''13, 03:11', 1),
('100077081', '100077075', 'users/100000364/michael-button', 'Dear Olga,  don''t panic you are not behind. The lessons are released on Mondays.  Take a look at the "Lesson Release Schedule" for the exact dates.  You will find the schedule in Wiki/Class notes.  Depending where you are in the world, you will be able to take lesson 6 on June 24th sometime in the late afternoon or early morning on the 25th.  Have fun.\nMike', '24 Jun ''13, 04:37', 0),
('100077082', '100077075', 'users/100008253/snowpolar', 'Well, fret not. You are perfectly on schedule!\nDo note that timezone difference might mean why some topics are not out yet too!\nHere is  the link to the schedule:\nhttps://www.udacity.com/wiki/ps001/lessonreleaseschedule', '24 Jun ''13, 04:38', 0),
('100077083', '100073373', 'users/100000364/michael-button', 'I think different people handle the death of a death of a loved one differently.  I lost my grandparents, mother, father, step-father.  I experienced a great sorrow, but no denial or asking why this happened to them.  I miss them but accept that death is something that comes to all of us, sometimes earlier sometimes later.  Perhaps why in part that I was not affected in the usual way is that at the time of their death, I was living in Germany and they died in the US.  Strangely enough my wife (German) went through all these stages when my mother died.', '24 Jun ''13, 04:49', 1),
('100077090', '100073352', 'users/118592416/catalina-1', 'There are already 7 years difference between the age my mom got married (26) and my unmarried current age (33). My dad was 23. In my opinion the shift is due to changes in society norms. Back then, everybody would have frowned upon you if you weren''t married at 20 something; the role of women was to get married and have kids and when all your friends would be married you would have tried to fit in. Now, there isn''t that much pressure and, also, some of the religious constraints have been replaced by career concerns (finishing formal education and having a financial stability). I admire people who get married as I see them certain that they are able to count on each other.', '24 Jun ''13, 05:36', 1),
('100077097', '100073105', 'users/118592416/catalina-1', 'My guess is almost in the same area: shy men need more time to approach and conquer women, while shy women don''t feel they would loose their style of life and postpone having a child.', '24 Jun ''13, 05:44', 0),
