('100077189', '100064455', 'users/121161386/greg-179', 'From the start of this experimental study to this point, I must have misunderstood something, because it seems to me that mid-way, the parameters of the study have changed. First it, if I understood correctly, it was about reaction time between caffeine and no caffeine. Now you''ve introduced the single blind (i.e. trickery) of the placebo group getting decaf coffee.\nThe only issue I have with the decaf coffee being used is that psychologically, people may have a reaction "just because" they are drinking coffee, and possibly they may think that it''s caffeinated. So, it would seem to me that we would get a faulty baseline.\nDecaffeinated coffee is not like a "brand" or anything. The word is literal, the caffeine has been removed (de-caffeinated). However, studies do show that that''s only at about 95%. So, using decaf coffee as a placebo would give sketchy results based on how susceptible someone is to caffeine, even the slightest amounts. \nDespite that small disagreement with the parameters of the experiment, I would say that this would be something fun to try out, since I know many people who are gung-ho about coffee in the morning, and swear they can''t live without it. \nMe.. I''ll stick with my Mt. Dew ;-)', '24 Jun ''13, 10:13', 0),
