('100077515', '100077281', 'users/117934209/dena', 'In my late 20''s and 30''s  I had the most wonderful dreams . I would be in a regular rather flat dream; low color not a clear story, when as if someone had changed a channel I would be in a white room with a dear friend of mine, Howie. Backstory; I fell despartly in love with Howie on the first day of Jr High, we became friends , much to my disappointment, just friends. Howie always said if we were to date it would ruin our friendship. A very sweet way of saying "I am not into you" . I still was mad for him through high school though we remained "just friends". I saw him years later after college. We went out once at laughed at how silly that was - Friendship was definatly they way to go. At 21 Howie died in a car accident. I could not bring myself to go to the funeral- He was not dead to me. Fast forward 10 years, I ''m married have 2 children and life is a bit tough, not going as I hoped. I start having "Howie dreams" , middle of a dream the channel would  change and I would be in a white room with Howie who is wearing a Hawaiian shirt ( he always wore one in high school). I would talk to him about present day issues I was having and though I don''t recall him ever telling me exact advice, I always felt a burden had been lifted and I was enlightened. I would wake up in the morning very happy and plan to call him. Then within moments, seconds I would remember he was not ...reachable. The more trials my life brought, the more "Howie Dreams" I would have always with the same result in the morning - But even after the realization I still found great comfort. Years passed, my guess, 10 or so. My personal life was still pitchy but I was stronger. One night to my delight the channel changed in my dream, only this time Howie was at an outdoor cafe on a corner , very European looking or maybe San Francisco. He still looked 21 , as he always had, but I became aware if me and what age I was. I was now close to 40. Howie reached out a took my hand and I felt it. We sat at the table in front of the cafe the morning air was crisp and the sunrise was beautiful. The sprinklers were on and a rainbow shone through and the mist was cold on face. I asked Howie why we were here. He replied because it was the last time I was going to see him. He said I didn''t need him to be strong - He hugged me and kissed me (on the cheek) which I felt , and can still remember to this day . I awoke that morning sobbing out of control. My then husband asked what was wrong - I said Howie died. He was very confused, because he knew Howie had died years ago. My day was spent crying and morning. I have not had a "Howie Dream" since.', '24 Jun ''13, 18:30', 3),
('100077544', '100077282', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'I was very excited to have to opportunity to interview Dr. Griffiths and Dr. Doblin. I read a lot of Dr. Griffith''s research while I was in graduate school and he has done some very interesting work. He is one of the top behavioral pharmacologists in the field. Also, Dr. Doblin is heading the charge to try to get MDMA approved as a medicine for individuals with treatment-resistant PTSD. Currently they have some promising results. I hope you enjoy these interviews and appreciate the research they conduct.', '24 Jun ''13, 19:15', 0),
