('100077584', '100077281', 'users/114211550/jaja', 'I''m a lucid dream practioner. I first heard about lucid dreaming when I was around 14. And then I started seriously studying and having lucid dreams when I was 15 years old. I am already 16 years old now, but I am still having lucid dreams until now. When I don''t have lucid dreams, I experience extremely vivid dreams. \n\nThis takes a lot of practice to be able to do. I want to know if any\nof you have ever been able to lucid dream and if so what was it like\nand how did you teach yourself to lucid dream?\n\nWhen I''m in a lucid dream, I start to realize how life-like dreams really are. For example, I can feel my surroundings, emotionally (atmosphere of the place) and physically (touching the objects, etc.). In dreams, just to cite a few more examples, I can also taste the food, listen to music, and sing. \nFunny, often times, the food, music and even the songs are completely new to me, but surprisingly, the food actually tastes VERY well. The music sounds incredibly good, too - while the singing, I''m honestly not sure I could come up with something like that in real life, because like the food and music, it''s very unique but also suprisingly good. \nThere was a time I dreamt I was in this opera. The song was very pleasant to the ear, and when I woke from that dream, the first thing I remember doing was singing the last few notes I could remember, but a couple of seconds later, it faded away. I can''t remember any of the song (but only some vague memory of some scenes from the play); it''s sad, because if I could remember even just that, I would have come up with an amazing song to share with my friend; it was really just that good.\nI could also socialize with the dream characters there (like engage in a bit of small talk, for example. Sometimes, when I have a phone with me in my dream, I can even send and receive texts, just like in real life).\nBasically, what I realized from all my lucid dreaming experiences is that, what I can do in real life, I can also do in my dreams.\nFurther, I could also even do things I cannot in real life, like play instruments (that I don''t even know how to play in real life) , drive cars, fly, shift the environment into something else, summon dream characters and objects, and so much more. \nLast night, I dreamt that I was chatting with my friend. Really, I could use a computer in my dream, just like I am doing right now in real life: I can feel myself tapping the keyboard, I can even see and remember the chat dialogues we make (before I started lucid dreaming, I could barely even remember myself being able to read anything in dreams because the text usually jumble or fade away as I''m reading it), and often times, the website I''m chatting in my dreams are the same in real life (in one of my dreams, I was chatting on Facebook, and I saw the same design there w/ the same friends on my newsfeed, etc.) and they''re just as interactive as well, like if I would scroll down, posts would automatically be generated in my newsfeed, just like they would in real life.\nI taught myself how to lucid dream by reading different books on the topic, as well joining in different forums.\n\nI have been aware of the fact that I was dreaming but I have never\nbeen able to actually change the outcome of a dream. Usually once I\nrealize it is a dream I just wake up. What about you?\n\nThe first time I had a successful lucid dream, I remember it was because I listened to some binaural beats. This binaural beats helped stabilized my lucid dream, in a way that once I realized that I was dreaming, I would remain very calm (so I wouldn''t be too excited &amp; eventually wake up from that) and focused on my purpose to experience lucid dream.\nI would recommend listening to it as well before sleeping. Here''s the link if you''re interested:\n http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=66tq9xji0xA', '24 Jun ''13, 20:37', 1),
('100077608', '100073352', 'users/118533420/martin-281', 'My parents were in their early thirties when they married - same for me.  I would caution against marriage because of the toll of divorce.  If I offered you the opportunity for a free cruise on one of two luxury ships, held up two tickets from which your selection would decide which ship you will set sail on - with the caveat that one of the ships will sink at some point on the trip with the potential to cost you much of what you''ve worked for and love in this world - would you take a ticket?  What if it was a choice of planes to LA - knowing that one was going down during the flight?  If divorce rates are at about 50% in this country then it''s a somewhat similar decision - I think.\nTwo people can profoundly love and respect one another without marriage getting in the way.  Co-habitation seems like it''s more popular than ever and who knows, maybe it''s because younger folks choose that based on witnessing their parents divorce or someone they know divorcing and all of the negative consequences that went along with that process.\nI believe children are the most wonderful thing that a union can produce and you don''t need to be married to produce, provide for or love them.  I believe the nature part of nature vs. nurture never stops and so the person you are, or the person you think you want to marry at 30 will be a different person at 40, 50, 60 - a continuous process of evolution that may - or may not - progress along increasingly divergent paths until you perhaps realize the certainty of your eternal love at 30 was more hope than reality and now what are you going to do?\nI''m all for love since I believe life would be unimaginably empty and lonely without it, but I cannot say the same for marriage.', '24 Jun ''13, 21:24', 1),
