('100077662', '100073352', 'users/117175141/ruth-23', 'My mom was married to my dad when she was in the ages between 21-23 and my dad married her when he was between 29-34.\nThis doesn''t  differ for when I want to get married for the reason that I may not be in the same situation as them, times are different and the fact that my priorities are different from theres.\nI think there is a shift in marriage because people start putting education and there careers as a priority and as people start to live longer the idea of getting married later in life starts to look logical and realistic.\nThe main things that make me think I will be ready to get married is if I''m in love with the person and I cant imagine life without them, my age, and where I''m at in my career.', '24 Jun ''13, 22:48', 1),
('100077716', '100073352', 'users/118972377/nycalexis', 'My parents married around 20 (Dad) and 21 (Mom) years old and had their first kid at about 22 and 23. I want to get married someday if I find the right person, but I don''t really care when that is. \nI think this is because of how cultures, morals, and beliefs change or evolve over time. For example, many years ago in some cultures it was socially acceptable, encouraged, and expected of young girls in their early teens to marry men who were far older than them (adults and older). Sometimes girls where even forced to marry men they did not want because it was convenient or because they were sold. Now, of course, this may be seen as wrong or immoral, although it is still practiced in some parts of the world.\nI think that once I am an adult with my own source of income, am living in my own apartment, and am done with college I will be ready to get married.', '25 Jun ''13, 01:07', 1),
('100077725', '100073352', 'users/112984983/anastasia-21', 'My parents got married when my mom was 23 and my dad was 28. I got married at 22, my husband was 28. There is not much difference. Maybe it''s because the typical age of getting married hasn''t changed much in our country since then.\nHowever, I see now that more and more people are choosing not to get married until they are successful and independent in financial terms. There are also a lot of insecurities in our society.\nI got married mostly because my parents pushed me to do this. It felt like the right thing to do, as I loved my boyfriend and so did he, and we wanted to be together. However, I still don''t think it was necessary. I could have waited till we had a baby (which we haven''t got yet).', '25 Jun ''13, 01:25', 1),
