('100077979', '100077851', 'users/114211550/jaja', 'Oh, not having dreams is impossible, dear - every single night, whether we like it or not, we dream because dreams actually play a vital role in our mental health. Regarding REM sleep, you also get that every night. You see, our sleep goes through 5 stages. Yes, it''s mandatory. Not just one 1 stage, but 5 whole stages. One of those stages is REM sleep. \nJust to give you an idea of what REM sleep is, it is the stage which is the longest lasting &amp; the one that gives us the most vivid and most memorable dreams. Also, REM sleep helps restore our body, and  it also influences memory. \nNow that you know that REM is a part of vital stages of sleep, it''s highly unlikely that you go to sleep every night, but don''t get REM sleep.\nThat being said, the problem here maybe because you are just not very good at recalling your dreams. It could be also possible that you''re not having enough REM sleep, which you can solve by adjusting to a healthier sleeping lifestyle. I recommend visiting SleepWarrior.com for articles to help you develop a better sleep lifestyle + reading their free ebook on the 40 sleep hacks. Really helpful stuff.\nThe good news about dream recall is that, much like any other skill, can be practiced and developed overtime. :)  (Here''s my tip: Try practicing it by keeping a dream journal. Basically, what you do is that, the moment you wake up, you pick up your dream journal and you list down keywords for the things/scenes you remember from your dream. I would recommend min. of 5 keywords. Again, just keywords - doesn''t have to be long, extremely detailed descriptions of your entire dream. :D\nThis tricks the brain into thinking that it''s VITAL to remember those dreams, and consequently, the next time you dream, your brain will try harder to remember more details about your dreams, thus improving your dream recall. Try this for a week straight, and let me know about your progress.)', '25 Jun ''13, 12:12', 0),
