('100078182', '100077421', 'users/122939709/carly-8', 'I''m not sure which one is better or if there really is a difference as long as you get your 8 hours of sleep, but there are many studies which suggest sleeping from the exact same time every single day can be much more beneficial to your overall health and well being. For example people who suffer from sleeping disorders are typically reccommended to sleep at the same time every day for the same amount of time to help regulate their sleeping patterns which in turn does help the person to sleep better. I have also heard that sleeping at the same times does help stabilize metabolism and things as well... And when you think about it typically people who are on the same schedule all the time (Such as my grandparents and now even parents) basically have an internal alarm clock because their bodies are so used to that sleeping schedule.  To reply to the above answer, I agree that having a variety of sleep either too much or too little is never good. It would be interesting to see if you slept 8 hours every day but at different times how it would affect you. \nOverall I think having a fixed sleeping schedule is likely more beneficial to the body.', '25 Jun ''13, 18:00', 2),
('100078185', '100073352', 'users/122950762/s-37', 'My parents were 19 and 20 when they got married so I grew up thinking that was the best age, you''re still young enough to have fun and do/ be able to do  all kinds of interesting things which creates memories together that you can hold on to for the rest of you life and also old enough to live on your own and be independent from your parents . When you''re older (lets say 40- 45) and you get married you probably already have a career and a "5 year plan" that most likely includes buying a house, having kids and starting a family, not travelling or seeing the world with your spouse and in turn not creating a bunch of wonderful memories to hold on to. Not that getting married at an older age is a bad thing I just felt like you miss out on sharing your youthful years together.\nNow I''m 23 and not married and terrified of the idea of marriage. So much commitment and so much opportunity to fail.\nI found this article and thought it might share it with you guys: http://news.menshealth.com/proposal-clues/2012/12/17/', '25 Jun ''13, 18:14', 1),
('100078194', '100073373', 'users/122950762/s-37', 'I feel like we don''t  all go through the stages while dealing with death, I feel that the way we deal with it varies depending on how well we knew the person who died, also how old we are when the death occurs. As a member of a large family I have dealt with a lot of death in my life, aunts great uncles, grandparents, friends, pets, great aunts and uncles. I know from my experience that age plays a large role in the grieving factor. When I was 12  my aunt  died of cancer. I was pretty close with her, but when my mum told me she had died I did not cry or feel sad until about 4 months later. I am not even completely sure that I cried because I missed her if it was because I felt bad for not crying when she did. I even remember my sister leaning over to me at the funeral and saying "its okay to cry" but I didn''t cry.  I think this was because when I was 12 I didn''t really understand death the way I do now, the year my aunt died I also lost two great uncles. I think because there was so much death occurring at the time it didn''t really phase me as something sad but as something normal.\nTwo years ago my Nana died, I was very close with her and looked up to her more than I have anyone else in my life. She was a wonderful women who always had something nice to say. I remember I was really sad and devastated but never bargained or felt angry because of it. \nI feel that as we age we start to really realize the impact someone''s death will have on our lives which makes us miss them more and in turn makes us more sad. I am not sure that we go through every stage when someone we know dies however I don''t think most people go through all of them.', '25 Jun ''13, 18:34', 1);
