('100078202', '100073373', 'users/122939709/carly-8', 'I feel that everyone copes with death in different ways, but that it is quite common for people to go through all 5 stages of dealing with loss the same way. Some people may deal with the stages in different orders or may not deal with some of the stages at all but I do think it is safe to say that everyone goes through at least a few of the typical stages.\nThe 5 stages are:\ndenial and isolation - The first reaction to learning of terminal illness or death of a cherished loved one is to deny the reality of the situation. This is also the first stage of pain that people go through.\nanger - As the masking effects of denial and isolation begin to wear, reality and its pain re-emerge. We are not ready. The intense emotion is deflected from our vulnerable core, redirected and expressed instead as anger. \nbargaining - The normal reaction to feelings of helplessness and vulnerability is often a need to regain control\ndepression - Two types of depression are associated with mourning. The first one is a reaction to practical implications relating to the loss.  This phase may be eased by simple clarification and reassurance. The second type of depression is more subtle and, in a sense, perhaps more private. It is our quiet preparation to separate and to bid our loved one farewell. Sometimes all we really need is a hug.\nacceptance - Reaching this stage of mourning is a gift not afforded to everyone. Death may be sudden and unexpected or we may never see beyond our anger or denial. It is not necessarily a mark of bravery to resist the inevitable and to deny ourselves the opportunity to make our peace. \nI have been lucky to not experience death many times, the only person close to me who has died was my grandma a few years ago. When she died I definitely went through the first stage of denial and isolation. I kept to myself and didn''t really want to be around anyone. I hid my emotions and didn''t want to show how upset I was. I pushed away the people closest to me. I eventually went through the second stage of anger where I came to the realization of why I was acting that way and was able to see that it was the passing of my grandma that was causing all of my emotions. I do not think I went through much depression, but I did go through some of the bargaining stage. I think everyone goes through a what if stage, and I know I definitely did.  Eventually I came to the acceptance stage, but to this day I still regret being in such a rush at one of my graduation events that I couldnt take a quick picture with her. She died a month later and I still wish I would have just stopped for a second and taken that picture.', '25 Jun ''13, 18:46', 1),
