('100078211', '100078186', 'users/122950762/s-37', 'Although you have some very valid points I think there is too much science backing up depression as a real sickness, there have been hundreds of studies done on depression and many people who suffer from it would assure you it a real disorder.  I have posted some links below that you may want to look at for more information. \nhttp://www.cmha.ca/mental-health/understanding-mental-illness/depression/\nhttp://www.helpguide.org/mental/depression_signs_types_diagnosis_treatment.htm\nhttp://www.womenshealthmatters.ca/health-resources/mental-health/depression/', '25 Jun ''13, 18:56', 0),
('100078216', '100073194', 'users/122939709/carly-8', 'My parents are not legally married but are common law and gave eachother rings and stuff... They did this at the age of 30. I have always wanted to be married at a younger age. When I was 16 I wanted to be married at 23 with a kid by 25. Now that i''m 21 I feel like maybe 25 for marriage and 27 for a child. I have a boyfriend right now who I can honestly say I would love to marry, but because of all the statistics out there I am terified that if I went ahead with it at such a young age that we would end up divorced somehow like 50% of the population. I do feel that my parents getting together a bit older makes me more reluctant to get married at a young age. I am sure if my parents got married at 18 I would be totally be fine with getting married at 21. \nAlso I have noticed that it is very common for people who have parents who got married at a young age to do the same, for instance in a community I lived in for a little while (Chilliwack, BC) I would talk to women at the gym and alot of them got married at very young ages and their daughters and sons were all getting married and having children at young ages as well. I think it is very common for people to follow in their parents foot steps and that there is likely a correlation between the age people get married and their parents.', '25 Jun ''13, 19:03', 0),
