('100078325', '100078192', 'users/118533420/martin-281', 'I do not, but this is from someone with a massive bias based on a disastrous divorce.  It''s a risky proposition and one which - I believe - most people go into wholly unprepared.  Co-habitation sounds better to me since I believe as animals we need the companionship and love that a trusted partner provides and this can be obtained without the legal complications of a marriage contract.\nYou state that "Psychologically I believe they are beneficial to your overall well being since people in happy marriages tend to have extremely good mental and physical health."  But you further state a rate of divorce in this country of between 40 - 50%!  By definition that would suggest that half of married people are sad and suffer from extremely poor mental and physical health!  I would submit that if marriage were a drug trial it would be prematurely halted because of the adverse effects it was having on an unacceptably high percentage of the test subjects!\nI agree that where children are concerned, a happy union of both parents is incredibly beneficial.  A recently released CDC report however, found that this benefit is bestowed upon the children regardless of whether the parents formalized their relationship through marriage or not - which kind of makes sense.  The study also found rates of cohabitation increasing while rates of marriage were on the decline.\nMy wish would be for everyone in the class to either be or one day be in the happy 50%, because it doesn''t get any better when that''s where you are!', '25 Jun ''13, 22:35', 0),
('100078414', '100074643', 'users/118592416/catalina-1', 'Jeffrey Mogil, Ph.D., is professor of pain studies at McGill University in Montreal, Canada. He explains that while not all studies have found sex differences, those which have all point in the same direction that contradicts conventional wisdom. "Females are more sensitive to pain, less tolerant and more able to discriminate different levels of pain than males," he says. This is true in studies of both humans and animals. Pregnancy is the exception to the rule.\nOn the other hand,  in research conducted by Mogil''s group on opioid medications, only redheaded women were different from others in the way these drugs relieved their pain; they needed less opioid painkillers than brunettes or blondes. Male redheads were the same as everyone else.\n(Source: http://healthyliving.msn.com/health-wellness/do-women-have-a-higher-pain-threshold-1)', '26 Jun ''13, 01:42', 1),
