('100078965', '100078895', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'Hello,\nAll of the studies discussed in this lesson were approved by Human Subjects Review Boards. They looked at the risks vs benefits of conducting the research and decided the benefits outweighed the risks. However, to be approved, the researchers had to create inclusion and exclusion criteria in an attempt to make sure that individuals susceptible to potential negative effects would not be included in the study. If you recall, Dr. Griffiths was very clear about the possible negative effects of psilocybin and discussed this important concern when giving hallucinogenic substances to humans.', '26 Jun ''13, 21:44', 6),
('100078969', '100078518', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'This is a good question. In any research with drugs, there is the possibility of a negative or adverse reaction. This occurs not only with hallucinogenic drugs, it can also occur with drugs we may think are rather benign, such as aspirin. This is why the Human Subjects Review Boards carefully consider the potential risks vs the potential benefits of the research. In this case, the boards thought that the benefits from psilocybin outweighed the risks. However, it is very important to remember that the researchers had to develop inclusion and exclusion criteria to get approval. That is, they had to identify people who should be included and those who should not included, based on a variety of variables (e.g., previous addiction problems, mental health difficulties, etc.). This helps to ensure that people susceptible of having a negative experience are not included in the study. Another thing to consider once the person has met the inclusion criteria for the study,  is that the participant has been informed of the potential risks and potential benefits and he or she provides informed consent to participate. Finally, why would the person participate if there might be negative consequences? In the cases presented in this lesson, the participants were experiencing much psychological distress and, therefore, they were willing to participate because they felt, personally, they might have a greater chance of experiencing a benefit. I hope this answers your question! \nThanks!\nDr. Snycerski', '26 Jun ''13, 22:01', 1),
