('100079162', '100078173', 'users/120686583/chadwick-4', 'I''d have to argue for the need to have faith in much of what we teach as evolution. There are a lot of assertions based on inferences, but not a lot of unambiguous testable data. To be fair, the requirement of scientific inquiry is to disprove everything. Scientific discovery is only "as far as we can imagine with the limited understanding we have" and I love the sciences. But we are definitely prone to hubris. Accepting uncertainty in science is a core tenant.\nFor a question about God''s hand in evolution, it puts both evolution and God into the realm of philosophy. But I love philosophy too. ;)\nJust offering my opinions as I enjoy the subjects very much and I certainly do not want to offend nor create discord. :)\nEnjoy!', '27 Jun ''13, 04:25', 2),
('100079164', '100077024', 'users/120686583/chadwick-4', 'I find this subject quite fascinating. Psychologically, evolution has an interesting place in our society, especially in our recent generations. The imagination of such has been extensively imported to my mind through cartoons and video games (all of which I quite enjoyed as a child). It is really hard to separate the social constructs of evolution and the scientific evidence. It is also hard to interpret the scientific evidence without influences from very dominant societal factors both for and against certain aspects of evolution theory.\nSometimes the constructs we form help us tackle questions and problems from new points of view. So, it has it''s uses. But the emotional response connected to ideas about evolution is psychological and deeper than science. I''d be curious to see some research on the area of the brain from which such thoughts and emotions are activated.\nJust trying to join some of the discussions. Thanks for the class! :)', '27 Jun ''13, 04:38', 0),
('100079186', '100077024', 'users/100058444/george-el-azar', 'Evolution is the best theory we have for how we and other species came about. It makes less assumptions than other alternate explanations that involve complex beings like God and extraterrestrial aliens, and it sufficiently explains all the collective evidence on its own without the need for any such entities. Plus, it continues to be confirmed by further evidence and it has yet to be falsified.\nIn short, there is no valid reason to reject it in favor of something more complex and that doesn''t even sufficiently explain all the relevant evidence we have access to.', '27 Jun ''13, 06:25', 3),
('100079232', '100061827', 'users/118232219/sourav-3', 'Hi,\nI am Sourav from Mumbai. After being an Engineer (a few years) and an Advertising Writer (for 9 years), I am now an Art History / Art Theory Student.\n I have always been interested in human mind and behaviour. I have had the habit of analyzing my own and everybody else''s behaviour in my mind (including those of fictional characters) and reading up books and online articles about psychology, especially those on mental disorders.\nI have also had history of mental problems in my family and among my very close friends.\nI just didn''t want to miss the chance to learn about Psychology from professionals.\nSo far the course, especially the structure has been excellent.\nCan''t hardly wait for the next lesson!', '27 Jun ''13, 09:22', 0),
