('100080672', '100077423', 'users/119901270/benjamin-159', 'I have quite a bit of experience with Lucid Dreaming and I might be able to help! There are a few things that you can do in daily life that will really help you conquer this issue. It can take some time to learn (1-3 months average), however, considering the severity of the dreams it sounds like you are having, it might be worth the wait. First off, keep a dream journal. Whenever you wake up take that dream journal and write in it as many details from your dreams as you can, however minute they may be. It is imperative you do this right after you wake up because dreams are forgotten very fast and seem to deteriorate with movement. After about a week or two you should start to notice patterns when you dream. It might be something like a relative whom you rarely see, or a boss from an old job, or an ex girlfriend/boyfriend. You must condition yourself to question reality whenever you see one of these triggers. \nSo now we move onto reality checks. During your day there are a few subtle things that I recommend you do frequently. One of them is to look at your hand and count your fingers. If you are having trouble counting or notice a tentacle arm (or other odd feature about your hand) you will know you are dreaming. Another check is to hold your nose and see if you can still breathe. I usually do this under the guise of adjusting my glasses. Another check is to simply look at your watch, remember the time then about 10 seconds later look back and see if it has changed drastically. If it has, you are dreaming. Finally, there is looking in a mirror. If you look in a mirror and see a disfigured or younger version of yourself, you are dreaming. \nYou will want to perform one of these reality checks at least once an hour (once every 15 minutes if you want to be really thorough) in waking life. It is important to note that you should do this whilst you are using you dream journal, not after. Also, don''t time your reality checks down to the hour, as time is not reliable in a dream. You will just end up confusing yourself in a dream.  \nNow that we are done with the lengthy preparations, let''s get to what to actually do once you realize you are dreaming. Once you realize you are dreaming, which for me happened about a week into trying, there is one of two things you can do. In your case, you probably just want to get out of the dream. Good news! Usually once you realize you are dreaming you will get very excited and wake up. But, if you want the added perks of unlimited control and power in an alternate reality then you may continue. \nIf you want to have fun in your dream you can stabilize it once you realize you are lucid. To do this, either rub your hands together (like you do when they are cold), which will bring a vibrancy of color and will seem to turn the saturation up on the dream. You should also be very tactile. Touch as much as possible during the first (seeming) 5 minutes. You can spin around if you want to go somewhere else, this would be useful if you are in a scary place. \nNow that you have stabilized the dream, I will tell you about control. Dreams are limitless. If you can think it, you can do it. With NO ill affects in the real world. If you die in a dream there will be absolutely no harm to you in the real world. So don''t be afraid to try cool stuff. You also typically cannot feel pain in dreams unless you want to. So feel free to cause all the debauchery you want. \nAs I said dreams are limitless. You can go wherever and do whatever. If you want to go on a date with your favorite actor/actress you can and the outcome will be whatever you will it to be. Just note that getting too excited in a dream can cause you to wake up if it is not stable enough. \nFinally I leave you with this, you can discover things about yourself that you never knew in dreams. The professors might disagree here because this is not tested, but I believe the following to be true. All the characters in your dreams are manifestations of your subconsciousness. If you ask them a question they will answer honestly. \nGood luck with your Lucid Dreaming!', '30 Jun ''13, 00:24', 1),
('100080704', '100079400', 'users/118577135/jamie-77', 'Tolerance also depends on how long the person has been using the drug. If it''s two days, the person might not need a different amount than they took before. However, someone who has been taking a drug for years on a regular basis will probably be taking a bigger amount than they did initially because their body adjusted to that drug being there for so long. People who have been using a drug regularly for years who try to quit abusing it immediately will also go through withdrawal and have issues since their body is used to the drug''s presence and may be producing less or more of a chemical in response to the drug''s effects. It might depend on the kind of drug too, since some are harder than others.\nLet me try a concrete example. If a person goes off a stimulant, then they might withdraw and show signs of depression as their body is producing less dopamine than when the drug helped stimulate that production.\nDoes that make sense? It''s been a while since I took psych.', '30 Jun ''13, 02:02', 1),
