('100082384', '100082236', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'In terms of learning and classical conditioning, yes, you can say that a reflex is an unconditioned response. That is, the reflex does not occur unless there is a stimulus that elicits it. For example, we do not have a startle response unless there is a stimulus that elicits it. Therefore, the "reflex" is the "response" which is unconditioned when it happens naturally (e.g., meat powder causing salivation) or conditioned if it happens due to a learning history (e.g., tone causing salivation after training). I hope this answers your question.\nThanks,\nDr. Snycerski', '02 Jul ''13, 18:58', 0),
('100082394', '100077423', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'Hi Francis,\nThis is the tip I used that my professor in undergrad taught us. He told us to ask ourselves throughout the day, "Am I dreaming?"  So, if you asked yourself right now, "Am I dreaming?" you would of course know that you were not. He told us to do this many times a day for a few weeks and that one day, if it worked for us, we would find ourselves in a dream and we would ask ourselves "Am I dreaming?" If we were dreaming, we would then become aware of it because we would realize that we were, indeed, in a dream. \nI did this for a long time and then one night found myself in a dream wherein I was eating a glass mug. This seemed very unusual and not quite right.  Therefore, I asked myself, "Am I dreaming?" and I immediately realized that I was dreaming because there was no way I would be eating glass! I usually awake at the moment I realize I am dreaming, but it always is really neat when I do wake up because I realize I''ve had a lucid dream! \nMy husband, Dr. Laraway from the Udacity Statistics class, also has been able to lucid dream as well. He started out using the same technique. However, he also tells himself before he goes to sleep that if he is having a weird or unusual dream and he "wakes up in it" and he "is not in our bed in our bedroom" that is dreaming. On these occasions, when he realizes that he is in fact dreaming, he tells himself to fly, and he does! I haven''t been that lucky to fly yet, but I keep trying!\nI hope you find this informative! Good luck lucid dreaming!', '02 Jul ''13, 19:13', 1),
