('100082421', '100080938', 'users/100003824/eleftherios-kosmas-1', 'As a sleep technologist in a university sleep medicine research laboratory I have to disagree with the notion that sleep is just a mental state. It is a physiological necessity not only for humans or mammals but all vertebrates and even some invertebrates seem to have sleep like conditions. I remember a well know study of the sleep of fruit flies (yeah I know it''s weird even for me) that supports the notion that prolonged and systematic disturbance of their sleep circles does lead to cognitive disabilities (1), \none would expect that is wasn''t that essential we would be able to find animals that don''t sleep, that don''t do recovery sleep when they stay awake more than usual and that don''t have severe pathophysiological concequeses when they are sleep deprived that doesn''t seem to be the case but I am open to new data.\nWe know for a fact that sleep is affecting some basic functions especially in mammals\n- Sleep deprivation affects the immune system (lowers white blood cell count in rats) (2)\n- REM deprivation in infants can lead to smaller brain size (3)\n- Prolonged sleep deprivation in rats was lethal\nI am not a doctor but it seems that we have reason to believe that sleep does affect several body functions. In way it must act as a regulatory phase for the body. I am not a sleep doctor or bear any high profile degrees of any kind. But these articles are so quoted in sleep medicine circles in support of an active role of sleep in other than mental functions.\nI hope that I helped \n:D\n(1) Huber R, Hill SL, Holladay C, Biesiadecki M, Tononi G, Cirelli C (2005): Sleep Homeostasis in Drosophila Melanogaster; Sleep 27(4):628639 (2) Zager, A.; Andersen, M.L.; Ruiz, F.S.; Antunes, I.B. and Tufik, S. (2007). "Effects of acute and chronic sleep loss on immune modulation of rats". Regulatory, Integrative and Comparative Physiology 293: R504R509. doi:10.1152/ajpregu.00105.2007. (3) Morrissey M, Duntley S, Anch A, Nonneman R (2004). "Active sleep and its role in the prevention of apoptosis in the developing brain". Med Hypotheses 62 (6): 8769. doi:10.1016/j.mehy.2004.01.014. PMID\n15142640. (4)   Guidelines for the Care and Use of Mammals in Neuroscience and Behavioral Research. Institute for Laboratory Animal Research (ILAR), National Research Council. The National Academies Press. 2003. p. 121. ISBN 978-0-309-08903-6. "Sleep deprivation of over 7 days with the disk-over-water system results in the development of ulcerative skin lesions, hyperphagia, loss of body mass, hypothermia, and eventually septicemia and death in rats (Everson, 1995; Rechtschaffen et al., 1983)."', '02 Jul ''13, 20:10', 6),
