('100082684', '100081869', 'users/100011383/abdo-achkar', 'Lauren, I am wondering if Michael''s issue is his reaction to the result of the night terror not the night terror itself:\nMichael''s getting angry and feeling shameful because he feels he''s hurting others.\nHis response, I think, keeps his cycle going. He has night terrors because he''s feeling angry and he''s angry because he has night terrors.\nWhat if Michael works on being more optimistic and focuses on being grateful after the night terror. \nMichael can train himself to modify his response to night terrors by saying to himself when he wakes up: "Nice.. It wasn''t real, it was just a night terror."\nI think since Michael is not conscious after his night terrors, he wouldn''t be able to build the habit of being grateful/optimistic right after the night terror. What if he (literally) simulates and act out having a night terror when he''s awake, and reacts positively and gratefully (it wasn''t real, I have a wife who cares about me, I have not hurt anyone, etc...)\nI think night terrors is a state of learned helplessness and can be remedied with optimism and habit building.\nI would love to hear what Michael has to say about this =)\ndisclaimer: besides this class on psychology and a few of related books I have read, I know nothing about psychology and the post above is just a suggestion.', '03 Jul ''13, 08:35', 1),
