('100085301', '100084567', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'Remember that we use the term "conditioned response" when referring to classical conditioning. In this example of the pipe and loud sound, we are removing the aversive sound, so the aversiveness is "subtracted'' or "removed" and that is where the "negative" comes into play. It is also "reinforcement" because we perform the behavior again under similar situations. Thus, we have negative reinforcement. I hope this explanation helps.\nBest,\nDr. Snycerski', '07 Jul ''13, 16:38', 4),
