('100086070', '100085970', 'users/117443595/nancy-27', 'I think that it is a combination. We hear our mothers voice when we are in the womb. I don''t think we are able to make out the words but we can hear the different tones. Then when we are born and we are growing we learn from our environment. It seems that we teach our children words that associate with items and that is how we learn the language that we speak.', '08 Jul ''13, 19:02', 0),
('100086102', '100073352', 'users/100083008/geannie', 'My mom and dad got together when my mom was 22 or 23, and my dad was 14 years older than her.  They never did get married, and while I am married now, I never had really strong opinions about whether or not I was going to get married in future.  I do think that their relationship, and others in my family (grandparents, aunts, uncles, and so forth) did influence why I waited as long as I did (33).  I wanted to be super-sure that I was making the correct decision for myself if and when it happened.\nThe historical shift in when people tend to get married seems to be directly related to social and world conditions.  It appears that, for instance, in times that directly following war and famine people seem to get married and have children at a younger age.  Maybe they''re more connected to a sense of their own mortality.  In times of relative peace and abundance, people have a chance to take their time with these types of important decisions.\nIn terms of when I got married, I needed to be sure that I was compatible with my spouse, and that he held the same view as I that marriage is not always easy, that it requires work, and that while it may not necessarily be "forever," it is a lifetime commitment that should not be taken lightly.  Aside from those core similarities, I needed to be certain in who I was and that I was able to convey that correctly so there were no surprises.  I''m sure I''d be divorced several times over at this point if I''d married each of the people I was involved with previously up until my current relationship or extremely miserable.', '08 Jul ''13, 20:09', 1),
