('100086759', '100081796', 'users/116220715/rohan-29', 'Hi,\nPlease post the video downloads at the same time as the courses modules go live.\nThis will help us ( in places where internet connectivity is not very good) to keep pace with our peers and hence participate in forum discussions.\nAlso, my course experience is much better when I download the videos before hand. getting the video to stream takes a lot of time to buffer, also the video quality is set at LOWEST, hence the content is fuzzy.\nI think the course instructors, susan, greg and lauren have put in a lot of effort in designing the modules. All that gets lost if I am not able to fuel my excitement of waiting for the Lauren''s email on the next module being available.', '09 Jul ''13, 20:41', 0),
('100086814', '100075348', 'users/100056883/sebastian-raschka', 'DNA (in the nucleus of the cell) is \nfirst transcribed by a particular machinery (called Ribosome) into the so-called mRNA, which is short for messenger RNA. RNA is somewhat similar to DNA, but one of its 4 Nucleotide is different, and it has a one chemical group of its backbone different (3''-OH instead, this is where the name DNA comes from btw.,  DNA stands for deoxyribonucleic acid, where RNA stands for just ribonucleic acid).\nOkay, so we transcribed DNA into mRNA. Genes are particular regions of DNA that contain the code to produce an mRNA of a defined size. This mRNA of a particular length is then "translated" into a protein.\nThe flow is like this: DNA(gene) -&gt; mRNA -&gt; Protein. \nDNA does not only consist of "genes", but also consists of regions that are not coding for something, or at least it is not known yet (in fact, 98% or so are not coding for proteins).\nAlso, mRNA is not the only form of RNA ... but this is a whole different stories.\nSo to summarize, GENES are the particular REGIONS on the DNA that have to code to produce proteins.', '09 Jul ''13, 22:56', 2),
