('100088016', '100085970', 'users/119644085/christopher-263', 'So, in Lesson 09, we''ve heard a lot about B. F. Skinner, not so much about Chomsky.\nIn response to the "you decide" section, I choose Skinner over Chomsky. Chomsky''s belief that the initial language learning was more of a "discovery" seems ill-fitting to me; is not anything learned in the first few years a "discovery" in and of itself? For instance, besides my native English language, I was also taught to count to 10 in Spanish. I was so young when this happened that I do not recall this learning process. Yet, whenever I was asked, the numbers 1-10 in Spanish would flow from my brain without a fight, in much the same way as I spoke my native language. I did not "discover" these ten words (in my opinion); they were deliberately taught to me, much in the same way that English (at the very least, the grammar aspect) is taught to younglings (consciously or not).\nMy siding with Skinner does not necessarily mean that I believe Skinner''s ideals to be accurate; rather, it is of my opinion that Chomsky''s ideals are considerably less accurate.', '11 Jul ''13, 20:00', 0),
