('100088135', '100085970', 'users/100115570/jeff-diamond', 'It''s a mixture; although I lean more toward Skinner.  \nWhen I was in the Navy I sent to the spy school in Monterey to learn Russian. There are 5 levels of difficulty in languages according to the DoD. Russian is a level-4 language. Spanish is level-2. French, German and Italian are level-3s. There is no "level-1" because that''s a person''s native language. For non-English speakers however, English is level-5 as is Arabic. \nI won''t even get into levels of ability.\nFast forward: After two months I began dreaming in Russian.  Later I also began (occasionally) to speak English in an odd structure and meter. Example: I was getting to know this girl and I wanted to ask, "So, where are you from?" --a common ice breaker. But instead, I asked her, "From where do you come" which was a literal English translation of the Russian sentence for the same thing.\nLikewise, my ability to speak Russian improved drastically when I started trying to think, and even affect an accent, like a Russian. The first time I spoke with a heavy accent (like a character from a movie) my teacher stopped still and stared at me, the classroom went quiet --they thought I was being a wise ass (I wasn''t). Still, a part of me thought I was about to be chewed out. Instead, he walked up to me and grabbed my arms and shook them. Then with a big smile he said, "Xorosho!"\nAnyway, that''s my story and I''m stickin'' to it!\nJ', '12 Jul ''13, 00:36', 0),
