('100090055', '100089909', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'Hi Cody,\nThe reason we used the term "welfare families" is because that is the name given to the group by the researchers. When discussing the research of others, we use the group names given by the researchers. instead of creating our own group names for their study and their participants.  In this study that was published in 1995, Hart and Risley categorized the children as coming from "professional, middle-class, or welfare" families; therefore, in order to present their study as they described it, we used their terms.  That is, it is not for to us to change the categorization from "welfare families" to "working poor" families because that is not how the original research defined their groups. Also, that distinction was an important part of their group assignment as they specifically wanted to study children who came from families that received government assistance and those that did not ,but that also varied in income (professional vs middle class). Therefore, "welfare families" and "working poor families" are fundamentally different in that one is getting government assistance and the other not. I hope this clarifies for you why we used their group names for describing the study.\nBest,\nDr. Snycerski', '15 Jul ''13, 18:04', 10),
