('100090262', '100085970', 'users/100031890/arun-kohli', 'Chomsky vs Skinner\nI believe that what Chomsky says about universal grammar is correct. I have seen in many different languages, I learned 12 of them, there is a certain universality. I do not agree with him though, that learning language is like an instinct that we humans have such as walking. He probably means talking is an instinct, if it is so, I do not need to distinguish between talking and language.\nSkinner on the other hand makes more sense because one needs to learn a language. I had to go to school at least 12 times for long periods to learn the languages. I could not acquire them. \nI have another thought: Giacomo Rizzolatti was working with Giuseppe Di Pellegrino and other scientist and during an experiment discovered the existence of mirror neurons in a monkey. This concept was extended to humans and V. S. Ramachandran has spoken a lot about it on TED and elsewhere. Is it possible that children have more mirror neurons up to a certain age? These may help them not only to emulate the adults and their care givers in physical aspects, but enable them to learn the language or languages spoken in their surroundings with such ease that it seems as if they were acquiring them? With age, just as our hearing  ability changes, so it may be that mirror neurons reduce in numbers and then we need to learn the language?\nFascinating stuff, love this course!', '16 Jul ''13, 07:11', 0),
