('100090317', '100086661', 'users/117578412/greg-feist', 'This is a great discussion and glad to see it produced thoughtful responses. As with all debates it comes down to definitions and if you broaden the definition wide enough to basically mean any life form is intelligent then I guess you could do that. Psychologists tend not to use quite so broad of a definition, because it also requires things like "working memory" and "abstract reasoning". But clearly all life forms with nervous systems are intelligent. But I think biologists and other scholars would debate and not all would agree on non-nervous system life forms and intelligence. But the debate is good and healthy! Keep it up. It''s what education is about!', '16 Jul ''13, 09:50', 3),
('100090325', '100066604', 'users/125525748/nemesis-fixx', 'I think it''d be worth exploring the psychology behind these social behaviors. \nFor example, in the neighborhood where I rent, it''s common knowledge that unless if one of the residents is your friend, hardly does anyone raise alarm when a burglary is taking place at someone else''s home. It''s like, people don''t wish to [risk] getting involved in preventing negativity if they have no reward to gain. But I might be wrong, though the behavior I describe is common place here.', '16 Jul ''13, 10:13', 0),
('100090364', '100084567', 'users/127539719/javier-187', 'REINFORCEMENT: something you do to increase some given pattern. If you add something  in order to achieve so, then it''s called positive reinforcement, for example you give somebody a tip for helping you with your bags (he helps you, then he gets a tip. In the future he will keep willing to help you). If you remove something in order to achieve so, then it''s called negative reinforcement, for example, you tell you wife "since you have been behaving very good lately, I am gonna do the dishes all this week". (she is good, then she doesnt have to do the dishes, so she will bahave good in the future to avoid doing the dishes)\nPUNISHMENT: something you do in order to decrease some given pattern. If you add something in order to do so, then it''s called positive punishment, for example, somebody doesnt help you with your bags, you give him a punch. ( so he will certainly help you in the future). If you remove something in order to do so, then it''s called negative punishement, for example you tell your wife " you have been behaving badly lately, so you cant watch your favorite soap opera for a week", (she has been bad, so you dont let her watch her favorite soap, so she will will go back to behaving good again very quick)\nOk, so back to the pipe example. we want to decrease a pattern, which is the noise of the pipe. when we do something to decrease something it''s called a punishment. And we do it by hitting in the pipe, which is an active action, then it''s a positive punishment.\nImagine a tv set, or radio  which was blury with White noise or statics, you hit it, and the signal gets clear again, that would be a positive reinforcement, we add something (hitting the tv set or radio set ) and increase something (the signal quality)', '16 Jul ''13, 11:58', 0),
('100090415', '100090174', 'users/122929792/greta-4', 'I think about it like that: independent variable is an input, it doesn''t depend on people that is in experiment, it is the same no matter what they do, what result will be. And depended depends on people''s behavior, it can change, we don''t know for sure  what will happen. \nit is often used used term :)\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependent_and_independent_variables', '16 Jul ''13, 13:46', 1),
