('100090918', '100089951', 'users/117523005/judy-12', 'In my field - foreign language education - critical thinking can be taught through appropriately structured activities for students - they do language based activities while at the same time exercising critical thinking.   Critical thinking is vital for participating in university/college level courses, in order to evaluate, and therefore to apply, theoretical ideas. Many education systems do not activate this kind of thinking in students, preferring to rely on rote memory tests as activities in class. While it''s important to train memory, other cognitive skills are important to function in the world of higher education and work, not to mention social relationships.  So the short answer is yes - you can train critical thinking!', '17 Jul ''13, 13:46', 1),
('100090930', '100088742', 'users/117523005/judy-12', '@Tung Yen - You are confusing intelligence and personality. Gardner''s theory of multiple intelligences is not about personality or even measurement in an exact sense. Rather, a person can be said to have a profile of intelligences - in other words, you can "score" something in each category. Let''s imagine a quick (and not very scientific) test - how would you rate yourself out of ten in each category (0= low intelligence or ability, 10 = the highest)?  Here''s mine : Linguistic 9, visual 9, interpersonal 9, intrapersonal 8, kinesthetic 4, musical 3, naturalistic 3 mathematical logical 7. So a person can be both highly intelligent in both interpersonal and intrapersonal intelligences. Gardner''s book Frames of Mind is an accessible and fascinating read. And there are plenty of multiple intelligences questionnaires online - some more valid than others. The more questions the better, is a rough guide to validity. I found R.M. Felder and B.A. Soloman, North Carolina State University to be a good one. Have fun!', '17 Jul ''13, 13:59', 4),
('100090936', '100064253', 'users/117523005/judy-12', '@Richard Keirnan: Some of this course is too basic for me, and other  parts very instructive - but I signed up for a general introduction. And that''s exactly what this is. If you wanted more challenge then you are obviously taking the wrong course. Remember that learning should be tailored to each person''s needs, and the guys at Udacity can''t know what everyone needs. It''s up to you to make an intelligent decision about whether this is the right course for you. So I for one  am having fun and find it brilliant. The guys are doing a great job.', '17 Jul ''13, 14:05', 0),
