('100092336', '100087263', 'users/100242689/karin-liau', 'That''s the doing of your brain and how it perceives visual sensations.\nOver the years you or better: your brain has learned by experience that objects visibly become smaller the farer away they are. The truck picture is showing you a perspective you may perceive as an 3-dimensional view, even if it''s just a 2-dimensional picture.\nYour brain tricks you in a way by automatically thinking you''d see a real life view on a street. Thinking "it''s just an illusion" by yourself could help a bit, but can not entirely override your brain activity.\nIn short: Your brain says that objects of the same size must look smaller the farer away the are. But the trucks are in fact the same size. Which makes your brain perceive the truck in the back (the one the left) as the biggest one.', '20 Jul ''13, 10:23', 6),
