('100093357', '100093166', 'users/128569738/roxanne-5', 'I find dreaming often represents my subconscious - providing me with answers I am looking for or reveals emotions I am experiencing.\nI believe strongly in dream interpretation as sometimes it reveals things we don''t necessarily want to hear or presents a side of ourselves / others / a situation we do not want to see.\nI could be wrong, but when you do those things (watch English movies or football), you stimulate your brain in a way that''s out of the ordinary (different from your everyday routine) - so when you''re sleeping, it''s probably still on your mind and your subconscious is processing everything you''ve just experienced.\nLike when I''m studying for exams and I read something before I go to bed, I might have a dream related to it (eg. water - signifies your emotions - pay attention to what the water is doing - is it stormy or calm - this will reveal how you are really feeling even if you do not allow yourself to experience it fully).', '22 Jul ''13, 15:12', 5),
('100093361', '100065293', 'users/100239659/sal-dekku', 'Hi Francis.\nIn a double blind, researchers do not know which group is which during the experiment. However, they make sure to have a way to find out when they need to draw the results.\nA trivial example might be that you have two boxes of coffee pods, one with decaf, the other with normal coffee. The boxes are perfectly alike and the packages are covered with a sticker or adhesive tape so that you can''t read if you''re using decaf or not. After the experiment, you can remove the sticker and find out about it.\nIf  you want to be extra sure, you can pay somebody external to the group conducting the experiment to apply the stickers. But you can form the groups yourself: it''s not important to know which group is which, just that the two groups are split using an unbiased criterion: in the coffee example, you just need to form two groups, it''s not important to know which one will get the decaf. You can perform the experiment even if nobody knows that.', '22 Jul ''13, 15:36', 0),
