('100093563', '100068557', 'users/100031956/jetishie', 'I first thought the same because that way, so that you won''t have any "innate" difference of subjects, one who have faster reaction time over the other innately if you measure and compare the "before" and "after"\nHowever, we cannot ignore the "learning" process of human. Especially such thing as reaction time can dramatically decrease as the subjects reacts more often. I think that''s why they made it only "5 times" so that the learning won''t be too effective.\nMoreover, the groups of subjects are based on "norms." The range of subjects does not vary from super human to sloths, they are just ordinary human natures I believe, so measuring the way they did, and averaging out the reaction times of each groups are quire sounding and suitable method for this kind of experiment.\nI don''t know well enough about the actual method they used or better baseline foundation, but I hope what I said made some kind of sense to help you :)', '23 Jul ''13, 06:01', 1),
