('100093848', '100093635', 'users/120886410/calvin-41', 'Good point, but there is something that coordinates the order in which people arrive. As Lauren states in this video, "there is something innately different about those two groups [the early versus later group]." What she means here is that there is likely a fundamental difference between those two groups that is evidenced by when they showed up. For example, if the study is conducted in the morning, maybe the early group is likely to be morning people who, at that time, are more lively and awake than the later group. This could mean they have a faster reaction time. This is just one possible example of a difference in these two groups. I would think that this bias is more likely than flipping heads 90% of the time. Maybe a compromise would be to put them in groups based on a pre-determined order, such as every other participant gets caffeine. Since the participants don''t really interact, my guess is that this would be a valid way to randomize the assignment.', '23 Jul ''13, 18:57', 0),
