('100093983', '100093663', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'What a great question! The short answer to your question is no, but I think you''ve conflated two issues:\n1) Every individual has two copies of every gene, one from mom and one from dad (except genes on the X or Y chromosome if you''re a male, and except mitochondrial genes which only come from the mother). So if light and dark colored skin were caused by one gene, then the offspring would have to get a copy of that gene from each parent.\n2) A trait being monogenic doesn''t mean that there isn''t "blending" of traits. Because you have two copies of each allele, if you had a dark copy and a light copy, they could mix to be in-between; or the dark copy could win out over the light copy, or the other way around. It all depends on the kind of copy that it is. This sort of phenomenon is called "dominance" and there are many different categories: complete/simple dominance, codominance, incomplete dominance, etc. Each describes a different interactions between the two copies of a gene. So even if there were only one gene, the differences could combine in many different ways.\nHope this helps clear it up.', '24 Jul ''13, 02:26', 7),
