('100095870', '100095376', 'users/129034155/sylvia-9', 'Okay, so I don''t know how to explain the values 20-600 (it''s something to do with distances and focus of the pupil but I learned that a long time ago and I''m no longer quite sure how it works) but what it means is that a baby will see things extremly close to its eyes as "sharp" and things that are just a little further away as "blurry".\nI don''t have kids but some of my friends have kids and I know what you mean by them (less than 2 years old) to be fascinated with colors - but (and I think this is in the video) they actually aren''t fascinated with the colors but with the high contrast created by bright colors. \nYou could see this yourself: If you take a picture made of bright colors (maybe bright pink house, on a bright blue sky and green lawn) and transform it into grayscale (which is closer to how a baby sees the world) you will still be able to see the house and see a difference between the sky and the lawn. Now if you take the same picture made with muted colors and transform it - you have a very hard time to still pick out the house.\nWell, I had a little time and made an image that shows what I discribe above.', '27 Jul ''13, 16:11', 7),
