('100098584', '100098529', 'users/129034155/sylvia-9', 'Okay, those two questions aren''t easy to answer but this is my opinion on them:\nWell, why was is once considered a disorder?\nIf you are straight, the idea of being attracted to your own sex is simply strange. You might not be able to understand "how" someone can feel this way. And since the majority of people are straight this mindset was pretty much everywhere and so this is "normal" while anything that deviates from "normal" is considered "abnormal". With this way of looking at it, you can view homosexuality as a disorder (which is by definition "abnormal").\nSo, why isn''t homosexualtity a disorder?\nOnce white people thought that people of color (particularly Black-Africans) where simply "stupid" - because what they considered "normal" wasn''t present in a lot of tribes. For example a written language, cloths, or modern tools. The african way of living was "abnormal" to them, so they figuered that this meant black people had fewer mental abilities than white people.\nIn both cases someone decided to impose their world view as the gold standard of "normal".  And in both cases there is no hard and fast evidence to show this assumption is true. There are a lot of smart people who are black (W.A. Lewis won the noble price in economics). And no one was able to show homosexuality as the result of any physiological abnormality. Actually homosexuality has been present though thousands of years (probably always but we can''t prove that) and it is not a "trait" that has been lost through evolution. And in a lot of animals homosexual behavior is pretty normal (giraffes, even primates). \nIf one considers all the research and knowledge today, viewing homosexuality as a disorder is not possible. \nWe (should) know now that even if something isn''t average or present in the majority, it can still be "normal". \nI know that sadly both of the prejudice I described are still around today - it just doesn''t make either one true or proveable.', '01 Aug ''13, 18:50', 3),
