('100099025', '100098583', 'users/100119986/anthony-21', 'Among developed nations, we diagnose ( I may go so far as to say over-diagnose) ADHD by a wide margin.\nIt is my opinion that kids, as much as we may want them to at times, are not meant to be politely trained robots that read, sit, speak, and eat when you want them to.  In my experience, some parents face difficulty in dealing with spirited children and think that there''s something wrong with the child.\nTheir inability to handle a seemingly normal child leads them to consider medicating their kids.  It scares me b/c they don''t realize the type of harm they can do to the kid.  In these cases, their willingness to medicate their child is not to make the child better, it''s to make life easier for the parent through a method of control all because the parent can''t face the insecurity of having to put in a lot of work to actually parent a child.\nThis is just my experience (limited sample size) that discuss my encounters with parents that choose to medicate their children.  As you can probably tell, it''s not objective and there''s a bit of bias.\nHowever, in an objective look at ADD/ADHD, search ADHD diagnosis by country, shows that we tend to lead diagnosis in the condition among developed nations.  Joseph Biederman, Professor of Psychiatry at HMS, had one of his papers on ADD/ADHD rated as one of the most cited papers in the world.  Biederman kiiiind of....forgot...to mention that he took in over a million dollars in money from pharmaceutical companies.  You can read about it here: Researchers Fail to Reveal Full Drug Pay\nI find it shocking that this diagnosis tends to be a mostly American thing and can''t help but suspect some sort of conflict of interest at play at the expense of children - children who may not fully comprehend what is going on.', '02 Aug ''13, 18:31', 16),
