('100099214', '100098004', 'users/100031890/arun-kohli', 'I was born in India and live in Germany. In India as a rule you show respect for elders. When some elderly people join a group many will stand up to greet them and their body language shows they are ready to accept them as the wise. Whereas in Germany if elderly people enter a similar group, people do not show interest. The intention is not to say which is better because I have my reservations about both sides. The idea is to talk about how different we behave due to influence of other: cultural impact. Joe Henrich, Steven Heine and Ara Norenzayan published their study on how human beings behave differently due to cultural influences. http://www.psmag.com/magazines/pacific-standard-cover-story/joe-henrich-weird-ultimatum-game-shaking-up-psychology-economics-53135/.', '03 Aug ''13, 07:54', 3),
('100099228', '100097455', 'users/100020586/sabine-miehlbradt', 'Yes. That way you can sure that someone does call. If several people are there for some reason they all think someone else has already done it.\nI''ve actually been in a situation where an old  lady was lying unconscious (but breathing and uninjured)  on the road and you can really see that people are just milling around until someone takes charge and says: you do this, you do that. I have also noticed that once some people start doing something the rest sort of fall in.\nThat one time it was near freezing so I took my jacket and put it under her head. Then I asked the man next to me if he would not mind covering her with his and within literally seconds half a dozen people took off their coats and jackets and carefully covered her neck to toe to keep her warm. Others had started to divert traffic around her and the group was being an effective fence so she did not get hit by a car.\nThat one ended up with me lying next to her (so to be close to her face) and talking reassuringly to her. She was regaining consciousness by then so I was relaying messages between her and her husband, who was too infirm to  go down on a freezing road. Within minutes a trained nurse happened by so she relieved me and the ambulance was not far behind.\nI learned in the paper the next day that it was a mild seizure and that she was recovering nicely.  It wasn''t her first, so I understood why the husband had been so calm.', '03 Aug ''13, 08:50', 1),
