('100099645', '100099158', 'users/100031890/arun-kohli', 'This is great question for present times where people move easily from one country to another and become foreigner or alien residents. I have done it for the last 37 years in six different countries on four continents. I realized that the feeling of inferiority is self generated. It is a form of social perception how others perceive you and it definitely has to be dispositional. It is likely to be due to lack of identification with the group, that people land up living in. I have seen a few friend from Turkey in Germany and they were aggressive towards the German system. I have German relatives in Austria, they feel the same way about the Austrians as my Turkish friend about the Germans. I read a book long back from a philosopher, forgotten the name now, who explained this phenomenon of the guest visitor hating the host community as a very normal occurrence in mixed societies. I stated to monitor my own attitudes and attributions. I found helping out in the community on honorary basis opens a lots of doors and gets you a lots of friends. I am convinced that if your friends seek out some work where they can help out the locals even twice or thrice a month for a couple of hours, they will be looked at friends, equals and very wanted people in the society. They may start wondering about the inferiority complex themselves.', '04 Aug ''13, 09:10', 5),
