('100099859', '100099171', 'users/100020046/code_jamer', 'Ok here is how it works as per my understanding:-\nInformation transfer from one neuron to another involves mainly two parts of a neuron:\n1- Dendrites:\nThese receive the information from another neuron.\nThe information received by the dendrite is in the form of chemicals which are of different types and are called neurotransmitters. \nThe neurotransmitters travel through the synapse or synaptic cleft which is the space between the terminal button (ending) of one neuron and the dendrite (starting point) of the other neuron\nThe dendrites contain receptors which receive the neurotransmitters from the synaptic cleft.\nThe receptors are also of different types. Meaning that there are specific receptors who receive only specific type of neurotransmitters and not of other types.\n2-Terminal buttons:\nThese are the endings of a neuron.\nThey release the neurotransmitters (chemical information to be accepted at the dendrites of the other/second neuron) into the synaptic cleft.\nWithin the neuron:\nThe information within the neuron is in the form of an electric impulse.\nThis process is repeated when ever there is a transfer of information in neurons of the brain.\nHope it helps!', '04 Aug ''13, 20:49', 1),
