('100100298', '100096191', 'users/118076567/diego-114', 'I agree that the theory that states if you don''t have a word for a concept the concept is not understandable is hard to accept.\nBut your example of "a word that doesn''t exist" is exactly with a word that does exist.\nSo I don''t think "schadenfreude" fits as a perfect example for that, since the word is used in the English speaking countries (and in many non-English speaking countries as well). Just because it comes from German, it doesn''t mean English has not incorporated the word. It''s the same case for "pizza" for instance.', '05 Aug ''13, 18:37', 1),
