('100100376', '100092655', 'users/119146441/sarah-129', 'There are many different ways to look at this particular issue. In this case, however, I think Dr. Zeligs is not saying that training them is better than just letting them doing their own thing in the wild. She''s saying that with animals in captivity, animal husbandry is a far better option than other crueler and more brutal methods of research.', '05 Aug ''13, 22:28', 1),
('100100381', '100073352', 'users/130893700/paton', 'my parents age at marriage, fathers age at least 10 years older and my mother was in her early twenties. They were happily married with 5 children till my father died in in 1997 .  my mother continued in her career as a teacher only stopping for each of the children and returned as soon as possible to teaching.  My father was very active in our upbringing and as a Farmer thought nothing of it', '05 Aug ''13, 22:35', 0),
('100100390', '100089779', 'users/118232219/sourav-3', 'Hi Diego,\nThanks for responding to the question.\nI don''t think getting this answer right or wrong will not prove or disprove Bouba / Kiki Effect but I will humour you anyway. Is the second one Mamoo? Do let me know.\nAlso an essential thing about Bouba / Kiki Effect and my question is not about the present time but the dawn of naming things and agreeing on the names, i.e. Language. Even if Bouba / Kiki Effect were true then, the languages have gone through way too many transformations since then to still retain the traces of the effect.\nHope I made sense.', '05 Aug ''13, 23:22', 1),
('100100393', '100062184', 'users/100003038/julesflwr-1', 'I think the conflation of introversion with avoidance of risky and stimulating activities is incorrect. I am a person who has occasionally\nfelt overwhelmed in loud,  overly stimulating indoor environments and among socially climbing people.  Yet I have always sought out\nand enjoyed highly stimulating outdoor activities like skiing, mountain climbing, sky diving, hang gliding, scuba diving, surfing,\nfield hockey, softball, etc.  I have also traveled to West Africa as a Peace Corps volunteer.  Although just about everyone labeled me\nas  shy and an introvert as a young person, I think that most of the people I interact with now would not label me as shy.  I think\nthat psychological labels can be very misleading and can prevent some people from obtaining appropriate assistance in dealing\nwith difficult life situations.', '05 Aug ''13, 23:39', 0),
('100100415', '100100377', 'users/117222955/christine-58', 'I remember my kindergarten teacher using token economy to make us focus on our work. The more work we do, the longer recess we get.\nI also use this method on the kids I tutor. They easily they distracted so I reward with a ticket for all the workbook pages they finish in an hour period (usually their session period). By the end of the week, they can turn in their tickets for prizes (erasers, pencils, snacks, etc) or they can keep accumulating them for a bigger reward (puzzles, break time, etc).', '06 Aug ''13, 01:09', 3),
('100100417', '100093874', 'users/116393908/lucas-87', 'In my opinion it really depends of many factors like age, personal dreams/goals, family, assets, and others. I mean, if you already have most of the goods/assets you think you need maybe money will not be a high priority. Or if you have a family, maybe you can think that it''s better to have a high paid job, so you can afford a better life for them. Or you will prefer a low paid job if it gives you more time and flexibility to be with your relatives. Also it can be different for each person as not everyone feels rewarded at the same way by spending time with family.\nI think that when the money is used to achieved owns plans or buy things that will really help the person to be more happy, or to have a better life, maybe it''s worth to have a not so much enjoyable job that pays higher. But it is different from the situation where people keep jobs they don''t like and then compulsively spend their money; in many cases they don''t enjoy either the job or the money.', '06 Aug ''13, 01:13', 3),
('100100431', '100093579', 'users/116393908/lucas-87', 'Masturbation can become into a compulsive activity, usually to people who already tends to develop compulsive behaviors. Same thing can occur to sex, and other kind of activities. In some cases it can really be a bad thing and hurt/harm the person and his or her psychological health. I think these cases are quite rare, and most of times are transitory/temporary, but not always.\nAnyway, this can be an interesting example about different cultural views regarding sex.', '06 Aug ''13, 01:55', 0),
('100100435', '100099657', 'users/129525164/kin-onn', 'I don''t think the word tabula rasa or term slate originated from Steven Pinker. The words are certainly popularised by him. These terms have been used by the "nurture" proponents with usually a hint of sinister agenda. The extreme application of the "nurture" would be the Pol Pot regime in Cambodia, which tried to invert the concept of family and even the sexes. They believe that hey since everyone starts with a blank slate, why not do a social experiment (on a mass scale) on cambodian children and maybe utopia will follow. Needless to say the results were disastarous.', '06 Aug ''13, 02:17', 0),
('100100436', '100092655', 'users/118076567/diego-114', 'Still, saying that "it''s not good, but it could be worse" is not a very good argument in defense of what she''s doing. She''s just using the animal for her own benefit. \nMost people have the assumption that "animal cruelty" would mean having pleasure beating up an animal till it bleeds. Of course, this is cruelty indeed (and pretty sick as well), but imposing stress in other ways such as separating from parents, taking away from their habitat, teaching tricks that have no other purposes that entertaining people, just to name a few examples, would also qualify as cruelty. \nThe kiss that she gives on the cheek of the professors is not a real kiss, and for me it''s not fun to watch that at all. It does serve as a good example for the subject taught in this lesson, but it also raises ethical issues.', '06 Aug ''13, 02:18', 0),
('100100443', '100089779', 'users/118076567/diego-114', 'What I have studied in linguistics (Saussure) is exactly the opposite, that the words are arbitrary. I confess the Bouba/ Kiki effect is a new subject for me, but it''s interesting. It just seems to me that there might be a huge number of details missing in the evaluation of the causes for the results they got, for example, the shape of the letters associated with the sounds; they could have changed the vowels or just the consonants; they could have done it with dozens of other syllable combinations.\nBut if you take other languages you will see that the similarities are due to the same origin, for example the word "love" in portuguese, italian and french: amor, amore, amour (they all come from latin). But compare it now with finnish, romanian and japanese: rakkaus, dragoste, ai.\nAnd it''s interesting to notice that even onomatopoeias differ from language to language. (knock knock in portuguese is toki toki).\nI still think is an interesting theory, but it needs more data in order to be more reliable. So far the only thing that it shows is that people tend to associate bouba with a round shape and kiki with a star shape. Apart from that, the conclusions one might get from that are merely speculations. \nBut now you proved the theory. Yes, mammoo is the second one.  ; )', '06 Aug ''13, 02:52', 2),
('100100445', '100089779', 'users/118232219/sourav-3', 'Thanks for the thoughtful reply and as I said me being right in this exercise doesn''t prove or disprove the Bouba / Kiki Effect.\nThis theory excites me because it says that there might be an intrinsic connection between how things look and what they were called (NOT talking about the correlation of how letters look and how they sound, because written alphabet came much later) in the earliest days of human evolution. (Exactly the opposite of what Saussure says). \nAnd No, I don''t have enough support to prove or disprove this.', '06 Aug ''13, 03:04', 2),
