('100101014', '100099604', 'users/130873283/bryan-150', 'Piggybacking to @Code_Jamer, a common misconception is that natural selection is the survival of the fittest. But as stated above, it''s more about who''s best suited for an environment. So if being slower or smaller meant surviving longer and reproducing, that could be a path a species takes. Also worth noting is that natural selection occurs because of preexisting mutations; conversely, if you don''t have the necessary preexisting genetic mutation for your environment, you may not survive and reproduce. Lastly, remember natural selection and ,more broadly, evolution occur on a population level, not the individual level', '07 Aug ''13, 09:06', 2),
('100101021', '100100988', 'users/127053095/carlos-303', 'I think you should tell between retrograde and anterograde memory.  If you have anterograde amnesia, there''s a point in the past that AFTER that you don''t remember anything, in fact you can''t form new memories (typically because you have damaged your hippocampus).   But if you suffer from retrograde memory there''s a point in the past BEFORE that you lose some memories.  So you can lose your memories during an event because this point in the past is just after this event, or this event was so traumatic that caused you having retrograde amnesia, that includes forgetting this very event.\nFor example, when I was a child I was run over by a car, and I''ve never remembered this accident (I only haver memories from the hospital), and it''s possible that I also lost some memories from before the accident, which would be retrograde amnesia.', '07 Aug ''13, 09:27', 2),
('100101026', '100100813', 'users/130873283/bryan-150', 'Well it''s not as simple as was stated in the video. It''s not just pure brown or pure blue. Brown is the dominant gene while blue is the recessive. So say your grandma has brown eyes and your grandpa has blue. Since your mom has brown eyes, in this example, brown is expressed but she''s also a carrier for blue eyes. We write this as Bb, B is brown and b is blue. Your dad would just be bb because if he had a big B, he''d automatically have brown eyes (Brown is dominant, remember?). Now when you and your siblings were made, half your eye color genes came from mom and half from dad. We would write this as Bb x bb. Now taking one from mom and one from dad, possible offspring eye color combinations are Bb, Bb, bb, and bb or just Bb and bb. In other words, 50% brown and 50% blue. So, you''d expect for half of you guys to have brown eyes and half blue, right? Actually, it''s more like each kid has a 50/50 chance of having brown or blue. In your guys case, it''s like someone flipped a coin a bunch of times and it kept landing on heads. Though this seems unlikely, the result of the current coin flip has nothing to do with the previous one. Genetics is messy and confusing, but I hope this is helpful. If not, feel free to ask questions. For everyone else, if you can find a simpler way to explain or find any mistakes in this explanation, I myself would be extremely grateful.', '07 Aug ''13, 09:40', 0),
('100101031', '100100850', 'users/126278157/amanda-69', 'Take a look at this video: https://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-ps001/l-292662527/m-290926633', '07 Aug ''13, 10:00', 2),
