('100101421', '100101131', 'users/120886410/calvin-41', 'You''re correct in that drugs can be used to alleviate biological symptoms and psychotherapy can be used to manage arousal or otherwise treat psychological aspects, but the question is not quite asking for that.\nThis question is not worded very clearly; it asks for an example of a psychological form of treatment that alleviates symptoms and sometimes cures disorders. A combination of drugs and psychotherapies is not an example of a psychological form. Does that make sense?', '07 Aug ''13, 21:48', 0),
('100101434', '100100377', 'users/100119986/anthony-21', 'I''ve been subject to acting as a recipient in a token economy as well - specifically relating to school work as a young child.\nLooking back, while it was effective at getting me to do the work in the short run, the motivation was extrinsic and may not have been the best thing for me in the long run.  The values of the tokens needed to be increased - diminishing returns on accumulating tokens of the same size.  A lack of a token could cause conflicts or lack of interest in task at hand.\nI think there is more value to be gained for the recipient if a potential token supplier can expose intrinsic value (learning is awesome!) in doing school work (make it more fun and less like work).', '07 Aug ''13, 22:20', 2),
('100101439', '100101131', 'users/117262389/silvina-1', 'Sorry, but if you look for Psychotherapy in wikipedia it''s said: \n"Psychotherapy is a general term referring to therapeutic interaction or treatment contracted between a trained professional and a client, patient, family, couple, or group. The problems addressed are psychological in nature and can vary in terms of their causes, influences, triggers, and potential resolutions. Accurate assessment of these and other variables is dependent on the practitioner''s capability and can change or evolve as the practitioner acquires greater experience, knowledge, and insight.\nWhat do you think?', '07 Aug ''13, 22:24', 0),
('100101466', '100100557', 'users/100119986/anthony-21', 'Thank you very much for putting together the course.  In spite of some of the press, I feel that what I got out of the course was related (correlated??) to what I was willing to put into the course.  \nThe grade(s) weren''t as important as the knowledge gained in understanding psychology.  I felt like you three ( as well as the udacity olympians and others behind the scenes) did a very good job of making psychology interesting and fun.\nKudos.', '07 Aug ''13, 23:08', 1),
('100101505', '100101010', 'users/118967285/jelena-16', 'Thanks, I got it :)', '08 Aug ''13, 00:10', 0),
('100101514', '100099922', 'users/118577135/jamie-77', 'My best guess would be that Dangerousness is not used because Dysfunction already covers risk to self or risk to others. I think Disturbance refers more to something out of step with reality. \nDeviance differs from Disturbance in that people may have very unusual or unique thoughts or behaviors but still be functional and capable of taking care of themselves. They may be odd, but they are not always out of touch with the world around them. A search on eccentricity and eccentric people would probably turn up some things on deviance as well.', '08 Aug ''13, 00:38', 0),
('100101529', '100098583', 'users/118577135/jamie-77', 'Children do fidget, but disorders are also on a spectrum. There can be different degrees sometimes it''s difficult to decide where to draw the line. A trained psychologist should know to take many factors and context into account when making a diagnosis such as home life, social life, or classroom. The developmental stage should also be taken into account in order to understand what is reasonably expected of a kid. Obviously, just having a fidgety kid doesn''t automatically mean they have ADHD. If I remember, there are also different types of ADD so hyperactivity doesn''t always have to be the defining feature of an ADD child.\nAnd while it is true that some are misdiagnosed and that there are some parents that could take more responsibility, I imagine it''s harder to ask for therapy than for medication and that insurance is more likely to cover medication. Sometimes it''s not a parent''s willingness, it''s also a struggle for them because of the resources available or the information they''ve been given. I think it''s better to take the therapy when possible because of what it does in the long run and leave medication as the last thing you go to.\nAnd as for the reported increase in diagnosis in the USA, I''ve heard conflicting things but I go to an international school and I know that diagnostic criteria is tighter in some countries (ie England) than in others. This contributes some, but not entirely to the difference.', '08 Aug ''13, 01:32', 0),
('100101560', '100100635', 'users/121166559/iulia-5', 'Hi. \nI think i got your point now, and i think it depends on how you look at it. \nThe need for hunger and shelter are some of the basic, but you also need to look at the degree in which they were satisfied. Germany wasn''t food-less or shelter-less, what it lacked completely though was social interaction without the context of war. \nThis can be observed in the case of post-communist Romania. After the fall of the regime, people engaged in those activities that were forbidden or unavailable before, cinema being one of them (under Ceausescu''s ruling, the only works of art permitted were ones praising him and the regime).', '08 Aug ''13, 02:42', 2),
