('100102860', '100100702', 'users/100020586/sabine-miehlbradt', 'At least they are better than the disease. I suppose the idea of someone opening your abdomen and taking out a part should be scary, too. But is is less scary than a sepsis from an infected appendix.\nAll medical treatment should be applied at minimum necessary levels. Yet even that is not always possible - in cancer treatment, the cancer is surgically removed with some room to spare to be as sure as possible to have removed all the malignant cells and the following chemo- or radiotherapy also uses the shotgun approach in the hope of eradicating the cancerous cells while leaving enough healthy cells alive to have the patient survive. Currently we can do no better.\nThe suicide is actually a sign of healing. With for instance SSRIs the lethargy of depression is lifted before the mood improves so a patient is likelier to take action. Couple this with a reduced impulse control, as in a teenager and you have a side effect of suicide. The easiest way to prevent this is to have the patient in a hospital for the first 2 weeks of therapy or otherwise under close observation. Informing the patient and his environment of the danger is also helpful.', '11 Aug ''13, 12:28', 6),
('100102870', '100100612', 'users/100020586/sabine-miehlbradt', 'That was my first thought, too.\nBut I suppose you can do it with the patients consent. I seem to remember its use in treatment of alcohol dependency. There are many drunks who wish to break the habit but cannot control their impulse. What the doctor does is give them alcohol with something that induces vomiting. Pretty soon they cannot ingest alcohol without throwing it up at once.\nPretty bitter medicine but if it is done with consent it''ll surely make a persons life easier.', '11 Aug ''13, 13:03', 2),
('100102887', '100101036', 'users/100020586/sabine-miehlbradt', 'It''s most likely a matter of debate.\nI''d say it was self-inflated pride because he felt pride about an extrinsic event (pay rise) instead of an intrinsic. Much is in the wording of the question.\nIf it had been worded something like:\n\nJohn told his friend that his output had improved by 25% during\nthe last fiscal year and that he''d gotten a pay rise as a recognition\nand used the extra money to buy himself a new car\n\nthe answer would probably have been authentic pride.\nWhere''s the course on examology? Shouldn''t that be a special branch of psychology anyway?', '11 Aug ''13, 13:53', 0),
