('100104704', '100104221', 'users/117476074/b-mohan', 'Thank you - the course was very informative. The content and presentation by all the 3 tutors excellent.  Having said this, these courses will get compared with other courses being offered by other platforms .\nThe feedback is:\n1. Some questions can be better structured especially those with the " fill in the blanks" - since there are possibilities of multiple interpretations, a set of choice words can be provided, to make machine correction easier. \n2. The collateral,supplemental material and other assignments can be more, and weaved into the course appropriately.\n3. Regular communication on " Next What " is required, else  students will disconnect fast. The tutors would get a feel from the forum discussions / posts. \n4. A clear sense of direction for the course is needed, with clear milestones\nAll the hard work may come to a naught, if the critical links in the chain are not ironed out soon. Just as a good idea is important, so also is execution !', '16 Aug ''13, 23:23', 0),
('100104796', '100093635', 'users/137220243/kathleen-28', 'This is one of the problems I have with the MOOC concept because I thought the same thing as Conor.  Sometimes I feel there is not enough relevant information in simple multiple choice questions, while if you were in an actual class or even an online class you could email the instructor and say, "well, is anybody coordinating groups? Are people arriving at the same time?" Because if you just emailed all the participants and said "this experiment will begin at 8" and then did assign them by who arrived first, it would produce two random groups of equal size.  Flipping a coin isn''t that great because like Conor said if one group size is significantly larger than the other it weakens the results of your findings. \nKate', '17 Aug ''13, 11:36', 0),
('100104806', '100093635', 'users/120886410/calvin-41', 'Sorry the explanation for this problem isn''t very good. This question is trying to make the point that if you did just tell people to show up at eight, then the group of people who are earlier or later has an inherent difference.  Nobody is "coordinating" morning people or anything like that; they would still have an difference. By knowing that someone will show up in the early half versus the later half tells you that there is some innate difference in those people that could skew the results. The purpose of this question was to point out that there could be these differences and that you would want something supposedly random to choose. Choosing the early group or later group is NOT random.', '17 Aug ''13, 12:25', 0),
