('100105532', '100070783', 'users/137736360/vipin-2', 'Working memory is an advanced concept  which replaced the general concept of short term memory with an active maintenance of information in the short term storage. Working memory is also the premise for what allows us to do everyday activities involving thought. It is the section of memory where we carry out thought processes and use them to learn and reason about topics. \nWorking memory consists of three basic stores: the central executive, the phonological loop and the visuo-spatial sketchpad and the episodic buffer. The phonological loop stores auditory information by silently rehearsing sounds or words in a continuous loop: the articulatory process (for example the repetition of a telephone number over and over again) which makes a short list of data easier to remember. The visuo-spatial sketchpad stores visual and spatial information. It is engaged when performing spatial tasks (such as judging heights or distances) or visual ones (such as counting the windows on a house or imagining architectural plans or images). The prefrontal cortex has long been thought to subserve both working memory (the holding of information online for processing) and "executive" functions (deciding how to manipulate working memory and perform processing). The episodic buffer is dedicated to linking information across domains to form integrated units of visual, spatial, and verbal information and chronological ordering (e.g., the memory of a essay or a movie scene). The episodic buffer is also assumed to have links to long-term memory and semantical meaning.\nWhen considering the frontal lobes in regards to memory, we see that it is very important in the coordination of information. Therefore, the frontal lobes are important in working memory. For example, when you are thinking about how to get to a new city you have never been to before, you combine various bits of knowledge you already have: the layout of the city, information from a map, knowledge of traffic patterns in that area and conversations with your friends about the location of the city. By actively using all of this information, you can determine the best route for you to take. This action involves the controlled use of information in working memory, coordinated by the frontal lobes. \nThe hippocampus is important for explicit memory. The hippocampus is also important for memory consolidation. The hippocampus receives input from different parts of the cortex and sends its output out to different parts of the brain also. The input comes from secondary and tertiary sensory areas that have processed the information a lot already. Hippocampal damage may also cause memory loss and problems with memory storage. Severe damage to the hippocampi in both hemispheres results in profound difficulties in forming new memories (anterograde amnesia) and often also affects memories formed before the damage occurred (retrograde amnesia).Damage to the hippocampus does not affect some types of memory, such as the ability to learn new skills (playing a musical instrument or solving certain types of puzzles, for example). This fact suggests that such abilities depend on different types of memory (procedural memory) and different brain regions. Brain imaging shows that people have more active hippocampi when correctly navigating, as tested in a computer-simulated "virtual" navigation task or spatial skills. There is inherent connection between frontal lobe and hippocampus for proper coordination of short term memory.', '20 Aug ''13, 05:18', 1),
('100105543', '100104709', 'users/100042256/tobias-kuster', 'I don''t think it is about "a lesser number of people hearing the cry", but about addressing people individually -- and those people knowing who was addressed.\nThere seem to be two main "motivations" why people come to help (despite the bystander-effect, so to say):\n\nIf they see that if they do not help, then really no one else will, thus if the victim dies (or similar), they would have to live with their bad conscience.\nIf they have been addressed directly ("You, with that yellow shirt, help me!") and other people have noticed, so others will blame them (and not themselves) if they do not help and the victim is killed.\n\nIn your example, she might have called her neighbour, maybe even by name, but he probably still was in the comfortable position of no one else (maybe not even the victim) knowing whether he heard the call -- not  knowing whether he was actually at home, or sleeping, or listening to loud music, or having some other excuse not to help. He (and all the others) probably thought: "Meh, she might have called me directly, but others have heard the cry, too, and no one knows I''m home, so I won''t risk my life."', '20 Aug ''13, 06:46', 1),
