('100108355', '100106891', 'users/112861100/tanushree', 'For a little clarity on the topic of subjective v/s objective I would like to use the following  quote:\n"People convince themselves of their own lies, becoming victims of their own inventions as they begin to direct their lives by standards of behavior, ideas, feelings, or instincts which do not correspond to their inner reality. What is truly serious in this matter is that the individual loses all points of reference regarding what comprises truth, and what comprises lies. He becomes used to considering as true only that which is convenient for his personal interests; everything that is in opposition to his self-esteem or in conflict with already established prejudices, he considers false." \n- John Baines \nSubjective point of view can be defined as Proceeding from or taking place in a person''s mind rather than the external world.\nHaving actual existence or reality is what you can enunciate as  the Objective point of view.\nIf you can prove something by measuring something then it is by default objective else it is subjective.But you never know whether your subjective opinions/experiences are bang on but you prefer your point of view because everyone prefers their own version of reality.Opinions are colored by one''s feelings,emotions and past experiences.This is subjective.Objective is some concrete fact with proofs.\nI guess you are pretty clear on this topic yourself.These were just my inputs to make concepts more clearer.Have a great day!', '29 Aug ''13, 02:10', 5),
('100108357', '100102205', 'users/100020046/code_jamer', 'This is a really good question,  what I gather from the previous lectures is that, people low on Serotonin levels have a greater tendency to experience depression.\nSSRIs increase the levels of serotonin in the brain, hence counteract depression.\nPeople suffering form Panic disorders are overly anxious and are prone to worrying, both can be associated with depression.\nA depressed person would probably be anxious and worried.\nSo, since SSRIs counteract the effect of depression, they should too for Panic disorders as well.\nOf-course I infer all this from the lectures, I do not speak on account of explicit medical evidence that I may have come across.', '29 Aug ''13, 02:24', 2),
('100108412', '100073918', 'users/141162538/alex-856', 'You can never tell unless you measure the whole world''s population. You''re just getting as big a sample as you can (with the financial and volunteer numbers as limiting factors) . The bigger the better. That''s why scientists shouldn''t say "this IS causal, rather they should say "this suggests a causal link".', '29 Aug ''13, 07:01', 0),
('100108421', '100108059', 'users/100058997/sundararaman-r', 'I''m sure there''s a systematic answer to that question, but as an amateur in this field two things come to mind: \n\n\nSample size and selection. If we surveyed four people, and it so happened that the number of sandwiches they have per week is also the number of rock album CDs they possess in each case, there''d be a perfect correlation, but it''d be wrong to conclude a causation from this. Similar issues can arise due to who and where you survey (selection) also. \n\n\nIMO this is the more subtle and easier-to-miss case: the common cause effect. If we surveyed a bunch of teenage girls and found that their frequency of wearing black lipstick is perfectly correlated with their interest in black metal music, we cannot conclude one of these caused the other - both maybe caused by a third factor together (in this case, that''s possibly their adherence to the goth lifestyle). There''s still cause and effect here, but both the factors we measured are the effects here and the cause is a third factor which would need further study.', '29 Aug ''13, 07:34', 3),
