('100108978', '100074851', 'users/100116941/jochen-fromm', 'The whole sensory cortex takes part in perceiving and storing information. The senses of vision, audition, and touch are served by the visual cortex, auditory cortex and somatosensory cortex, respectively. While the sensory cortex is responsible for perception, the motor cortex is responsible for action, and both are connected in various and multiple ways. Basically the flow is as follows\n\nInput (from senses) &gt; Sensory Cortex &gt; Mortor Cortex &gt; Actions (from muscles)\n\nIn reality it is more complicated, there are lower, primary areas and higher association areas, there are gateways, and there is the brainstem. The Thalamus serves as gateway for all sensory informations, while the Basal Ganglia serve a similar function for motor control.', '30 Aug ''13, 17:37', 0),
('100109007', '100067942', 'users/141057170/desiree-6', 'I am wondering why your question focused on monkeys and not simply animals? In fact, when a research scientist chooses to work with animals they have to demonstrate the need to use animals, and the need to use the species suggested in their protocol. They must always try to conduct their research using the lowest species on the phylogenetic scale, in other words, this study would be conducted in mice or rats. There would be no need to use monkeys. This is one of the ways the IACUC uses ethics to determine the acceptability of animal research work.', '30 Aug ''13, 19:49', 1),
