('100109220', '100102722', 'users/141719025/darkicedragon', 'In the case of memory, I think Cognitive Neuroscience would focus more on how the memory is stored (I haven''t read any neuroscience books, but I think it would involve biochemical reactions, synapses, neurons, which parts of the brain are activated, etc. etc.); while Cognitive Psychology would focus more on why the memory is stored (like in the video, it says we might remember a random childhood event, but we might forget the name of a person we met recently. Why did our brain store something useless ,in this case, the childhood memory, for so long even though it wasn''t needed, while we forgot something we actually needed to remember, in this case, the person''s name)?\nFor learning, it could possible have the same meaning. Cognitive Neuroscience might elaborate on how we learn, and Cognitive Psychology might discuss why some methods of learning work for some, but not for others (like some people learn better when they take notes or read aloud from textbooks, or listen to an audio recording of a lecture, while some learn best when they draw representative diagrams, charts and watch the lesson as a video)\nSo I think while Cognitive Neuroscience teaches us the how, Cognitive Psychology teaches us the why.\nBut while there isn''t an extremely large distinction between the two, differences can be made out in most cases I think.', '31 Aug ''13, 12:05', 3),
