('100109769', '100065293', 'users/100045870/afgak', 'Here''s an example:\nFrom a pool of applicants, two groups are picked at random. This is done with a random number generator, so who ends up in which group is completely random. Let''s call the groups Blue and Green. \nThere are two pills, the drug to be tested, and a placebo. The pills look the same. Let''s call them P and S. \nAs the researcher, I know who is in group Blue, and who is in group Green. I know what is in pill P, and what is in pill S. To make it a double blind study however, I need to give each group one pill, without knowing which is which... that''s the challenge. \nIt''s also very easily solved with an assistant, and two empty pill bottles. The empty bottles have numbers on them, say 1 and 2. \n"Here, go into this other room, flip a coin, and then put all the P-pills into bottle 1 if it''s heads, or 2 if it''s tails. Then put the S pills in the other bottle. Make a note of which bottle you put which pills in, and seal that note in an envelope."\nThen you give one group pills from bottle 1, and one group pills from bottle 2, and the only people who knows what pills are which is the assistant and the note in your safe. If you want to make sure the assistant doesn''t know which is which either, just do the same thing yourself when the assistant is out of the room - put the 1-pills into empty bottle X, and the 2-pills into empty bottle Y, or vice versa, make a note of the change in a sealed envelope, and put it in the safe with the other note. \nNow nobody has a clue what pills are what, but it''s easy to find out by just opening the envelopes at the end of the experiment.', '02 Sep ''13, 11:48', 0),
('100109781', '100105500', 'users/141719025/darkicedragon', 'According to the video, I think it means that the correlation is not a perfect one, but there is a moderate relation between the two variables. For the exact definition, I think a bit of statistics would be involved. Searching around on the web could help.', '02 Sep ''13, 12:46', 2),
('100109800', '100093635', 'users/141719025/darkicedragon', 'I had this same question, incidentally. I thought that the arrival time of a person should be a random enough variable to separate the groups upon. Let''s say if the study was conducted in the morning, supposedly the persons arriving earlier are more likely those who are habituated to waking up early, hence have increased reaction times, than persons arriving later. But what about traffic jams, commuting distance, weather, and other variables like this? They could influence the arrival time of a person, yet they might not specifically influence the reaction time of a person. At any workplace, people usually arrive on time, regardless of their grogginess or such, because they have to. Wouldn''t that be random enough to base the selection of groups upon?\nMy question is, even if I did use the flip-a-coin method, the study would still be in the morning, and some people would still have the delayed reaction times (if they didn''t get enough sleep, or other factors), regardless of whether they arrived first or not.\nThe only explanation to my question that I can think of is that the flip-a-coin method mixes up the groggy, sleep-deprived, or non-''morning'' persons and the active, ''early-bird'', well rested persons just a teeny bit more than the arrival time method. Is this correct?', '02 Sep ''13, 13:59', 0),
('100109811', '100101946', 'users/141719025/darkicedragon', 'Hmm.. as far as my understanding of this experiment went, we were trying to find out if caffeine affected the response times of people. More specifically, if it decreased their reaction times or not. A caffeine/no caffeine group would have been just as effective as a caffeine/placebo caffeine group, but I think the placebo method gains favour, because if we see that the placebo group''s reaction times did not change, while the caffeine group''s went down, we can safely conclude that caffeine reduces our reaction times. If we see that both group''s reaction times went down, then we can conclude that caffeine has no effect whatsoever on our reaction times. If we see that both the groups saw a decrease in reaction times, then we can safely say that caffeine does not cause our reaction times to go down, it might be the thought of drinking coffee that causes it, or maybe some other ingredient in the coffee.\nIn a caffeine/no caffeine group, we cannot accurately and specifically find out if it is simply the thought of drinking coffee, drinking caffeine or another ingredient in the coffee that affects us, we can only see whether the caffeine group''s reaction times went down with respect to the no caffeine group''s or not.', '02 Sep ''13, 14:12', 1),
('100109813', '100105500', 'users/142767656/hampton', 'The number correlation depends on the degree of the correlation, on the scale. For example, if the scale was from -10 to 10, you might say that a 4 is a moderate positive correlation and that -9 is a strong negative correlation. In this case, the scale is from -1 to 1, so a 0.4 correlation, no matter if it is -0.4 or 0.4, is moderate since it is about half way between 0 and 1, or 0 and -1, if the 0.4 is negative.', '02 Sep ''13, 14:14', 4),
('100109825', '100107089', 'users/141719025/darkicedragon', 'If the researcher rates the reaction of times of people, he/she may not be accurate at all times, and it introduces the chance of human error into the picture. Also, this type of rating is subjective, and its value may differ from person to person, thus making the study an unreliable one. For example, a reaction time you rate on a scale of 1-10 at 5, I could rate at 6 or 7, thus we would end up having different conclusions for the same batch of people.\nBy using a computer-based time-test, we are removing the chance of bias on part of the researcher, or the subjective opinion of the researcher. It will also give us a more accurate time reading, as rating on a scale of 1-10, or asking the subject to rate their reaction times or using a stopwatch also has chances of human error. As we all know, a computer has no ''opinions'', it can only be objective, which is what we want.\nBut, to make this study a bit more thorough, we could add a questionnaire that the participants could fill up, rating their reaction times. Thus we would get the objective results, that is, the statistically accurate readings from the computer time-test, and the subjective results, that is, the opinions of the participants from the questionnaire, making our study thorough, reliable, and informative.', '02 Sep ''13, 14:31', 5),
