('100110731', '100102517', 'users/142767656/hampton', 'I agree that the wording off this question is a bit odd, but if the two groups were identical at the beginning of the experiment (if the sample size is large enough and assigned randomly, the groups can be can be called practically random), and the only thing different between the experimental group and the control group was the independent variable, it must be true that the independent variable caused this difference.\nHonestly, I think that your wording it better than the original question, though the original wording is still correct. It requires you to assume two things: 1. That the experimental group and the control group only differed by one variable (granted, that is pretty much impossible, but if the sample size is large enough, etc. it is practically true), which itself is the whole point of experimental and control groups; and 2. That there weren''t any confounding variables, and even if there were any confounding variables, we can safely assume that it affected both groups (since both groups were same at the beginning) and therefore cancels out. \nI thought about this one for a while, but if I made any mistakes, please tell me!', '05 Sep ''13, 12:05', 1),
