('100110808', '100110753', 'users/118578353/susan-snycerski', 'Hello,\nThe researchers do not know at the time of the study start or throughout the study who is in the experimental group and who is in the control group; however, there is a code in place that will be opened once the study has been completed. At that time, once it is revealed which participants were the experimental group and which were the control group, the researcher will analyze the data to see if there is a significant difference between the groups. This process helps limit expectancy effects. Does this explanation help?\nBest,\nDr. Snycerski', '05 Sep ''13, 17:52', 4),
