('100110978', '100097154', 'users/118076567/diego-114', 'I used to volunteer for a non-profit organization, and we had a stand at a very busy street market.  There would be usually only three of us there. Sometimes we would wait for more than 30 minutes and nobody would stop at our stand. But when the first person stopped to talk to us, then a second person would stop, and a third one and sometimes a fourth one in a matter of two or three minutes.  And the same thing happened the whole day, every day. It was, of course, not a coincidence.\nNight club owners take advantage of this effect. The other day I went to a place with some friends and to my disappointment there was a huge line of about 30 people on the side walk. As I went to lock my bike in the parking lot, behind the building, I could notice from a window that the place was not full at all, and there were lots of empty tables. I went to the doorman and asked him how long did he think I would take to get inside, and he said 45minutes. I went back to my friends and told them the situation, and they were all angry that we were being kept out in the cold even though there was plenty of space inside just because the night club owner decided to use us to attract more clients. \nWould it be ethical if I used confederates to stand in front of my stand at the street market just to get more public?', '06 Sep ''13, 10:38', 3),
