('100113145', '100111700', 'users/147151445/vahavy', 'It is my understanding that we are operating on three levels when it comes to our brains: Reptilian, Mammalian, and Human.\nOur instinctual reptilian brain initiates the fight or flight response, our mammalian brain assesses how we feel about it and also evokes a physiological response based on the emotion evoked, and our human brain  which is largely considered to be the most recent structure, the prefrontal cortext, that puts it all together and allows us to think and decide about how we are going to react and attempt to foresee the consequences of the said action (if one has fairly well developed self awareness) beyond survival or cessation of life. (Apologies for the run-on sentence.)\nOf course, I am not a biologist in any sense, least of all evolutionary or psychological, and I could be completely wrong. This is all off the top of my head.', '14 Sep ''13, 01:21', 1),
('100113148', '100101946', 'users/147151445/vahavy', 'I would think that the statistical significance between the average reaction times of those who did get caffeine and those who didn''t would be the deciding factor. If those who got caffeine scored significantly higher than those who thought they were receiving caffeine, the fact that some of the data may have been influenced by the placebo effect makes the significance even more significant, if you will.\nMeaning that, actually ingesting caffeine will affect you greater than just thinking you are getting caffeine. Or put another way, in a drug study, if the takers of the drug had significantly better results than the others who only thought they were being administered the drug, then the drug could be considered a success as it outdoes even the placebo effect.\nI''m not certain if the wording and structure conveys exactly what I was going for but I hope it''s comprehensible, aha.', '14 Sep ''13, 01:33', 0),
('100113149', '100104724', 'users/147151445/vahavy', 'As far as the physiological and neurological effects of meditation or spiritual experience, you can find a lot of information on YouTube. Here is a video I enjoyed very much: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sNc52LmHgUs\nIt likely wont cover everything, but it''s a good place to start, and there are many more videos out there.', '14 Sep ''13, 01:37', 0),
