('100114554', '100113704', 'users/149063993/karen-115', 'Rods are nerve cells that help us see in the dark because they process black and white and shades of gray. As the light increases, so do the function of the cone cells, sending color signals to the brain (a combination of red, green and blue). The rods don''t "shut down" in the light. They are still at work completing the color information for the brain by processing shades and shadows.\nKaren Levine\nhttp://allaboutcolorblindness.com/', '19 Sep ''13, 07:21', 0),
