('100116026', '100101840', 'users/100044700/jim-roames', 'Bystander effect - "a social psychological phenomenon that refers to cases in which individuals do not offer any means of help to a victim when other people are present. The probability of help is inversely related to the number of bystanders."\nThe question isn''t whether or not there was a tragedy that occurred. The question is whether or not the apartment residents did nothing and whether or not a large number of bystanders were present. If you read the Superfreakonomics bit (or better yet, the article in the September 2007 American Psychologist by Manning et al) you''d know that the apartment residents did in fact intervene: they called the police, they chased away Moseley and they saw that Kitty had gotten away. You could argue that the residents should have gotten together and formed a search party to seek out Kitty and make sure she received adequate help. Then again, we do pay our police to respond to emergencies when we call them.\nThe only evidence that the Genovese murder is an example of the bystander effect comes from Gansberg''s NY Times article. You said that I''ve given too much weight to one source, but (let me repeat) the ONLY evidence that the Genovese murder is an example of the bystander effect comes from Gansberg''s NY Times article. In all versions it is a horrible tragedy, but the bystander effect is something very specific. There are a lot of subsequent writings that use that article as their source. But those aren''t new sources providing new data or evidence. It''s just people repeating what they''ve read elsewhere. (Superfreakonomics and Manning et al 2007 both provide new data and don''t just take Gansberg''s article at face value) The reasons why I am not willing to trust that source is that it is factually inaccurate (e.g. claiming that there were three separate attacks, when there were only two) and that the source used was a police inspector trying to cover up the fact that his police force had been extremely slow to respond to an emergency.\nThe Kitty Genovese tragedy is still a horrible tragedy. What Julien and I were saying is that it is not a good example of the bystander effect because the apartment residents did in fact intervene.\nSo, my question to you would be: what evidence do you have that the Genovese case is actually an example of the bystander effect (and not just a horrible tragedy) other than what a police commissioner told a NY Times reporter in order to hide the fact that the police were slow to respond to the call(s) they received after the first attack?', '25 Sep ''13, 14:55', 1),
('100116044', '100106722', 'users/100104209/marcus', 'Sorry about your dad, but on the other hand physicians are quite quick in prescribing insulin and you might need it for the rest of your life.\nA general statement on this charpter: it''s rather on the homeostatic regulation of cellular metabolism than on the specific physiology of hunger you talked about. But it''s true, Decreasing glucose availability can cause hunger.\nHunger is quite autonomously regulated by the hypothalamus. Which uses afferent impulses from the limbic system, and of course also gets such afferent excitement directly. But there are also chemoreceptors in the liver and in the intestines so the storage, uptake and consumption information can be integrated in superior instances of the brain. And the drive(hunger) is therefore also dependent on this instance.\nWhether you''re fasting, were physically active over a long time or taken too much insulin: The lowered availability of glucose can create hunger and activates the the sympathetic nervous system.\nAdding insuline I can imagine that an otherwise wise system can create the wrong needs and contractions of the stomach.', '25 Sep ''13, 15:52', 0),
('100116071', '100114052', 'users/100104209/marcus', 'There are ways to make the visualization show that it''s on a scale first and it''s about groups in a region later on. \nYou always compare the IQ correlation within groups of a certain relatedness. for example parents and their children (0.5) in the same environment and then you look at the figure where they have different environments.\nThe last two bars show the correlation between the adopted children in the same environment and (the last bar) the correlation between foster parent and adopted child in the same environment.\nOf course you could add two green bars there in order to have a baseline and know what''s noise.\nAnd still there is the question what it is you compare genetically. Unless there''s no definition for genetic relatedness the validity stands in question and thought aestheticism can''t follow nor does it answer the question but it could help fix the graph in 1.', '25 Sep ''13, 17:57', 2),
