('100121010', '100117934', 'users/154020240/sandra-89', 'I am not sure about how development is different.  I had watched a lecture on youtube about aspergers a while back. According to the lecture, the primary difference in asperger''s syndrome and someone else is a social one.   Someone with aspergers will not be as interested in other people as another person, but will become more interested in things.  There was a study done where they watched where the eyes focus on a movie or picture of someone with Aspergers and someone who does not have it.  The people who did not have it were looking back and forth between the people.  But the group with the disorder would look at the things in the room and not the people.  Also often people with Aspergers will get a hobby or something like it that will be very important to them.', '15 Oct ''13, 12:09', 0),
('100121015', '100114994', 'users/154020240/sandra-89', 'My parents got married around the age 30.  I got married at 24.  My parents spent a lot of time in college and I have not.  I think that before the college movement people were getting their lives started much sooner.  After that people are encouraged to get degrees because otherwise there is a feeling someone won''t get a job that is acceptable in life.  Many higher paying jobs (and more perhaps more satisfying jobs) will go to people with the right degree.  Without that job then how will a person buy food and pay for their shelter?  So having later families is a trade off for a better financial situation, and it is an issue of survival to me.  I don''t think people would start families as late as their 30''s otherwise.', '15 Oct ''13, 12:40', 0),
