('100123131', '100117281', 'users/100104209/marcus', 'He''s the the founder of psychoanalysis as a broad theory, psychoanalysis as a personality theory and also psychoanalysis as a method. Amidst a time of natural science and seeing patients as machines he explored and applied his "talking treatment"(1893) in order to change the whole person to the cure. \nPsychology is studying the behavior and mental processes of individuals scientifically. Of course today there are other standards to what science is but in his time he was scientific in discovering the irrational. He had interesting hypotheses which are already incorporated in the way we see things, he was very experimental in his sessions though we imagine wrongly, of course observant and his thinking still remains clear in his works. As fashionable as Freud bashing has become (that it has even seeped into therapy training programs), Freud too was not always wrong. Some hypotheses have even proven to be right: Freud not only invented but also posited the fundamentals of psychotherapy: the value of insight and deep self-exploration and expression; the existence of resistance, transference, repressed trauma; the use of dreams and fantasies, role playing, free association; the need to address characterological problems as well as symptoms; and the absolute necessity of a trusting therapeutic relationship.\nHe can be seen as a neuroscientist who worked as an explorer and clinical psychologist even though the institutionalization of what he did still needed to be done. The practical psychologists came before the approved. In the USA you could get a certificate(formal education) for psychology from 1927 till 1932 and after that it was not until the 1950ies where it has become possible to get a formal education in this field. Quite to the contrary the term psychology was used about 1520 for the very first time and the beginnings of science and psychology and their application go way back, to the ancient greek world. And even seen over this time span Freud''s revolutionaly insights and contributions to culture, psychoanalysis and psychotherapy remain unparalleled. He prefigured many of the major developments that were to occur over the next one hundred years.', '24 Oct ''13, 14:54', 3),
