('100124993', '100122246', 'users/163057010/felix-102', 'The difference between a correlational study and an experimental study is that in an experimental study the independend variable is controlled by the experimenter. So it can only be an experimental study if the experimentor sets the value the independend variable will have in advance. If before the experiment the experimenter decides that one group will get this amount of caffein while the other group will get that amount of coffein it is an experimental study. If however the amount is only recorded during or after the experiment it is a corrolational study. If we let people take their coffe however much they like and only record how much they took, it is a corrolational study.\nIn the given question it is clear that the amount of sugar was not set by the experimenter but was merely recorded. The children still took as much sugar as they normally took. So it obviously is a corrolational study. And since obesity increased with an increase in sugar intake it is a corrolational study that showed a postivie correlation between sugar intake and obesity as measured by weight.\nAll other answers are just wrong, And since the question system did not accept the correct answer it has a bug. So just skip this question by clicking on the next question in the top line.', '02 Nov ''13, 08:08', 0),
