('100126932', '100123722', 'users/100104209/marcus', 'Hi there William,\nto answer your question I''d suggest to have a look at the pekrun 2006 control and value model.\nUnlike the American ethos that says: Success comes from being successful there are more things you need to consider when you ask yourself how you appraise(think about) the amount of control you have over a situation and how your values were built up.\nOf course you''re right when you say: I passed a test, I''ve got control over the situation and I appreciate being good. But the emotions you attributed in the process of appraisal is dependent on your genes and your temperament(personality). How you appraise the situation also depends on the social environment. If your social environment doesn''t induce certain values, doesn''t let you be autonomous or gives you poor instruction quality or no feedback you are quite unlikely to have or develop certain values or the thought that you might be able to control the situation of have control in general. This means the social environment directly influences(i.e. over feedback and consequences) your general believes and aims which are the background of your situational appraisal but also influence your temperament and your epigenetics(!!) which in turn influence your achievementmotivation. Which influence your emotions and therefore the appraisal of control and value in the situation.\nWith this model I can be more specific in answering your question: achievement motivation, which stands on a changeable base influences the appraisal of the situation but your general believes and aims  and your social environment also determine how you appraise the situation. This appraisal (together with your genetics and temperament) determine your motivation and emotions.\nwhen you''re talking about "motivation from challenge" you might be referring to a generalized believe which is controlled by the feedbacks and consequences of your social environment.', '10 Nov ''13, 09:26', 1),
