('100131645', '100105108', 'users/100029839/viliam-bur', 'May be something they learned in the past. For example if someone had abusive parents who didn''t respect them and made fun of them everytime they said something positive about themselves or expressed a dream... such people would learn not having self-respect and not trying new things as a survival skill. Such habits are very difficult to get rid of, even if later the situation changes completely.\nAnother possible cause is having a different model of the world than you have. For example, why do you think that having self-respect or wanting to do new things is a desirable thing? Because you believe something (e.g. that people who respect themselves have better lives on average, and that people who learn new things improve their lives). Why do you believe that? Either because this is your experience, or because someone you trusted told you so. Now imagine you lived under different conditions where you got an opposite experience (e.g. you survived a war and you saw people expressing self-respect getting tortured and killed while more humble people were abused but survived, or you had friends that loved learning new things and then something bad happened to them, like they learned to make an explosive which killed them, while your other good friends learned nothing and just enjoyed their lives) and/or the people you trusted told you opposite things (e.g. that people with self-respect are too proud and will go to hell, or that learning new things is a sin). Some people live very different lives.', '28 Nov ''13, 10:56', 1),
