('100132042', '100104615', 'users/100029839/viliam-bur', 'Human eyes process colors as if in two steps. In the first step, the wavelenght of the light is translated to signals of (three types of) cones. In the second step, the signals from the different types of cones are combined to produce a perception of the color.\nThe perception of color is not directly a signal from one type of a cone, but rather a combination of signals. For example, think about the red color. In your picture, there is no type of cone that would have a maximum at red. The RED line actually has its maximum at yellow, and then towards the red it decreases; it just decreases slower than the other lines. So the perception of a yellow color is something like "high RED signal, medium GREEN signal, no BLUE signal", while the perception of a red color is something like "medium RED signal, no GREEN signal, no BLUE signal". It''s not just the presence of RED signal,but also the absence of GREEN signal that together create the perception of a red color.\nNow look at the picture carefully and tell me where else is the RED signal higher than the GREEN signal. Yeah, it happens a bit near the violet end of the scale. At which point our eye perceives a blue color as "high BLUE signal, medium GREEN signal, a bit lower RED signal", and a violet color as "high BLUE signal, medium GREEN signal, a bit higher RED signal".\nSpeaking about wavelenghts, violet is at the opposite end of our scale. But speaking about signals from the cones, there is a similarity between how they react on a red color and a violet color: in both cases, the RED signal is stronger than the GREEN signal. So despite the wavelenghts are different, they happen to translate to signals with some similar traits. Which creates an illusion of similarity. But it''s an illusion; an artifact of how human eyes work.\nThe violet light is not a mix of red and blue lights. But the cone signals triggered by the violet light are a mix of signals triggered by red and blue lights. By mixing a pure red light and a pure blue light, you can create a mixed light that a human eye would perceive as a violet color. But it wouldn''t be the same thing as a pure violet light. (You could tell the difference using a prism: the mixed blue+red light would again split to its component, while the pure violet light wouldn''t split.) A different species and some partially colorblind people would see them as different colors.\nSummary: A wavelength is not the same thing as a color. Wavelength is a physical property of a photon. Color is a simplification of a combination of wavelengths, a feeling computed by human cones. Different combinations of wavelengths can result in a perceptions of the same color. For example, a mix of blue and red wavelengths can create the same color as a violet wavelength, despite being a different physical thing. This is actually how television and computer screens create an illusion of all colors using only three wavelengths. The three colors in RGB correspond to the the three types on cones in the average human eye; this is not an inherent physical property of light. A different species would have different perceptions of color.\nIf you think about the signals, it also helps to explain how colorblind people see. For example imagine that someone does not have the GREEN signal. (For genetic reasons, they simply don''t have this type of a cone, or it''s damaged and unable to process signals correctly.) For them, both green color and red color are perceived like "no BLUE signal, medium RED signal", so in the result they both look the same. This is the most frequent type of partial color blindness. (Theoretically speaking, from a different species'' point of view, our inability to see the difference between violet and blue+red would also be considered a partial color blindness shared by all humans.)', '01 Dec ''13, 05:32', 2),
