('100133852', '100066998', 'users/177295975/gemma-11', 'This is a very good point but I don''t agree with Marina''s view. If we only test on people who never have caffeine, the result we get might not apply to people who are used to it. If we do as she says, the conclusion of our experiment would be ''Caffeine affects/does not affect reaction time on individuals not used to caffeine''. \nIf we randomly mix caffeine users and non-caffeine users the results would be more universal so we could say ''Caffeine affects/does not affect reaction time''. \nAnother option would be to create four groups and compare:\n1) Group 1: Caffeine users: reaction time after caffeine\n2) Group 2: Caffeine users: reaction time after placebo\n3) Group 3: Non-caffeine users: reaction time after caffeine\n4) Group 4: Non-caffeine users: reaction time after placebo\nThis four-side comparison would also find out whether reaction time after caffeine is different in those people who are used to it or not.', '08 Dec ''13, 16:22', 1),
('100133870', '100067942', 'users/177295975/gemma-11', 'A key question here is, would that experiment be useful to avoid major suffering to humans or would it just be used to satisfy scientific curiosity? In my opinion, it would be totally unacceptable to carry out such an experiment just to satisfy curiosity. \nBut let''s imagine that a controlled experiment with animals helps us to find way avoid or cure cocaine addiction. The suffering caused to animals would be largely compensated by the reduction of suffering for hundreds of thousands of people. We should choose the least evolved animal as possible, and reduce any suffering as much as possible during the experiment. Under such conditions, the experiment might be acceptable.', '08 Dec ''13, 17:26', 0),
