('100147357', '100147091', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'This is Matt here. Just a quick clarification: all humans and chimps are apes (or primates).\nNo, chimps will not evolve into humans; nor did chimps evolve into humans. Chimps and humans are like cousins - closely related but not in an intergenerational sense. Chimps and humans share a common ancestor that lived approximately 8 million years ago. That ancestor is extinct now, but there are many intermediates, most notably Australopithecus.\nDoes that help answer your question?', '24 Jan ''14, 21:00', 3),
('100147360', '100096534', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'This is Matt, the instructor.\nAll of psychology has to do with what comes from the brain. But the brain is an evolved structure, changing over millions of years of evolution. To understand the biology of the brain we need to understand the context of where it came from. The easiest way to learn about the context is to compare the human brain to that of our closest living relative, the chimpanzee. By comparing and contrasting the human and chimp brain we can see what changes have evolved over the past 8 millions years or so that might contribute to making us uniquely human. \nDoes that help answer your question?', '24 Jan ''14, 21:05', 3),
('100147361', '100099604', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'We learn about natural selection in the genetics course Tales from the Genome. You should check it out and see for yourself:\nhttps://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-bio110/l-301472399/e-299884998/m-299884999', '24 Jan ''14, 21:07', 1),
('100147363', '100111872', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Pitossomo has it right here. It''s not just about the quantity but the quality. The increase in brain size came at the cost of needing to eat a lot more protein.', '24 Jan ''14, 21:11', 1),
('100147366', '100100811', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Yes, it is true that Prader Willi syndrome is caused by a deletion of genetic information, this specific syndrome is only caused if you receive that deletion from your father. If you inherit this deletion from your mother a different syndrome is caused called Angelman Syndrome. The cause for this is a bit complicate for this course, but is the result of something called genetic imprinting.', '24 Jan ''14, 21:15', 0),
('100147367', '100100812', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Having color in the eyes is due to pigmentation. Pigment is deposited over time, and newborn babies may not have all of the pigment deposited that they will receive over their lifetimes, so eye color will usually get darker as they child grows. However, pigment almost never decreases (so you won''t find a brown-eyed baby growing up to be a blue-eyed adult).', '24 Jan ''14, 21:25', 1),
('100147368', '100112767', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'I give a more detailed explanation of eye color in lesson 9 of my course, Tales from the Genome.  You should really check it out:\nhttps://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-bio110/l-301726615/e-301927562/m-301927563', '24 Jan ''14, 21:28', 2),
