('100148506', '100098529', 'users/100024337/stanislav-zholnin', 'I see this again and again in discussion of homosexuality. Most people I talked to actually share this thought and I think that THIS thought is the real problem, not discussion of whether homosexuality is normal. Let me quote:\n\nAnd they seem to serve a function, which functions we don''t know yet.\nSo why should we consider them "bad" when a human uses them to bond\nwith other organisms of his species?\n\nHope you see what is wrong with that. Why, why, so many people whenever they are told about "disorder" or "deviation" immediately conclude that this is something bad?\nOften when I argue for the fact that homosexuality is a disorder I immediately get blamed for "thinking that I am better than homosexual", "being homophobic", "being fascist", "saying that homosexual people are bad". My next question to such people is whether they consider person with diabetes as being somehow inferior or bad? They generally say no. So why they assume that thinking that homosexuality is a disorder make homosexual people inferior?\nSo I think from the beginning we should have been fighting the whole idea of discrimination towards people with disorders. As long as disorder does not make person dangerous to other people. Instead of this we chose different way - fighting to prove that specific disorders are not disorders. Now we are getting to the point of recognizing that sexual attraction to children is not a disorder, sexual attraction to animals is not a disorder - do people start to realize that maybe we just chose a wrong road?\nI do support fighting against discrimination of gay people, but I think that it is a mental disorder and my opinion is unlikely to change (I don''t want to put my arguments here, because this is not the main point I want to highlight). But my opinion doesn''t make me think that gay people are "bad" or "inferior".', '28 Jan ''14, 13:38', 1),
