('100154319', '100143876', 'users/204666671/annie-50', 'I''ve been listening to a CD which advises on how to be happy, which is in effect stop being sad!\nThe best way is to exercise. If you don''t want to do hard physical exercise, taking a walk outdoors for an hour or so, breathing in fresh air, feeling the wind and sun on your skin and looking at objects far away is an excellent way to calm our nervous system and studies have shown it helps patients with depression.\nOther ways are listening to music, singing, dancing, forcing yourself to laugh and smile and also creating something with your hands- be it cooking, painting, arts and craft or playing a musical instrument. Writing down and focusing on what you appreciate and feel grateful for will help take your mind off sadness too.\nAnother interesting way it mentioned to get rid of negative energy is using the ''tapping technique'' that Roger Callaham developed. Just google ''tapping'' for lots of hits online.\nHope this helps!!! :)', '13 Feb ''14, 04:03', 0),
('100154396', '100138997', 'users/153303224/thekla', 'Welcome to Intro to Psychology. \nI''m Lauren.\nI''m Susan.\nAnd I''m Greg.\nWe''re your instructors for this course. \nWe''re going to take you on your journey through psychology.\nWe''ll go over different areas of psychology and how different psychologists examine and explain thought and behavior.\nWe are all very different.\nWe like different things.\nWe think differently.\nWe even react differently.\nSo for instance, I have something here that might create different reactions in people.\nOoh. Look at this guy.\nMy snake Thickles.\nI''ve come to really enjoy him.\nHe''s a nice snake.\nI wouldn''t mind holding Tickles or touching him but I certainly wouldn''t want him as a pet.\nLauren?\nNo, no, I don''t do snakes.\nYou don''t do snakes.\nNo. I don''t do snakes.\nThe perfect example of how people react differently to different situations.\nSo, there''s many different areas of psychology, for instance, personality psychologists would look at what''s going on here and try to really understand the individual differences in the fear and why I''m not really afraid, you''re fine and she''s more or less terrified.\nBehavioral Psychologists might look at an individual''s learning history.\nSo, for example I was exposed to a lot of snakes when I was growing up.\nSo, perhaps I''ve learned that snakes aren''t dangerous for me.\nAnd a Social Psychologist may look at how other people''s behavior influences our own.\nSo, for example, looking at other people''s reactions may influence our own reactions.\nA biological psychologist, perhaps, may look at Lauren''s fright response in terms of increase in heart rate, or even sweating.\nAn a neuroscientist. They may look at the areas of the brain that are activated during the fear response, such as the amygdala.\nBut for now, I think it''s time for Tickles to head home.\nEven though this example exploited my fear of snakes.\nThanks a lot Greg.\nIt was a really effective tool for Susan and Greg to use to show you just how diverse psychology can be.\nNow psychology is defined as a study of thought and behavior and is an amazing way to make sense of our world.', '13 Feb ''14, 11:08', 1),
('100154498', '100149298', 'users/218183783/besseler', 'Bigger brain = we need more energy (which comes from food, so we definitely need more food) to support all the extra brain activity\nBigger brain = bigger heads = childbirth more painful = we are born earlier (so the head can pass through the vagina)\nThose are the costs of having a bigger brain, the other two options are the benefits', '13 Feb ''14, 18:32', 2),
