('100155685', '100105016', 'users/225238250/xavier-78', 'When talking about "Different groups" my assumption is that, for a given experiment, your groups are as homogeneous as possible (gender/age/social status/education...) and as big as possible in order to dilute the error that comes from that variable. You would probably group them randomly in groups big enough to avoid the group "abilities" to interfere on your study. \nYou surely don''t want to create a group full of teenagers and another group full of older people or one of males and the other of females... Unless "they" are the independent variable.', '17 Feb ''14, 16:32', 0),
('100155690', '100118876', 'users/225238250/xavier-78', 'Yes you can, but in that case you may need to study the effect of one independent variable over the other independent ones and not only over the dependent one. Actually you can have many inputs and outputs on one experiment.\nI don''t know if whis will be introduced or mentioned in this course but you may find more information regarding this searching for "multivariate experimental design" and "Design of Experiments".', '17 Feb ''14, 16:42', 2),
('100155691', '100147478', 'users/225238250/xavier-78', 'Because it is not random. You are assuming that people will show up randomly, which may not be true (actually, it will most surely not be). You may end up with a group of people that wakes up sooner... Or appeared sooner because they usually drink coffe at that time of the day (which surely will impact your experiment)... Or a big chunk of one group may be a group of colleagues of the same age/gender/status that went there to drink/eat something.\nA little more random approach may be to separate them as they come (odds and evens). But what will surely be random (as you like on an experiment) is flipping a coin, even if you may end up with two not equally sized groups. But statistically, for an unbiased coin (that''s an assumption we are making) you will end up with two "almost" equally sized groups.\nYour groups need to be as random as possible. The flipping coin is just an example.', '17 Feb ''14, 17:02', 1),
('100155701', '100137438', 'users/225238250/xavier-78', 'Generally speaking what you need to assure is that groups are as equal as possible. For big enough randomly chosen groups, effects like the metabolism rate wouldn''t affect one group more than the other as you would statistically have the same ratio of male/female in each group.\nYou may clearly see that metabolism rate might play a role in the results of the experiment, but there might also be a lot of factors that you are unaware of when designing the experiment that can affect its results. Also, maybe you assume that metabolism rate is a factor and then it''s not. And, what''s worse, by "unrandomizing" your selection of groups you may bias the experiment unknowingly (even if I agree that "forcing" equal ratio of male/female probably wouldn''t hurt) but the point here is that the better approach is the random approach.', '17 Feb ''14, 17:14', 0),
('100155706', '100093635', 'users/225238250/xavier-78', 'In that case, you would have a biased coin. Change it, and keep on going with your experiment. This is just an example to point out the importance of randomly choosing the group of people.\nObviously you could try better solutions like generating (or using) a random sequence of ones and zeros and then applying it to the incoming people.... But there''s no need to add complexity to the example. And then again, how do I know if the sequence is random enough? Or if I will end up with two groups of the same size? Again, this is just an example trying to point out the importance of randomness on choosing your groups.', '17 Feb ''14, 17:23', 0),
