('100159984', '100092318', 'users/100040856/david-xin', 'I did some digging around, and managed to stumble upon this site which has an answer to your question (The second Q&amp;A on the right of the webpage): \nhttps://www.snoozon.com/lucid-dream-science\nIt looks more credible than most of the other sources I found (namely threads with people''s personal opinions), but it''s also a site to promote lucid dreaming so there may also be some bias.\nIn any case, the answer seems to be "no", lucid dreaming does not make you more tired. The argument for this is that lucid dream happens in REM sleep, when brain activity is already similar to that of being awake, so being aware that you are dreaming shouldn''t make much of a difference.', '05 Mar ''14, 22:39', 1),
