('100160214', '100160054', 'users/137331772/steven-315', 'Normally, when the fight or flight response is functioning properly, it should only activate during periods of intense fear  i.e., times when you will need to fight or run away. During those times, your body needs to have the best vision possible.\nThat is why your pupils dilate. When they dilate, your eyes are letting in more light and your vision temporarily improves.', '06 Mar ''14, 17:34', 1),
('100160249', '100139714', 'users/100040856/david-xin', 'Pavlov is a neutral stimulus, because he doesn''t have any effect on the dog at first.\nThe meat powder is an unconditioned stimulus (unconditioned meaning the dog did not learn to salivate at meat, it is just a natural reflex). The salivation is an unconditioned response because it''s a response to an unconditioned stimulus.\nSince Pavlov always has meat powder, the dog begins to associate Pavlov with meat powder. Then, if Pavlov does not have meat powder (the unconditioned stimulus), and then the dog still salivates, then it is salivating at Pavlov, who is now a conditioned stimulus. The dog has been conditioned to salivate at Pavlov by associating him with the meat powder. The salivating in this case would be a conditioned response, because it would not have happened before the conditioning.\nI hope this makes it clearer.', '06 Mar ''14, 20:51', 0),
