('100169675', '100114994', 'users/259303966/franziska-13', 'My parents were about 25 and 28 when they got married. Right now I can not tell when I really want to get married. Sometimes I think, that 30 might be a good age but sometimes I do not see the importance of getting married at all. And this is not because I have not found the right person. It is more because I have the feeling that thinking about marriage has changed in my generation. \nFor me there are several reasons for this. It might sound banal, but I still think that the women''s movement had a great impact on how especially women are living now. In earlier times it was simply the idea of society that you as a woman got married as soon as possible, because you needed the security of a husband taking especially financially care of you to "unburden" your family (besides the fact that of course love-marriage was possible!). Most of the women did not work at that time so they did not earn money to support the family. And when it was not for money reason, in richer families status was a criteria for finding the right husband/wife. This is also, why so many movies and books tell us about cross-status-border marriages. People were forced by society to marriage for something they did not always belive in.\nBut starting with my parents generation, society accepted working women and thus they became more independently from men. Their was not necessarily a restraint to get married because of financial security. Now, one was really able to choose and wait for somebody, that is right for one self. And as society grew more and more tolerant, there came up also same-gender, cross-cultural and cross-social-status and enriched our lifes by the freedom of choice when it comes to partners. And this progress is something we all should support as it is a release for everyone who does not "meet" society''s expectations. \nThis is the great advantage that I now still have: All magazines and blogs are talking about finding Mister right, downloading the best dating app and doing speed dating in your homecity. Because we are looking for our right match in personality, character, interestets and beliefs. Not (only) for our financial match. I have to admit that money is not the only important factor but it is the factor that strokes me the most when I was thinking about his topic. Money and security. And surely the women''s movement is not the only movement that influenced marriage. There are many other movements, that concentrated on all kinds of discrimination besides sex-only. They all have an impact on how we think of marriage today. So please see the women''s movement as on sample out of many.\nThe most important factors for me to be sure of are now that my partner is the right one for me. That he supports and respects me the way I am. And also, that I can see, that he will do this in future. For me, there are no quantitative factors to evaluate this but more qualitative factors such as love, trust and happiness. And here it comes to the point: Marriage is about feelings not about status. But maybe this is not how it was intented to be earlier. So that now has changed our image of marriage, maybe we have to think about the definition of marriage and if it still represents what we think of as marriage.', '15 Apr ''14, 07:50', 0),
('100170018', '100156435', 'users/258806947/anja-16', 'Light is actually an electromagnetic wave with a specific frequency. \nIn the freqency of 400 nm to 750 nm these waves are visible as light with different colours. \nWhen the frequency increases, the waves will turn into ultraviolet light and even into x-rays or gamma rays. Low-frequency colours are infrared. And when the frequency decreases beyond the realms of light, we are able to perceive the electromagnetic waves as sound.', '16 Apr ''14, 14:40', 1),
