('100179305', '100146170', 'users/182029122/ashok-32', 'Well, I think these two theories are not antagonistic, but complimentary!\nWhile Skinner''s view is on the environmental factors,  like exposure and encouragement, Chomsky is focused on how it happens with reference to the child. Also, Chomsky says, it happens naturally! which means the environment is assumed to influence.\nLike in economic theory, "other things being equal" ( here the social, cultural environmental factors being the same ) it does happen naturally!!. So both the theories, though apparently start from diametrically opposite views, they in fact, converge.', '07 May ''14, 01:56', 0),
('100179456', '100120216', 'users/100052000/luke-summerville', 'Because it''s a redundant to say"memory" twice.\nFor example:\n"What type of memory was activated?"\n"Implicit"\nYou don''t need the second the "memory" after "implicit", because it was already said in question.\nAnother example:\n"How many pounds of chocolate do you want?"\n"2"\nI guess if you wanted no confusion you could say, "2 pounds".', '07 May ''14, 11:00', 0),
('100179461', '100173656', 'users/100032279/dell-anderson', 'I think one Anurag''s primary point is valid:   The change feels like "Bait &amp; Switch".   Many things in the U.S. are marketed this way and it is completely legal, but feels somewhat disingenuous to me.   Cell phones for "only $ per month (first year only, fine print, yada yada",  furniture loans with "no interest for 6 months" etc.  Western nations are used to this slightly misleading marketing technique, but it does not mean consumers like it.  It means that consumers are mostly suckers for psychological tricks.   I myself occasionally fall for them, but try never to invest too much time and effort into something that is ''too good to be true''. \nFrom day one, I suspected this would happen, even thought that the free material would go away (it does cost money to stream video data) but I believe we were promised it would always be free, so that is only what I have counted on.   Unlike Anurag, I did not prosyletize for Udacity (I did somewhat for Coursera, but in my opinion they had a better platform (did not rely on YouTube, allowed easier video downloads etc) and I do not regret telling people about Coursera).  However, they too have gone the way of ''Verified Certificates" costing a reasonable amount ($49 last I checked).   They do have standard certificates for free, and that is fine by me.  If they stop issuing them, I will be less motivated to use their services but no more motivated to pay for a certificate because I question their value.\nThe cost of certificates is simply a tax on dishonesty paid by the honest.  If the potential employer does not believe me when I say I have completed the course successfully, then he or she probably won''t believe me when I say I worked 55 hours that week, etc.  In other words, not sure I would want to work for anyone like that.   Sure, someone could pay someone else to take the course for them, but that would be a little stupid, and in any case, there is nothing that would 100% prevent that from happening with the current system.   The only thing it does is sort people by how much money they have.   Which is nothing new to us in the U.S.   \nI expect any day for Google to start charging for gmail and when they do that, I will quit using it (after downloading all my emails).', '07 May ''14, 11:13', 4),
