('100181163', '100179026', 'users/182029122/ashok-32', 'I do not agree.\nThe delhi rape case, the incident happened in the night, on a bus that had no other passengers other than the assailants and the victims.\nalso the windows were covered with sun-control films.\nwhere is the question of bystanders there? there were none to witness the event. only when the victim was thrown on the street side - it took some time for the late night drivers to realize the gravity.\nbut then, self preservation probably took over the curiosity to find out the victims were indeed genuinely someone desperately needing help.\nvery sad.', '12 May ''14, 00:58', 0),
('100181179', '100179026', 'users/100111180/ubaier-bhat', 'Sorry...I should have made it clear... I agree with you that there was no bystanders while the victims were on the bus. However the media reported that while the two victims were on the road many people just passed by and did not offer help. Here is an article about it. (blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2013/01/05/delhi-rape-why-did-no-one-help/) . I had put a link in the question itself. \nAccording to the article the male victim had said:\n\nWe tried to stop passersby. Several auto rickshaws, cars and bikes slowed down but no-one stopped for about 25 minutes. Then, someone on patrol stopped and called the police.\nNobody from the public helped us.\n\nRegardless whether there was a any bystander effect or not surely it was a very sad event and no one should ever go through it.', '12 May ''14, 02:13', 0),
('100181225', '100110304', 'users/275847319/doron-7', 'The Iris reduces the UV Radiation our eye suffers. That is why dark-eyed populations are more common where it''s sunnier. Although snow can be a mean reflector, I guess the Nordic sun tends to be obscured with clouds much more than it is here in Israel, for example.\nBy the way, albinos - their red-ish eye color is caused by their lack of pigments, making their retina, a very vascular little thing, transparent. That''s also why flash photography can cause a red eye effect - the strong light gets inside our pupil - a hole, basically - hits our retina, and comes all the way back to hit the CCD sensor in the camera. So the red eye is actually a bloody eye, which sounds creepy, but is pretty cool.', '12 May ''14, 05:01', 2),
('100181236', '100150294', 'users/275847319/doron-7', 'I agree, although they clearly say that "every 10 dB decrease corresponds to half the volume". \neach 10 dB increase/decrease makes the differences exponential.\nThat''s the flat explanation. It saves a lot of the technical mumbo jumbo, but either way it should be X10 each 10dB increase/decrease.\nEdit:\nOK, I found the answer. It''s explained pretty well HERE, but I''ll try to sum it up:\nIt''s a matter of definitions.\nWe have LOUDNESS, which is a subjective term, derived from subjective perception.\nWe have VOLTAGE, which can be objectively measured via the observation of the sound pressure level within a specific sound field.\nAnd we have the ACOUSTIC INTENSITY, which is defined as the sound power per unit. This includes subjective factors, such as ear sensitivity, with objective factors, such as VOLTAGE. It''s a theoretical definition which tries to measure how noisy will a noise be for an individual''s ear, from a medical point of view.\nNOW, as it seems,\nLOUDNESS doubles itself with each 10dB increase.\nVOLTAGE doubles itself with (approximately) each 6dB increase.\nACOUSTIC INTENSITY grows 10 times with each 10dB increase.\nSo I guess the folks at udacity meant to say that, if you ask a person, he''ll say that a 60dB sound sounded 2 times as strong as a 50dB sound.\nThanks for the question dude, that''s interesting. Hope I helped', '12 May ''14, 05:31', 1),
