('100184483', '100126980', 'users/100104209/marcus', 'I like your question.\nConsidering coping strategies you have to sperate instrumental from palliative and the terms alloplastic from autoplastic. This just means that whenever you look at a coping strategy you ask yourself: does it remove the causes which come in your way(=instrumental) or not(even Greg didn''t work on the feelings he had towards the waves). And you too ask yourself whether the coping is working on the environment(alloplastic) or working on yourself(on your emotions for example).\nSo in the example of Greg and Lauren: instrumental solving of the problem is only possible in the autoplastic domain. (With their resources they can''t change the reasons for the annoying tides). Which means: when Greg tries invention(as he did by thinking) his actions(thinking) could only be palliative(could only lead to frantic thinking). Similar to this he could also engage in aggression(get into a state of rage) or start to cry(supplication) anyway those three strategies are only possible in the palliative here. This might be what you call "not problem-focused".\nLauren looked for a solution in the autoplastic domain and opted for revision. But even in this category she could have picked the denial that there would be tides at all. Which also would not be very instrumental. But in fact she picked the instrumental revision called reappraisal.\nThe key thing when thinking about coping always is to know which problem you are looking at(in the example with Lauren and Greg getting rid of the annoyance by tides should have been worked out more clearly) and to know where the possible instrumental solutions are. Either in the alloplastic or in the things you can change in yourself(autoplastic). Sometimes you can change things in both fields. But there''s always a palliative way to it in each strategy.\nCoping normally tries to be instrumental in the first place. But if it isn''t(can not be) functional over time the dysfunctional state of distress could do damage. So if you don''t change strategy(to one which can become instrumental) you will then atomatically switch over to the palliative version of the strategy (e.g. if begging for support doesn''t help and you stay in the strategy of supplication you will palliatvely get into a fit of crying).\nMarcus', '21 May ''14, 08:11', 0),
