('100186152', '100110022', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'My BELIEF is that when it comes to music the environment has much more to do with musical ability than people give a credit. It might not make you a genious though. \nI take my father as an example. When I was a kid my father bought a small keyboard that came with music for many popular and traditional songs. As well as the normal sheet music, the pitch of each note was expressed by numbers so even untrained people like my family could play. One particular song had a mistake that was a whole full note out but my dad could not hear it even though we pointed it out to him. Whenever he sang it was equally out of tune. But when I was a teenager he joined a local amateur choir. At first he was told to sing very quietly because of being so badly out of tune and we all thought he was hopeless. I moved out but a few years later he surprised me by singing in tune as well as any "normal" person. Not only that but it even sounded pleasant! Now I believe that ANYONE can learn to sing. At least well enough for it to sound pleasing to the ear. (I''m not talking about being 100% in tune all the time.)\nIt would be interesting to know if there has been a research in musicality and environment and how feasible such a study would be.', '27 May ''14, 23:41', 0),
