('100186519', '100118572', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'Hi Kids - this is Matt. We apologize for any errors that exist, and I apologize especially for any errors in my section. At Udacity, as with many other online education platforms, we struggle with how best to address mistakes. Please understand that there are a lot of resources that go into making these videos, so many resources that to simply re-do all mistakes everytime they are found is virtually impossible. So we have been trying many different methods, from making comments in the instructor''s notes to making PDFs with corrections, etc. There are also limitations in the technology of how/when to modify videos. Please know that we hear your concerns and take them seriously; we''re constantly working to make this a better experience.\nFrom a strictly pedagogical point of view, mistakes are not all bad either. Just as you find mistakes when your in a regular classroom with a live teacher, we make mistakes. And when it happens here, someone is able to post a comment, link, or idea that clarifies the mistake. Typically when it happens in a live classroom it is missed and will never be corrected ... at least here there is a chance that it will be caught and corrected. And that process of correcting is the BEST learning experience of all. Education research shows us that when you find an error, the effort it takes to discover, research, and rectify the error is a huge boon to your learning about that specific topic. Now I''m not suggesting that we should put more errors in a course, but errors are unavoidable and pedagogically it''s possible to learn much more from them in an online environment than in a live classroom setting. Just food for thought.', '29 May ''14, 12:34', 2),
('100186524', '100159982', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'You should watch this lesson from the Genetics course to learn more about what a gene being "on" or "off" really means:\nhttps://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-bio110/l-299989443/e-300022414/m-300022415\nAs for your question about tagging, I think you misunderstand the tagging event. If the DNA sequence is tagged, the sequence DOES NOT change, it just has a tag added to it. These tags do not silence individuals DNA letters, but silence the expression of a whole section of DNA ... this is what we would call silencing a gene or turning it "off". Watch that lesson 4 from the genetics class to really have it make sense.', '29 May ''14, 12:43', 1),
('100186525', '100186297', 'users/113259599/drcookie', 'This is a great (and pretty difficult) question to answer. The broad definition of epigenetics is any change in gene expression not due to alteration of the DNA sequence. The major source of epigenetic variation is your environment: what you breathe, what you eat, what you''re exposed to, how active you are, etc. Gene expression is changing all the time due to environmental factors. So yes, you can alter gene expression patterns and do so all the time. But the key is that you are limited genetically. The DNA sequence itself still dictates most of the changes because it was the environment has to work with.\nDoes that make sense?', '29 May ''14, 12:46', 0),
