('100187437', '100069749', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'People are still born with various genetic mutations like 6 fingers in each hand (which could be handy when typing :-P  ) but they are often operated purely because the assumed stigma a child would suffer in our society. What other evolvement (evolution by revolution) we dont allow? What about the boy in India who is claimed to have eyes like an animal and can see in the dark? I am not saying that I believe it but IF... My impression is that our societies are not usually very tolerant of people who are different, especially if they are "gifted" in a way we''re not used to.. \nFor example, when I was young I could "see" what I now guess was the electromagnetic field around living things likehumans and animals. In other words I was especially sensitive and my brain created a visual representation of those vawes or vibrations. I learned several years later that other people call them auras... Well, I was told to be quiet about it because it was  likely to be a sign of madness, just the same way my friend''s grandmother refused to impart her knowledge of medicinal herbs in fear people would accuse her of dabbling with witchcraft. Yet now herbal medicine is commonly accepted part of healthcare. \nSo evolved or throwbacks, they disturb us and we''d rather they are just like us.', '02 Jun ''14, 01:04', 0),
('100187439', '100068310', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'Stimulating environment for babies and children vs. derivation, which child till young adult would be more intelligent or would there be no difference? How well could a person from deprived background catch up as an adult? How much of intelligence is learning to problem solve because of previous experience and tools for thinking it has given? How different should  an experiment be to eliminate any likelihood of the test subject not being able to use his experience? Isn''t that also part of intelligence, to be able to use past experiences and knowledge in a new situation? If that is the case, and everyone''s life experiences are different even of the same event, how can we be sure what we test is pure herited iq gene? They say that smart people have smart kids but are they that much smarter really or is it because their parents peovide their kids naturally more stimulating environment? How can we be so sure what we are really testing? Is there really a single gene or few genes that makes someone clever regardless of an environment?', '02 Jun ''14, 01:26', 0),
