('100189300', '100168782', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I think a lot depends on your equipment, what frequencies they can produce. There are "ultrasonic" mosquito repellents for phones but some app makers state that not all phones can produce all of the awailable frequencies. Ouch, that was painful! I could hear the whole range, except not 8 Kh. I''m not really sure if that''s good or not for a 50 year old but I''ve always thought myself as having a good hearing.\nI put my "good hearing" down to the fact that I rarely listen to loud music and I avoid noisy places. Although  this pilot study* claims it isn''t hazardous to work in a nurzery, I still think it is the biggest threat to my hearing working in a nursery: lots of high db, high pitched children, especially when even higher pitch screaming during tantrum - anywhere else in same conditions you''d be warned to wear ear defenders! \n\nhttps://www.google.com.kh/url?sa=t&amp;source=web&amp;rct=j&amp;ei=ri-VU5LJGsj6PNLCgegD&amp;url=http://www.icben.org/2003/pdf/9_t1a.pdf&amp;cd=8&amp;ved=0CDoQFjAH&amp;usg=AFQjCNFLQvS6OxwDiDvvWcaXks2SU-2TfQ\n\nIf this study** shows the quality of children''s voice can be affected by noise then why not the carers hearing? \n** https://www.google.com.kh/url?sa=t&amp;source=web&amp;rct=j&amp;ei=ri-VU5LJGsj6PNLCgegD&amp;url=http://www.icben.org/2003/pdf/9_t1a.pdf&amp;cd=8&amp;ved=0CDoQFjAH&amp;usg=AFQjCNFLQvS6OxwDiDvvWcaXks2SU-2TfQ', '08 Jun ''14, 23:01', 0),
('100189301', '100113638', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I don''t know about olfactory nerves but nerves in general have a tendency to be able to renew themselves, depending on how extensive the damage is. If the hearing loss is caused by damage to ear drum then then that''s more complicated.', '08 Jun ''14, 23:08', 0),
('100189308', '100103115', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'Many animals use sounds for communication  or navigation that we can''t hear. A common example would be bats and whales, although bothalso have audible sounds in their range.  \nCorrect me if I''m wrong but I''m also thinking of certain musical instruments, such as a cello. When plucked or played with a bow it doesn''t create only one sound wave but a series of "complementary" sound waves which are in harmony, that we are not aware of. That is why many music lovers complained that MP3s sound "flat" compared to analog LPs. Low sounds that are on the edge or below hearing are used in music to create a sense of foreboding, sadness and fear. I guess they are also used in horror movies, although I don''t watch them so I can''t say for sure.', '08 Jun ''14, 23:39', 0),
('100189324', '100080779', 'users/301873158/hurr', 'That''s why there is a baseline.\nThere would be way too many variables otherwise.', '09 Jun ''14, 00:44', 0),
('100189343', '100102233', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'Well, let''s imagine I''m an extrovert. It is easy for me to approach and to be approacable to the opposite sex, so I have more potential partners to choose from. Therefore I am likely to be confident about being attractive to the opposite sex and to take my time choosing a mate, having also met more arseholes, before entering what could be single parenthood; and also when it suits me best.', '09 Jun ''14, 03:03', 0),
('100189490', '100101906', 'users/281676430/richa-17', 'Yes, they are both different. Physical dependency can be seen and felt physically, like having fever, having a broken arm, a bruise on the body. Psychological dependency can not be see, the body will not shown effects in order to make understand that it needs something. It is only a feeling that have, it is unseen but is felt.\nI too am not getting the answer to this question. Not being concerned with the answer I simply am able to distinguish between physical and psychological. I really do not understand what could the answer be.', '09 Jun ''14, 13:58', 1),
