('100195895', '100170225', 'users/309040415/sheetal-15', 'I think it is applied in organising the  people,their behaviour,which background they are coming from,what industry will suit them better etc.', '18 Jun ''14, 23:50', 0),
('100196066', '100103014', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'While wrter wants to give the impression she has done her research on pregnancy, her claim of nausea during pregnancy being a sign of a healthy one sounds dubious to say the least. I know plenty of women who have had  "perfect" pregnancies and women who have had nausea and not had a good pregnancy. In fact, the three times I suffered nausea were the ones I had nausea but during the three pregnancies that resulted to healthy and perfectly intelligent children I did not suffer from it... while I was in hospital after my second miscarriage I met a woman who was in the hospital for the whole duration of the pregnacy for the second time, because her nausea was so bad she couldn''t eat at all. When the older child came to visit she didn''t seem particularly bright, proably due to the complication during the pregnancy. I do not know if there are any studies about pregnancy related nausea but I guess there is no correlation. \nMy point is that although this article is interesting I would take it with a pinch of salt.', '19 Jun ''14, 10:33', 0),
('100196098', '100122793', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'What about aural memories? For example, if a child hears a noice that causes strong emotion by association of accompanying event, won''t she remember that sound? And how about smell? I think I''ve read long time ago from somewhere that babies can recognise their mother by smell. After all, they are usually very close to the mother''s body when feeding.', '19 Jun ''14, 11:47', 0),
('100196166', '100078992', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I think repeating an unethical study is a tricky one. I discussed about it with a (medical) scientist once who pointed out that repeat studies can give new light or even overthrow the results of the original study because of the original study''s biased setup. Hence in medical science many well-established experiments are still repeated. However, I believe that most European countries have stopped cutting up frogs and other animals in biology lessons. At least kids of my age didn''t cut up anything when I was in school 40 years ago and I have never heard anyone else do it either (in my country).', '19 Jun ''14, 14:46', 0),
('100196272', '100141518', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I was acutely aware of my rapid cognitive decline when I was stuck at home with kiemphasized textds. Looking after small kids doesn''t need much thinking and as it has been said, it''s a question of use it or lose it. Onthe other hand I have known quite a few men in their 70s who are working and can put many younger people into shame with their pin sharp minds.', '19 Jun ''14, 18:39', 0),
('100196289', '100074995', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'Our family dog was arthritic and old and by the day I took him to the vet he had been suffering from a big gash on his hip given by his arch enemy dog. A typical hunting dog, he really had only one true owner, my father. But my father had an accident a day after the fight so he was staying in hospital. My dad being absent, our dog became depressed and lost all will to live. He did not eat or even drink. Seeing that our beloved dog was so old and so sick, and in fact we were supposed to have put him down earlier because of my mother''s diagnosis of asthma, it was time to take him to the vet. Now, he had always loved visiting the vet but that day he knew he was not coming out again: despite his weakness, he put up such a strong fight that I had never experienced before, not even when he was in his prime. \nI think that many people who are OK with their own death are  really like our dog when it comes to crunch. I am sure I will, although in theory I''m OK about dying any time, as I think I have been here long enough to fulfil my purpose in life, never mind not wanting to live with dementia as I know what it does to you.', '19 Jun ''14, 19:57', 0),
('100196402', '100136923', 'users/307967718/glenn-pierre', 'Unless you are so sure of the method you used and have garnered enough qualifications to conclude causal relationships, you may not say "this caused this." If you are experimenting, however, it does not hurt to say instead "this appears to have caused" or "seems to cause this."', '20 Jun ''14, 02:48', 0),
('100196750', '100102470', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I understand that in order to remember something you must be fully aware of it. If that is the case, then not remembering is not being aware of it. So the level of remembering is related to level of consciousness.', '20 Jun ''14, 19:25', 0),
('100196816', '100096802', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'There''s another one if you can''t see the original. \nhttp://m.youtube.com/watch?v=6JONMYxaZ_s\nBe sure to watch also Simons'' talk in TEDx\nhttp://m.youtube.com/watch?v=9Il_D3Xt9W0\nCool, even though I did notice the blurring the first time - but that''s not the point.', '20 Jun ''14, 23:02', 0),
('100196823', '100139292', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I think I''m a prime example here. I didn''t notice any changes at all at first. I''m likethat in real life, I used to frustrate my mother, a typical woman ;-)  because I would not remember at all how someone looked like or what theywere wearing even after spending a whole hour with the person. That''s because that really isn''t important to me. However, I did gymnastics and dance so I I remembered how they moved. And conversation and personality...', '20 Jun ''14, 23:37', 0),
('100197494', '100092474', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'After waking up early every morning (study and work) it took me almost two weeks to get back to my normal rhythm of stayin up till 1 -3 in the morning. The only time I go to bed early is when I suffer from sleep deprivation, which is about twice a week because I still have to be at work by7 am. When I was young I thought midnight was late, but then I did lots of physical training as well as work/study.', '23 Jun ''14, 00:10', 0),
('100197497', '100080938', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I don''t think that Raghu''s 4th point is a very valid one, becacuse the body uses almost as much energy as asleep as it does when weare awake. However, there is a new study showing that brain is indeed necessary - we all know that lack of sleep can cause headache andslowed reactions, as if being drunk. It affects the heart and prolonged total lack of sleep apparently causes death faster then lack of food. And this is why: \nTaking Out the Trash\nThe purpose of sleep remains mysterious. Using state-of-the-art in vivo two-photon imaging to directly compare two arousal states in the same mouse, Xie et al. (p. 373; see the Perspective by Herculano-Houzel) found that metabolic waste products of neural activity were cleared out of the sleeping brain at a faster rate than during the awake state. This finding suggests a mechanistic explanation for how sleep serves a restorative function, in addition to its well-described effects on memory consolidation.\nAbstract\nThe conservation of sleep across all animal species suggests that sleep serves a vital function. We here report that sleep has a critical function in ensuring metabolic homeostasis. Using real-time assessments of tetramethylammonium diffusion and two-photon imaging in live mice, we show that natural sleep or anesthesia are associated with a 60% increase in the interstitial space, resulting in a striking increase in convective exchange of cerebrospinal fluid with interstitial fluid. In turn, convective fluxes of interstitial fluid increased the rate of -amyloid clearance during sleep. Thus, the restorative function of sleep may be a consequence of the enhanced removal of potentially neurotoxic waste products that accumulate in the awake central nervous system.\nReceived for publication 30 May 2013.\nAccepted for publication 28 August 2013.\nhttp://m.sciencemag.org/content/342/6156/373\nThe more tightly the brain is packed, or maybe it is the size compared to body mass, could explain why differentspecies need different amounts of sleep?', '23 Jun ''14, 00:32', 0),
('100197671', '100073352', 'users/273430756/tristan-64', 'My parents were around 23(Father) &amp; 22(Mother). I think I would wait a little longer, if I do end up marrying at all in the future (I''m only 19, and have never had many friends due to a social impairment).  Probably the shift in the marriage age is related to a change in cultural perception and financial stability among the people. As I stated before, I don''t know if I will ever marry because I have a history of royally putting my foot in my mouth with the best of intentions.', '23 Jun ''14, 11:21', 0),
