('100199846', '100198001', 'users/316072911/sarah-386', 'It''s really saying that most people are like each other. Height is quite a good example. The average woman is about 5 foot 6 inches. And most woman are around this height. As you get further away from the average, i.e. 4''6" or 6''6", you''ll find less and less woman. Does that help a bit?', '27 Jun ''14, 19:56', 1),
('100199960', '100190069', 'users/137470381/prudhvi-1', 'No, this isn''t viewed on a basis of the effect. Because, it is a correlation study. Moreover, if you ever get confused. Picture a graph. Put money on x-axis and number of crimes on y-axis. You would get a graph line with a positive gradient/slope.', '28 Jun ''14, 04:45', 1),
('100199961', '100067439', 'users/137470381/prudhvi-1', 'Yes, I wish I could learn more about the how they programmed the site and how they maintain it. If they allowed, I would hope on the next plane from India to USA.  I just love learning so many new things. Thanks,Udacity.#Udacity #Learning', '28 Jun ''14, 04:51', 0),
('100199971', '100112767', 'users/137470381/prudhvi-1', 'Well that''s one puzzle. But I think I might have the answer, it''s called mutation. When normally a person produces a reproductive cell like a sperm or ovum. They have a normal cell. Which divides into 2 using the normal mitosis. This gives us 2 identical cells. But then these 2 cells further divide using meiosis. This gives us a total of 4 cells and each with 23 chromosomes. A normal cell would have 23 pairs of chromosome. Also during this process a small part of the gene is mutated on purpose. How this happens is one part of the allele is taken and replaced with another. If the allele are identical, nothing happens. But if they are different, then you get a whole new allele. This is how evolution still continues. Because with no environment changes, there would already be the fittest organism a millienia  ago.', '28 Jun ''14, 05:20', 0),
('100199975', '100187952', 'users/137470381/prudhvi-1', 'Methyl group is anything that contains methyl or CH3. And what methyl does is that it attaches itself between bonds in the DNA and can shut off or silence the gene. So even the mothers were identical genetically. One mother was able to shut off genes allowing her offsprings to look different even with the same genes.', '28 Jun ''14, 05:35', 0),
('100199978', '100186299', 'users/137470381/prudhvi-1', 'See you can control your whole body if you think about it. But you will need to lots of practice to do some amazing things. But the basic point is you don''t have to constantly think about how much you have to breath or at what rate should your heart have to beat. Therefore they are autonomic. Basically its something that happens without you thinking about it. Even if you can control it if you want. Like you can control your hand, but it won''t move without your brain thinking about it unless it doing a reflex action. If it does move a lot without no reason and without you thinking about. I bet you should get yourself checked. But did you there have been cases where the left brain and the right brain are disconnected.  the left brain think in logic and right is for artistic purposes. Also left brain controls the right part and the right brain controls the left part. A simple test would to identify anything normal like an apple with your right eye closed. If you can''t, you have got the condition.', '28 Jun ''14, 05:49', 0),
('100200243', '100102679', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'When I was a child I shared the bedroom that opened to the kitchen, with two of my brothers. He woke me up once when I was sleepwalking as a child. I had no idea of where I was at first or how I got there but I was ashamed to say it because my brother was angry with me. So, standing next to a bucket of drinking water (we only had well water those days) I pretended to be thirsty and took a sip with the scoop, but my brother didn''t believe it.... \nI don''t think I was sleepwalking because I had a night terror, the only thing that scared me was my brother that night. However, I was entering into puberty and I wonder if that had anything to do with it? Otherwise I do remember waking up from night terrors, soaking with sweat at times, but always in bed and usually remembering the dream at least vaguely. I still have them sometimes but I cannot connect their occurrence to higher levels of stress than normal...', '28 Jun ''14, 22:20', 0),
('100200254', '100077421', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I have pretty irregular sleep pattern, especially when I''m not working but I don''t feel any difference as long as I have had enough sleep, especially REM sleep. other''s are sensitive to daylight and find it very difficult to sleep during the day. \nWhat I would like to know is why do I get headache if I sleep much more than 9 or 10 hours?', '28 Jun ''14, 22:50', 0),
('100200269', '100080876', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'When I was a teenager I read from somewhere that a native tribe of some country would comfort their kids who woke up from a nightmare but told them go back to sleep and face the monster, as an example, which was chasing him. I decided to try that and it was actually dead easy, so easy in fact that I could choose the topic and loose outcome of my dreams before I went to bed and the next morning I would wake up having dreamed what I "ordered". It was cool for a while but i got fed up with the predictability of it  so I stopped doing that. Now I hardly ever have lucid dreams.', '29 Jun ''14, 00:09', 1),
('100200275', '100089472', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'i suffered from depression during my second pregnancy and the psychiatrist prescribed me antidepressants that didn''t work any better than L-tryptophan (a natural protein found e.g. in milk). I told the psychiatrist that as I was pregnant and aware of many side effects of such mind altering drugs as antidepressants, but I was willing to go  to therapy. Instead of supporting my desicion the psychiatrist dismissed me as someone who is not willing to coorperate. I actually felt sorry for him as when he said that, he was practically in tears and that moment I felt emotionally stronger than him. \nI have tried antidepressants 2-3 times and every time only felt increasingly worse and tired as if I suffered from constant sleep deprevation - and the worse I felt the less ble I was to fight against the depression... I believe drugs can help some people to cope initially, but they don''t take away the REASON why the person fell ill in the first place.\nHaving said that, I once saw a TV program about people who are born depressed, i.e. their brain chemistry is never right and even as children they never felt happy, say when receiving a big birthday present. For those people that suffer from that rare condition "happy pills" might have desirable effects that outweigh the negatives.', '29 Jun ''14, 00:48', 0),
('100200397', '100068872', 'users/137470381/prudhvi-1', 'Technically speaking voltage is the force that drives a charge around a circuit. So if there is  enough voltage, there has to be a charge. Also in superconductors, current can pass around a circuit with no voltage because the resistance is 0. V = IR', '29 Jun ''14, 08:26', 0),
('100200407', '100188369', 'users/137470381/prudhvi-1', 'Not really. All this would actually mean that the motor control of the left hemisphere is better than the motor control of right hemisphere. Your statement would only be true if the brain hemisphere didn''t work together. Or a guy wasn''t creative enough. But yes, in artists and mathematicians there would be probably be a difference. But not for everyone though', '29 Jun ''14, 08:57', 0),
('100200417', '100188369', 'users/100033350/sylvi-s', 'There definitely is not a set and stone difference. People don''t suck at art just because they are right-handed. There is some correlation, but can easily be canceled out by the fact that the two parts of the brain often work together\n~Sylvi\ngood luck :)', '29 Jun ''14, 09:17', 0),
('100201898', '100097489', 'users/100079430/chris-18', 'It''s neither good nor bad. It''s an inanimate substance. This is the problem with all drug debate is that  substances, chemicals, get tagged as good or bad. They are neither. Not prescription meds, not illegal drugs, not every-day drugs. It''s your behaviour and attitude towards them that matter.\nThere is no morality in chemicals.\nYou may think that I''ve misunderstood your question, but I know what you meant (to which there is no real answer) but I''m getting to the crux of human''s drug problems. The almost puritanical labeling of inanimate substances as being good or bad. Even though you didn''t mean it that way, our weird attitudes as a population are betrayed by the words you chose.\nI''ll have a coffee in the morning, I enjoy it. I may have one mid morning too. I''ll try to avoid it completely in the afternoon but occasionally it''s a social thing. Caffeine has a half life of 5 hours (last time I was told...) so it''s not advisable to drinking the afternoon if you (well, me anyway) want to sleep. It seems like an innocuous  drug by virtue of being unregulated and available on every corner but it has it''s effects and I suspect many are unaware of how much they are under it''s spell and won''t unless they clean up for a while. I enjoy it but 5 cups as a norm is too much.\n(yes I finally have the time to finish this course)', '02 Jul ''14, 10:17', 1),
('100202087', '100083590', 'users/287741424/annika-14', '"There seems to be an intuitive connection between humans and plants that enables some sensitive individuals, under special circumstances, to tune in to the healing potential residing in plants."\nI don''t believe you have to be that intuitive either. I could tell the properties of two plants simply by placing my hand a few inches above a living plant. I could feel strong warmth from one and a cool feel from another. I was trained as a nurse but didn''t know anything about plants... One turned out to be mustard and the other, which lating name I don''t remember or know the English name, is commonly used in drinks when it is hot... You can feel the cooling effect of live mints quite easily, too. \nIt makes sense: we are animals after all and have the same instincts, albeit mostly dormant because we don''t have to use them any more for survival. But take away the sivilization and they''ll soon awaken... While we all have the "gift" that we can practise and develop, some are of course more gifted than others, just like some are more musical or better at sports.', '02 Jul ''14, 18:52', 0),
('100202100', '100080977', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'Queen Victoria became probably addicted to food after sometime after her husband died. She was hugely fat but when advised to eat only when she was hungry she said " But I''m always hungry!" Food addiction is more common these days but why?', '02 Jul ''14, 19:51', 0),
('100202421', '100087501', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'I agree with both gingerbread and glob. But I know that some foreign students wish to get the certificate in the end and correct answers that are ot accepted because of the wording could make the final score less than 80%  - which isn''t really fair. For some getting the certificate of attendance is a way of showing a prospective employer the willingness of self-improvement, to learn new things, rather than resting on your laurels after finishing school. \nEither the there should be a greater recognition of correct answers, by now the ones causing problems should be identifiable, so start changing those; or using multiple questions throughout the course. If the course designers want to make some questions more difficult, maybe make the wrong questions (in multiple choice) less obvious.', '03 Jul ''14, 12:10', 0),
('100202427', '100168087', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'Yes. Caffeine is a stimulant (review previous videos) so anything containing caffeine is a drug, whether is is in energy drink guruana chewing gum coffee, tea or chocolate. The caffeine levels vary in tea and coffee depending on variety how much was used per cup etc. Sometimes the tea packaging indicates the level of caffeine by numbers or words like strong and mild, but if not, you can be pretty confident that something called breakfast tea has higher levels of caffeine.', '03 Jul ''14, 12:43', 0),
('100202465', '100092912', 'users/287741424/annika-14', 'My understanding is that it means any chemical or substance that affects the physiology, the function of the body of a human or animal. When you buy a drug you often see a separate mention of its active inredients: a drug contains often may others such as fillers or buffers which do not have medical value. E.g. a tablet''s coating and colour are not pharmacologically active but the aspirin in the tablet is.', '03 Jul ''14, 14:48', 0),
('100202590', '100202479', 'users/320775757/eduardo-2', 'Te recomiendo investigar sobre la esquizofrenia mas que de la paranoia debido a que solo la mencionas como un sntoma al referirte a la alucinacin que tuviste, En muchas ocasiones las drogas al ser estimulantes de nuestro sistema nervioso (evidentemente nuestro cerebro) desencadenan la enfermedad de la esquizofrenia no necesariamente por la droga en si sino por factores genticos en los que la enfermedad es muy latente. Son nuevas investigaciones asi que investiga esto y sobre todo busca ayuda si hay antecedentes de enfermedades mentales en su familia. Saludos. Sorry my english is very bad', '03 Jul ''14, 19:46', 0),
