('100220274', '100113275', 'users/351413550/christie-19', 'This resounds strongly with me... I had very little social interaction outside my family (except some schooling) until my early 20s.  \nAround this point, I left home, &amp; went through a period of complete confusion as to my own personality, because of how differently people outside my family perceived me - and therefore how I was treated - and ultimately the large impact this has had on my overall personality and sense of identity.  Within my family growing up, I was always described (and felt I was) a down-to-earth, intelligent, strong, stable person, a mediator, neutral, conscientious, a strong sense of morality.  Outside of the family, I was perceived and treated very differently, which knocked me to my core, fell off my foundations, I completely lost myself and my identity, &amp; still struggle with this to this day.  This was most especially so during a period of estrangement from my family for a couple of years.  \nSo I completely agree, family helps to develop your core values and personality, and keeps you strong if nothing else then by the sheer knowledge and knowing that they are there and care for you unconditionally. But I would say the external sources have the largest overall contribution to your sense of identity, further development of personality, and your overall experiences and opportunities in life.  \nSomeone who isn''t easily socially accepted may have less positive experiences - even possibly more negative experiences - &amp; therefore less opportunities, which may lead to an overall negative, depressed or anxious outlook on life, which can then become a cycle and integrated into the personality, even affecting emotional stability.  \nSomeone accepted easily may be more likely to have more positive experiences and more opportunities as result, and parts of their personality would shape very differently as a result, as opposed to someone who has more negative experiences.\nJust out loud thoughts, I guess these could change with further learning, experiences and studies.  Or perhaps not everything above could be considered to do with personality.', '27 Aug ''14, 03:53', 0),
