('100246832', '100173656', 'users/115489111/paul-352', 'After reading Sebastian Thrun''s Q&amp;A about MOOC, I think his points actually lend credence to the notion that you shouldn''t need to pay for a certificate.\nA little background on me: I recently leveraged online education (from multiple sites) and various skills/experience to get a job in the computer science field when that wasn''t my original background.\nThere seems to be a bit of a paradox in what Thrun is saying and what Udacity has done. Thrun responded to this petition by downplaying the certificate and indicating the education is the important part (which is generally correct). However, if the certificate is not important, why do we need to pay to get it?\nSecondly, in the Q&amp;A, Thrun says that only 10% of people who take the free classes without personal help actually finish the class. Maybe it''s me, but doesn''t that seem worthy of earning a certificate if you''re part of that 10%? Says a lot about your motivation, your drive and your abilities, IMO.\nWhile the education is clearly the more important part, the certificate has value itself as well. I have noticed before there are sites that pull your certificates from various online education and creates a portfolio, even with the ability to add it to LinkedIn. Which in turn easily summarizes for potential employers the direction you are going with online education, and what courses you''ve completed. Maybe most potential employers don''t actually care that much, but based on my experience they do care at least a little bit, as I''ve used that to show my initiative as well as my passion for computer science in interviews.\nI guess I don''t see why Udacity can''t simply have separate "free" and "verified" certificates that have different qualifications, but ultimately both verify that the course was completed.', '11 Dec ''14, 12:25', 2),
