('100254954', '100121006', 'users/100114930/c-laktionova', 'Actually, it may be a little bit more complicated than failures in early stages of development.\nAs cited in Wikipedia on Piaget''s theory of cognitive development -  "However, research has shown that not all persons in all cultures reach formal operations, and most people do not use formal operations in all aspects of their lives" \nFor many people there is no special need to use meta-cognition/ formal logic/ hypothesis testing in everyday lifes,  that''s why they simply don''t develop such cognitive abilities throughout adolescence. The fault may be on their culture, upbringing, lack of motivation and so on. Also there can be some deficit in frontal lobes/ mental illness / meningitis...and other various reasons taking place\nHope that helped :)', '12 Jan, 08:11', 0),
('100256397', '100117281', 'users/276650891/vincentm', 'His theories are just that: theories, which caught up with people''s imagination. Nothing more. Many of them are questioned today: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychoanalysis#Criticism', '17 Jan, 04:56', 0),
('100257174', '100147091', 'users/358843470/wildcyan', '@DrCookie makes a valid point, but it isn''t really the answer, because Australopithecus might still be around if history had gone differently.  Like how dogs evolved from wolves, but wolves are still around.  They just occupy a very different niche.  As the niche for wolves dwindles, it''s possible they will go extinct like Australopithecus, but for now at least, they exist concurrently.\nAnd while modern wolves are very slightly different than the ancient ones from which dogs evolved, if you take that a step further, every wolf or dog is slightly different than every other wolf or dog, just like humans (or chimps, or Australopithecus, or anything).  Because evolution isn''t a discrete occurance, it''s a trend of averages.\nAs Kabuto the Python rapped in "Yo, Science":\n\n...people think that evolution happens on a scale,\nand that a human''s more evolved and therefore better than a whale.\nNot so; there is no endpoint to all creation,\njust selection for an ever-changing niche - it''s adaptation.\nSecond, that selection happens over greater populations. \nIt''s an average, not a direct sign of deformation...', '19 Jan, 22:47', 0),
