('100267670', '100173656', 'users/357058315/s-668457', 'First I''d like to start off by saying:\n"Thanks Udacity and all those involved ( partners, employees, others )" for all you''ve done and are doing** to help those, who appreciate your services, to enrich and improve not only their lives, but the lives of those around them.\nI have some really " BIG " dreams and Udacity is helping me achieve those dreams and turn them into a reality.\nFor that I am eternally grateful.\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\nThanks Udacity &amp; Dave Evans for sharing the information and knowledge presented in the course "Introduction to Computer Science" !!!\nDave is a phenomenal instructor.  I like his teaching and presentation style.  Very easy to grasp, comprehend and process new information.\nThanks for providing exceptional tools and resources to learn, practice and develop new skills and talents.\nI was looking for a place to start learning Python and this is the perfect course.\nWhat makes this course so unique is there''s an incredible project ( webcrawler &amp; search engine ) that will  be created once course is completed.\n\n\nOnline experience and Python IDE are some of best, if not the best, bar-none.\n\n\nWebsite is very reliable\na. So far, I''ve never been disconnected nor did session timeout or log me out unexpectedly.\nb. Whatever I type in the individual quiz screens is persistent across logins.  Awesome !!!\n\n\nEverything one needs is readily available.\n\n\nUdacity has eliminated all issues. Just bring a hunger and desire to learn.\na. can start course immediately\nb. no distractions due to setting up or prep\nc. everything student needs has been provided\nd. no need to purchase software\ne. no need to purchase equipment ( pc, laptop, tablet )\nf. no time wasted with interoperability / incompatibility issues ( installing &amp; configuring software )\n\n\nThanks again for the magnanimous gesture, selfless act of benevolence and generosity in providing an avenue via which millions like myself have access to resources that can enrich our lives and the lives of others around us.\nSupport has been good too.\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\nThanks Cameron Pittman and Jessica Uelmen for the absolutely Awesome and Incredible training and learning experience received in "Intro to HTML and CSS ".   Not only did I learn more than I ever imagined or anticipated, but the course had hilarious moments.\nThe final project was extremely challenging, sometimes frustrating, but ultimately very satisfying when I was able to create a mockup that matched 99.83% when superimposed on top of the original design.\nI paid for the certificate, not because I wanted to prove to someone I took the course; I paid for the certificate to demonstrate and show my appreciation and how grateful I was for the structured training, resources provided, knowledge and experienced gain, time and energy saved.\nPrior to taking this course, I knew practically " nothing " about HTML and CSS.\nAfter completing this course I walked away knowing infinitely more about Web Page Design.\nIt feels good to learn something new.  It feels good to feel good.  It feels good to feel competent and confident.  I look forward to continuing the journey; learning, comprehending and retaining so much more while utilizing and implementing what I''ve been taught along the way.\nFollowing are just a " few " of the items I learned while taking this course:\n\n\nSignificance and importance of Separation: HTML ( Layout ), CSS ( Style ), JavaScript ( behavior )\n\n\nBox Layout, Grid Design, CSS Frameworks, BootStrap\n\n\nResponsive  and Adaptive Web Pages using media queries and layout.\na. Responsive design: designing website or page to fit device screen ( portrait or landscape ).\nb. Adaptive design: designing layout so it''s easier for mobile device users who use their fingers, not a mouse.\n\n\nMockups\na. How to look at a Web Page, Picture or PDF, visualize it''s layout, create a mockup\nb. How to use browser web developer tools to inspect and change various items on a page\n\n\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\nThanks Sarah Sproehnle , Ian Wrigley, Gundega Dekena and Cloudera for creating, presenting and offering "Intro to Hadoop and MapReduce".\nThanks to Doug Cutting creator of Hadoop and Chief Architect at Cloudera for sharing about Hadoop''s history and origins.\nI never imagined that within one week I''d developed a very solid foundation and learn the basics about Hadoop and MapReduce.\nUsing the Virtual Machine and data sets they provided, I was able to write Mapper and Reducer code.\nI learned:\n\nWhat is Big Data\nChallenges of Big Data\nThree V''s of Big Data : ( Volume, Variety, Velocity )\nHadoop''s  Origin and History\nHadoop''s Core\nHadoop''s Ecosystem\nHadoop Commands\nDataNodes, NameNodes, Job Trackers, Task Trackers, Input Split, Intermediate Data, Shuffle &amp; Sort, ...\nRole and function of Mappers, Reducers\nHadoop Streaming : Creating code with languages other than Java. ( input &amp; output via stdin &amp; stdout )\nHow to input and export data to and from Hadoop ( HDFS )\nHow to create Mapper and Reducer Code and verify code before submitting jobs.\nHow to submit Hadoop jobs and check results.\n.\n.\nAnd a whole lot more.\n\nI plan to pay for certificate once I complete course in next week or so.  Again, I choose to pay, not because I want to prove to someone I completed the course, but I want to show my appreciation and gratitude for all Udacity has done in making these " invaluable &amp; precious " resources available.  For connecting me to resources ( people, tools, services, ideas, thoughts, information, instruction, training, knowledge, etc... ) that I would possibly never be exposed to and especially not for free.\nI will use this knowledge, wisdom and skills acquired to learn even more about Hadoop and MapReduce.\nPerhaps some day in the not too distant future, I''ll know enough to setup, install and configure a Hadoop cluster, populate it with "meaningful" data and create code to process and analyze that data, then present it on a webpage in a dashboard so it can be easily understood and appreciated by it''s intended audience.\nThe courses I''m taking here at Udacity are enabling me to perform the above in a rather short time for an exceptional and incomprehensible low price ( $0 for the Knowledge, Training &amp; Experience and ~$200 USD for the privilege to get a certificate ).  Not to mention, most of the prerequisite courses needed by those not familiar with the technology or course material to complete the final projects required for the certifications is free.\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\nI''m grateful for all the services Udacity provides.\nWe''re very fortunate Udacity offers the training for free.\nI think it''s completely fair and reasonable for Udacity to charge for Certificates.\nI will pay for all certificates I plan to pursue as it''s a small token of appreciation for all the services Udacity provides and gives away for free.\nI''ve not seen any other training, online, free or otherwise that compares...\nUdacity saves me money and time by not having to:\na. Pay ridiculous tuition fees\nb. Paying for parking on campus or street\nc. Commuting to and from campus ( gas, time and/or fare )\nd. Searching for place to park once reach campus\ne. Spend time walking to / from parking to class\nf. Waiting for class to get started, because teacher or students are late\ng. Classes typically last hour or two depending on day or night classes.\nh. Classes may or may not be available every day, some are twice or three times a week. \ni. Udacity is available 24x7.  I can study at my own pace, 5-6, 8-10 or 12-16 hours per day.\nj. The " Final  Projects " and exercises Udacity provides are superb.  There is no comparison.\nk. At best other educational institutions are nervous and will try to replicate &amp; mimic Udacity''s format.\nWhen taking Intro to Computer Science with Python:\na. I like the IDE\nb. I didn''t have to search for an appropriate editor\nc. I didn''t have to spend cycles on how to use editor\nd. I was able to jump in and get started immediately\ne. I didn''t have to purchase any hardware nor software\nf. I didn''t have to spend time distracted with compatibility issues\ng. I didn''t have to spend time with software installations nor configuration\nInfrastructure:\na. Servers are always up\nb. Web and courses are always available 24x7\nc. I''ve never had any issues accessing the web or courses\nd. I''ve never lost any work, all course work is saved and persistent\ne. Even if you navigate away from page and come back, your work is still there\nQuality:\na. The audio is very clear\nb. The video is very clear, bright, crisp\nc. The courses, instruction, resources &amp; projects are best bar-none...\nSimply put, it takes money and Udacity has to pay someone:\na. to create web content\nb. to house their infrastructure\nc. support and maintain infrastructure\nd. for building to house their employees and Silicon Valley isn''t cheap...\nAll I can say is I''m truly grateful for the privilege and honor to learn from some of the best.\nWhile I know everyone''s financial situation is a very sensitive, personal and private matter and I can empathize with any and all who struggle day to day for the bare minimum to eke out a living...   That doesn''t change the fact that:  Udacity is doing a Superb and Phenomenal job.\nBe grateful the courses and all the material is free.\nIf one can''t afford the Certificate, then again, be grateful for all the knowledge gained.\nUse that knowledge, make some money, then come back and pay for that certificate.\nHold one''s head up no matter what situation or station you find yourself in.\nNever give up, Never give in, Never quit...\nKnowledge is power.  Knowledge creates opportunities, enables options and provides choices.\nAnd Udacity is offering that " knowledge ",  wisdom and experience for " free ".\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~', '27 Feb, 21:52', 1),
