('100284360', '100259878', 'users/357809110/william-735134', 'It refers to placing employees in jobs where they are likely to finish necessary tasks sufficiently.\nOddly enough, IQ tests do this very well when combined with other traits:\nhttp://mavweb.mnsu.edu/howard/Schmidt%20and%20Hunter%201998%20Validity%20and%20Utility%20Psychological%20Bulletin.pdf\nhttp://www.unc.edu/~nielsen/soci708/cdocs/Schmidt_Hunter_2004.pdf\nI think this metric could be useful to assess how difficult course material is and perhaps make it more accessible to students by reducing the loading on fluid intelligence, which as I understand it is harder to boost.\nThat''s a possibility I''m fascinated by. Industrial and differential psychology may be useful beyond just the job market.', '13 Mar, 06:19', 0),
('100284471', '100211920', 'users/357809110/william-735134', 'This is hard to answer because two of the biggest problems in a statistics-based question exist on this one:\n.1. What exactly constitutes good driving?\nNo crashes? Ability to get to places faster? Following the laws? Parallel parking ability? Skill with stick and automatic? Crazy stunts?\n.2. How do we collect the data once we know what metric(s) to use - in other words, what do we control for?\nDoes one gender or the other spend more time driving or traveling longer distances or making a variety of turns/techniques? What about following a map of how to get somewhere?\nObjective data can be collect on this question but the result will no doubt be contingent on what you choose to measure and how you decide what data to use for input.', '13 Mar, 06:39', 0),
('100284510', '100206535', 'users/357809110/william-735134', 'I don''t know specifics off the bat, but I think fluid (processing ability) and crystallized (embedded memory) intelligence patterns differ between young and old people. \nYounger people tend to have more fluid ability (probably since they need to learn more "new" things) while older individuals lose some fluid ability but gain some crystallized intelligence (the amount of vocabulary they can recall is higher for example).\nBut I don''t know what the research is on this phenomenon is. I just remember reading it in a book I skimmed (Teen 2.0) years ago where this topic was mentioned.', '13 Mar, 06:45', 0),
